15 
 

Classification: Internal Use 

This proposed mechanism may also explain the limited methane formation in butanes 

hydrocracking. If methane is formed during cracking of olefins on BAS, such as Steps c and f in 

Figure 12, it would result in stoichiometric formation of alkynes (C3H6 → CH4 + C2H2 or C4H8 → 

CH4 + C3H4), which is not very feasible mechanistically. Additionally, in the current catalyst with 

low Si/Al ratio (Si/Al = 25), the likelihood of forming a Lewis-acid extra-framework Al in close 

proximity to a Brønsted-acid Al is high. So is the chance of forming a pair of Brønsted-acidic Al in 

vicinity. When a Lewis acid Al is in close proximity with a Brønsted acid Al, according to 

Schallmoser et al. [16], it can increase the transient-state entropy of the protolytic cracking and 

hence facilitates the rate of protolytic cracking to form C2, i.e., Steps (c) and (f) in Figure 12. 

Similarly, Song et al. demonstrated, both experimentally and computationally, that the Brønsted-

acid Al pairs increased the intrinsic entropies of the protonation transition state, and consequently 

enhanced cracking rate of alkanes [18]. Song et al. also showed that the Brønsted-acid Al pairs 

favor central cracking over terminal cracking, which may also help explain the limited methane 

formation during the reaction from C3 to C2. Nonetheless, the scheme depicted in Figure 12 is 

merely a hypothetical route that shows reasonable mechanistic feasibility and is consistency with 

the observed reaction stoichiometry. 

Similar to ethane, selectivity to aromatics also increases with residence time (Figure 3B), 

and appears to be favored by higher temperatures, too. Figure 13 shows a possible route to 

convert a C3 and a C4 to toluene. The formation of a longer carbon chain is similar to the initial 

stage of the bimolecular cracking mechanism in Figure 10. The cyclization and aromatization of 

the C6+ carbon chain can occur on the BAS in H-ZSM-5 [19] or on the Pt sites that are in the 

micropores of the zeolite [20]. Due to the reaction equilibrium, the final step of aromatization 

becomes more prominent when H2 partial pressure is relatively low, which applies to the butanes 

hydrocracking reaction at high residence time (Figure 3B) when H2 was largely consumed. 

 
Figure 13. A possible scheme of converting a C3 and a C4 to toluene. 

The monocyclic aromatics can undergo further aromatization to form poly-aromatics (see 

the formation of naphthalene, methylnaphthalenes and dimethylnaphthalenes in Table 1), which 

eventually results in coke. 

5 Conclusions and future works 
With the inclusion of aromatics formation, a more detailed picture of the reactions in 

butanes hydrocracking process is drawn in Figure 14. Butanes are first dehydrogenated on Pt 

sites to form butenes. Butenes are transported to acid sites to dimerize before cracking into C3 

and C5. The C3 species remains as the major product until it gradually converts to almost 

+

- H+ + H+

- 3 H2

- H+ + H+- H+ + H+



 

16 
 

Classification: Internal Use 

exclusively C2 at high residence times, also via bimolecular routes. Finally, all the olefinic species 

return to the Pt sites to form corresponding paraffins through hydrogenation. The mechanistic 

details of the step from C3 to C2 remains unverified, which can be via methoxy group as a reaction 

intermediate. Besides C2, aromatics also emerge as C3 is being converted, which eventually result 

in coke formation. 

 
Figure 14. Scheme of the cracking reaction of butanes to ethane over metal-acid bi-functional 
catalyst with the presence of hydrogen. 

The coke, mostly hard coke, made up to 28% of the fresh catalyst weight, and can be 

effectively removed using diluted O2 at 500 °C. The regenerated catalysts after various 

regeneration cycles all performed similarly (both activity and selectivity) to the fresh one in 

butanes hydrogenation reaction. Although loss of Pt metal dispersion was observed by hydrogen 

chemisorption after reaction and regeneration, it did not impact the apparent catalyst activity in 

butane hydrocracking reaction, most likely due to the high Pt loading. The total catalyst lifetime of 

a fresh load plus four regenerations is estimated to be 19 months, which could be acceptable in 

an industrial-scale reactor to minimize catalyst recharges.  

Future works will include the development of a deactivation model, which will be integrated 

with the kinetics model. Additional characterization work can be conducted to quantitatively 

correlate the catalyst deactivation with loss of pore volume and the loss of acid sites. Moreover, 

solid-state NMR, in situ characterization and more detailed micro-kinetic analysis are needed to 

unveil the reaction intermediate during the conversion of C3 to C2, which will hopefully help 

elucidate the reaction mechanism. Sulfur poisoning and the regeneration of the sulfur-poisoned 

catalyst will also be examined. Lastly yet importantly, efforts need to be made to optimize the Pt

SABIC Technical Center – Houston 
Technical Report STCH-2020-001 

 January 29th, 2020 

Title: Deactivation modeling of an Ir-Pt catalyst in butane hydrogenolysis reaction 

Project: Butane to Ethane (Accolade # 116955) 

Authors†: Heng Shou, Ashwin Patel, Cong Nguyen, and Byeongjin Baek 

EXECUTIVE SUMMARY 

The deactivation of the butane hydrogenolysis catalyst was modeled using a Langmuir-

Hinshelwood expression. It is among the first efforts to model reaction-induced catalyst deactivation via 

reasonably hypothesized surface reactions. More importantly, it is the first discovery on a counter-intuitive 

phenomenon, in which precious metal catalyst can be more stable in hydrogen-lean conditions than 

hydrogen-rich ones in hydrocarbon processing. Despite the counter-intuition, such a phenomenon is 

consistent with the projection by the deactivation model. 

When comparing to the previously used benchmark testing conditions, the hydrogen-lean 

conditions can significantly extend the catalyst lifetime at a higher rate of reaction. The learnings from 

the model can substantially shorten reactor downtime, shrink the reactor size to achieve the same 

production rate, and reduce the cost of separating excessive H2.

1 
 

Classification: Internal Use 

1 Introduction 
The definition of a catalyst is a substance that accelerates the rate of a chemical reaction and 

cyclically turns over to its original state as the reaction completes. The implied situation is that the catalyst 

remains unchanged during this process. However, in all catalytic reactions, catalyst deactivation is as 

certain as death and taxes. Figure 1 shows the deactivation time for some processes. The time scale of 

deactivation has profound consequences for process design. The environmental catalysts for 

automobiles are required to last as long as the vehicle’s lifetime mileage. The processes with long catalyst 

lifetime (months to years) suit well in fixed-bed reactors. Those with shorter lifetime require slurry or 

moving-bed reactors. A process like FCC, where the zeolite catalyst can merely last for seconds, needs 

a catalyst regenerator that is larger than the reactor. 

 
Figure 1. The time scale of deactivation of various catalytic processes.1 FCC: fluid catalytic cracking, 
HDS: hydrodesulfurization, EO: ethylene oxide, MA: Maleic anhydride, SCR: selective catalytic reduction, 
TWC: three-way converter. 

Figure 2 shows a schematic representation of the deactivation phenomena inside a catalyst 

particle. Attrition is directly related to the structural integrity of the catalyst substrates, which is under 

rigorous tests when the catalyst particles are in motion; attrition hence especially applies to moving-bed, 

fluid-bed, and slurry-bed reactors. Sintering refers to the process of catalyst particles agglomerating, 

which requires high enough temperature to mobilize them. Deactivation also occurs when the catalyst 

reacts with a reactant to form a volatile species in a gas-phase reaction or a soluble species in a liquid-

phase reaction (leaching), such as anchored Suzuki catalysts for cross coupling2. Poisoning is often 

caused by impurities in the feed; example poisons are arsenic and sulfur on a CoMo hydrotreating 

catalyst supported on alumina or faujasite, where arsenic poisons both the metal and the substrate and 

sulfur poisoning mostly applies to the metals. Fouling is caused by reactions promoted by the catalyst 

itself; in this process, strongly adsorbed species are formed, which render their adsorption sites inactive. 

The cause of catalyst deactivation is highly specific to the application; we will consider here the 

deactivation phenomena during hydrogenolysis of alkanes. It is generally regarded as mono-functional 

chemistry occurring on metals. Iglesia and co-workers detailed the micro-kinetics of the process2-7. As is 

shown in Figure 3, as the linear alkane undergoes multiple dehydrogenation steps, two adjacent carbon 



 

2 
 

Classification: Internal Use 

atoms are co-adsorbed on the metal surface; this establishes the conditions for C–C bond cleavage. 

Finally, the highly dehydrogenated fragments on the metal surface react with H2 to desorb and form 

shorter alkanes. 

 
Figure 2. Major types of deactivation in heterogeneous catalysis1 

 
Figure 3. Schematic pathway of surface reactions of butane hydrogenolysis to ethane. R1 of R2 refers to 
either an alkyl group or a hydrogen.  

Given that the butane hydrogenolysis reaction on the Ir-Pt catalyst was conducted at moderate 

conditions (520-600 K, 4.5-11.4 bar) in a reducing environment, the metal clusters on the substrate 

should have limited mobility and volatility. The reaction was carried in fixed-bed reactors, so the structural 

integrity of the catalyst substrate is of minor concern. The feed has negligible impurities, especially the 

non-hydrocarbon ones, so the catalyst ought to have limited exposure to poisons. Therefore, it appears 

likely that catalyst deactivation in butane hydrogenolysis is due to fouling, caused by surface deposits 

formed during the reaction. It is consistent with the reaction mechanism of alkane hydrogenolysis 

presented in Figure 3, during which highly dehydrogenated surface intermediates are formed. 

This study is based on the premise that the deactivation in butane hydrogenolysis is mainly from 

fouling. Preliminary observations suggested that the deactivation could be described by Langmuir-

Hinshelwood (LH) type kinetics, and a deactivation model was developed accordingly using an approach 

similar to primary reaction kinetics based on reasonably hypothesized and simplified surface reactions. 

The presented work is among the first efforts to model catalyst deactivation using an LH rate expression. 

The findings herein suggest that elevating hydrogen partial pressure or lowering hydrocarbon 

partial pressure is not always the most effective means of mitigating catalyst deactivation. In fact, catalyst 

lifetime could be significantly extended when hydrogen was relatively lean, even slightly below reaction 

stoichiometry, which is unprecedented in literature reports. Besides, the Furthermore, the hydrogen-lean 

conditions coincide with a faster reaction rate, which implies that the same production capacity may be 

achieved with a smaller reactor size.

2 Methods 

2.1 Catalyst  

According to a previous report8, the following recipe was transferred to Zeolyst for scaling up. An 

aqueous solution was made by dissolving 0.042 g of H2IrCl6·6H2O (Aldrich) in 3.0 mL D.I. water. Similarly, 

an aqueous solution was made by dissolving 0.042 g of H2PtCl6·6H2O (Aldrich) in 1.0 mL of D.I. water. 

The two solutions were mixed while being stirred. The mixed solution containing both metals was added 

dropwise to the 5.0 g of the extrudates (Zeolyst CBV 28014 CY 1.5, containing 80 wt.% H-ZSM-5 with 

SiO2/Al2O3 = 280 and 20 wt.% alumina as the binder) while the extrudates were being stirred. It is noted 

that the volume of solution was in slight excess of the pore volume of the extrudates. The flask containing 

the impregnated extrudates were connected to a rotary evaporator instrument, which then rotated at a 

slow speed at room temperature for three hours for gentle vaporization. Consequently, the extrudates 

were dried in an oven at 363 K for three hours. Lastly, the extrudates were removed in a ceramic dish 

and calcined in the air as the following sequence: RT to 373 K at 2 K min−1; held at 373 K for eight hours; 

373 K to 453 K at 2 K min−1; held at 543 K for three hours. 

The recipe was scaled-up by Zeolyst in a 500-g batch (ID: ZD15014A), which has a composition 

of 0.3 wt.% Ir–0.3 wt.% Pt supported on γ-Al2O3–H-ZSM-5 (1.6 mm extrudates, 80 wt.% H-ZSM-5 with 

SiO2/Al2O3 = 280, and 20 wt.% γ-Al2O3 as the binder). 

2.2 Reaction 

2.2.1 Unit 136, 0.25-inch OD reactor 

The 1.6 mm catalyst extrudates were sized into 0.4-0.8 mm particles. The particles (0.05–1 g) 

were diluted with 0.4-0.8 mm silicon carbide before being packed in the center of the stainless-steel 

tubular reactors (¼-in OD, 0.039-in wall thickness). The mixture of catalyst and diluent formed a 4-in bed. 

The bed was held in place by glass wool, a spacer, and a mesh gasket. Thermocouples were positioned 

on the outer wall of the reactor to control the wall temperatures. The packed reactor was placed in a 

three-zone furnace, and an internal thermocouple is placed at the center of the catalyst bed to measure 

the reaction temperature, as shown in Figure 4A. The temperature difference between the wall and the 

bed was always below 0.5 °C. 

Hydrogen gas (Airgas, 99.999% purity) and ethane (Praxair, 99.99% purity) were controlled and 

delivered to the reactor system by Bronkhorst® EL-FLOW® Prestige gas mass flow controllers. The n-

butane (Praxair, 99.99% purity), i-butane (Praxair, 99.99% purity), mixed butanes (Airgas, 30-70 wt.% n-

butane of 99.99% purity, balanced by i-butane of 99.99% purity), or propane (Praxair, 99.99% purity) 

feed was controlled and delivered in liquid form by Bronkhorst® mini CORI-FLOW™ liquid mass flow 

controllers, from cylinders pressurized with helium. 

The reaction temperature was between 520 and 600 K, with an H2/HC molar ratio of 0.15 – 10 

and a WHSV of 3.5 – 200 gHC gcat
−1 h−1 (or simply h−1), under a pressure of 4 – 12 bar. Some example 

experimental conditions are summarized in the Appendix section. 

An online Agilent 7890B gas chromatograph analyzed the product gas stream. The pressure in 

the sample loops was equilibrated to ambient pressure before every GC injection. Sampled components 

were separated in an Agilent J&W GS-GasPro column (0.32 mm × 30 m) followed by an FID using He 

(Airgas, 99.999% purity) as the carrier gas. The peak areas identified by GC were used to determine the 

conversion of hydrocarbons, as well as selectivity of products. The volume expansion factor 𝜈 was 

calculated as:

bond, 1 for each ring) and volumetric concentration of product 𝑖 in the product stream, respectively. Since 

the products in butane hydrogenolysis reaction are nearly exclusively alkanes, 𝜈 ≈ 1 applies to almost all 

experiments in this study.

2.2.2 Unit 143, 0.25-inch OD reactors 

The 1.6 mm catalyst extrudates were sized into 0.4-0.8 mm particles. The particles (0.05–0.75 g) 

were diluted with 0.4-0.8 mm silicon carbide before being packed in the center of the stainless-steel 

tubular reactors (¼-in OD, 0.039-in wall thickness). The mixture of catalyst and diluent formed a 3-in bed. 

The bed was held in place by glass wool, a spacer, and a mesh gasket. The packed reactor was covered 

by aluminum sleeves (to achieve a more nearly isothermal profile across the reactor) and placed in a 

two-zone furnace, as shown in Figure 4B. Two thermocouples were positioned on the thermal sleeve 

reactor to control the sleeve temperature, and an internal thermocouple is placed at the center of the 

catalyst bed to measure the reaction temperature. The temperature difference between the sleeve and 

the bed was always below 0.5 °C. 

The H2 (Praxair, 99.999% purity) was controlled and delivered to the reactor system by Brooks 

5850E gas mass flow controllers controlled by secondary electronics. Normal butane (Praxair, 99.99% 

purity), isobutane (Praxair, 99.99% purity), mixed butanes (Airgas, 30-70 wt.% n-butane, 99.99% purity, 

balanced by i-butane, 99.99% purity), or propane (Praxair, 99.99% purity) was controlled and delivered 

in liquid form by Bronkhorst® mini CORI-FLOW™ liquid mass flow controllers, from cylinders pressurized 

with helium. 

An online Agilent 7890B gas chromatograph analyzed the product gas stream. The pressure in 

the sample loops was equilibrated to ambient pressure before every GC injection. One sample gas was 

analyzed with an HP-PLOT Q column (0.53 mm × 30 m × 40 μm) followed by an FID using He (Airgas, 

99.999% purity) as the carrier gas. In parallel, another sample gas was analyzed with a Hayesep Q pre-

column, followed by a Molsieve 5A column and a TCD using Ar (Airgas, 99.999% purity) as the carrier 

gas. The TCD was exclusively for H2 analysis. 

The GC data processing was the same as those in Section 2.2.1 except that 𝑐𝐻2,𝑖𝑛 was directly 

measured by TCD. 



 

6 
 

Classification: Internal Use 

3 Results and Discussions 
The preliminary studies on temperature and partial pressure dependences revealed that 

temperature did not have a significant impact on the deactivation rate at the experimental condition 

(Figure 5A). This temperature insensitivity will be addressed in a later section. The trends with partial 

pressures of hydrogen and hydrocarbons provided more insights on the development of the rate 

expression. As is shown in Figure 5B-C, the effects of partial pressure on the deactivation rate were not 

monotonic: For both hydrogen and hydrocarbon partial pressures, the deactivation rate reached a 

maximum when evaluated across a wide range. A conventional view on catalyst deactivation is that the 

deactivation can be mitigated by increasing hydrogen partial pressure or lowering hydrocarbon partial 

pressure. However, the results in Figure 5 show that the effects of hydrogen and hydrocarbons can be 

complicated. Specifically, the catalyst deactivation rates moderated when the hydrogen partial pressure 

was low enough (dotted line in Figure 5B), or the hydrocarbon partial pressure was high enough (dashed 

line in Figure 5C). The model development in the following section will be dedicated to illustrate this 

phenomenon. 

 
Figure 5. Preliminary evaluation of the dependencies of (A) temperature, (B) hydrogen partial pressure, 

and (C) butane partial pressure. The conversion (𝜒) refers to the hydrogen conversion. 

3.1 Derivation of the model 

Despite their counter-intuitive nature, it is possible to interpret the results in Figure 5 by a 

Langmuir-Hinshelwood expression. To reach a maximum in deactivation rate while varying the 

hydrocarbon partial pressure (𝑝𝑓), the exponent on 𝑝𝑓 needs to be greater in the denominator than that 

in the numerator. One possible way to achieve this is to have an open site involved in the rate-determining 

step (RDS). The derivation of the rate expression is presented below. 

Figure 6 illustrates three-step surface reactions that lead to catalyst deactivation. A hydrocarbon 

molecule, under quasi-equilibrium with constant 𝐾𝑚 , reacts with surface open sites, and loses 𝛼 

molecules of H2 to form the most abundant surface intermediate (MASI). The MASI does not have to 

participate in the rate-determining step of the deactivation reaction directly. Accordingly, a second quasi-

equilibrium step (with constant 𝐾𝑑) is introduced to allow the precursor in the deactivation RDS to be 

different from the MASI. The formed deactivation precursor (DP) interacts with an open site in the 

deactivation reaction. Note that these surface reactions are lumps of multiple elementary steps and are 

not meant to address the mechanism at a micro-kinetics level.

Figure 6. Schematic pathway of surface reactions leading to deactivation, which is composed of a quasi-
equilibrium step (with equilibrium constant Km) of surface adsorption to from MASI, a quasi-equilibrium 
step (with equilibrium constant Kd) to from deactivation precursor, and a rate-determining step (with rate 
constant kd) to form deactivated sites. 

In the process of deriving the rate expression, for simplicity, the feed is denoted as “f,” while the 

open site, adsorbed hydrogen, MASI, and DP are denoted in the following equations as “0”, “h,” “m,” and 

“d,” respectively.

partial pressure of H2.

𝜃𝑚 + 𝜃ℎ + 𝜃0 = 𝛩 (7) 

where 𝛩 is the number of active sites, which changes with time on stream. The value of 𝛩 is normalized 

by the initial number of active sites on a fresh catalyst.

of dissociative adsorption of H2 shown in Figure 7, as:

(18) 

If multiple hydrocarbon compounds contribute to the deactivation process, the total number of 

active sites now include the corresponding MASIs from various hydrocarbons: 

∑𝜃𝑚,𝑖 + 𝜃ℎ + 𝜃0 = 𝛩 (19) 

Each hydrocarbon 𝑖 contributes to the overall rate of site loss in a parallel fashion, giving rise to

summing the portions from different compounds, the total rate of deactivation is:

Since 𝛩 is not directly measurable, it must be related to H2 conversion, which is a descriptor of 

catalyst activity. The conversion of H2 is preferred over that of a hydrocarbon because a product of 

hydrogenolysis may undergo further hydrogenolysis to form even shorter alkanes. 

In an LH kinetic expression, the exponent of 𝛩 in the denominator should be equivalent to the 

number of sites in the reaction RDS. It is noteworthy that all the RDS of the reaction rates developed 

previously19 are LH-type and involve two sites. Therefore, the reaction rate of H2 can be expressed as: 

−

Figure 8. (A) Representative data processing of eq 29 to exclude the induction period and renormalization 
via back-extrapolation based upon the data after the induction period; (B) The corresponding process 

shown in normalized hydrogen conversion, 
𝜒

𝜒𝑡0
. 

As is shown in Figure 8B, an activity decay curve (indicated by circles) often has two portions. 

The first part is a relatively fast deactivation occurring towards the beginning of the experiment, and the 

second one corresponds to a relatively slow deactivation. The initial fast deactivation is likely associated 

with the induction period of the catalyst, during which the catalyst may still be stabilizing structurally and 

highly uncoordinated sites are passivated. The post-induction deactivation at relatively slow rates is 

associated with the majority of the active sites, and better reflects the deactivation behavior of the catalyst 

during prolonged operation. Therefore, the final step in data processing is to remove the impact of the 

induction period on catalyst deactivation as the following: 

 Extrapolating (dashed line in Figure 8A) the post-induction linear part of the curve (as the 

curve formed by the circles in Figure 8A becomes linear) to time zero; 

 Using the corresponding value of the intercept to normalize the initial performance back to 

unity (dotted line in Figure 8A), which matches eq (29). 

The corresponding data processing in the space of 
𝜒

𝜒𝑡0
~𝑡 is shown in Figure 8B, where the 

normalization of the post-induction decay results in the intercept of the extrapolation line (dotted) at 
𝜒

𝜒𝑡0
=

1. The derived value from the data processing is 𝑘𝐷 as shown in eq (22). It should be noticed that values 

of  𝛽 and  vary while fitting the model. The data processing adjust the change of 𝛽 and  accordingly to 

ensure that the back extrapolation of the post-induction decay curve (dotted line in Figure 8) starts at 1 

at time zero.

3.2 Fitting the model 

Upon the completion of the model development and data processing, the following section will be 

dedicated to the model fitting, which minimizes the difference between the experimental data and the 

modeled analog. With a given pair of measured and simulated deactivation rate constants (𝑘𝐷,𝑀 and 𝑘𝐷,𝑆, 

respectively), which correspond to Point P in the parity plot (Figure 9A), the residual (e) is defined by: 

𝑒 =
𝑑1
𝑑2

=
𝑘𝐷,𝑆 − 𝑘𝐷,𝑀
𝑘𝐷,𝑆 + 𝑘𝐷,𝑀

 (30) 

The fitting parameters were optimized by minimizing the sum of residual squares (∑𝑒𝑖
2 ) using the 

Generalized Reduced Gradient non-linear regression algorithm in the Excel Solver package. Since 100 

sets of initial guesses were applied during the optimization, the result can be treated as a global one or 

a semi-global one. 

A few restrictions were applied when performing the model fitting. It is reasonable to assume that 

all the linear alkanes form similar MASIs. In the present work, the α values of linear alkanes (see eq (22)) 

were fixed to two, which is projected by a DFT simulation in Ref 8. It means that the MASI associated 

with a linear alkane has four less hydrogen atoms than the corresponding alkane feed. It is worth noting 

that MASI in hydrogenolysis has also been reported as −3H from linear alkanes11-12, but the −4H premise 

yielded a better fitting result than the −3H one in this study. On the other hand, the 𝛼 value for i-butane 

varied during the fitting considering its distinct reactivity13 and likely different hydrogenolysis mechanism7 

compared to the linear alkanes. Applying the Born–Haber cycle, the formation of the MASI (see Figure 

6) on the catalyst surface can be divided into quasi-equilibrated dehydrogenation and chemisorption 

steps. The reaction endotherm to dehydrogenate the same number of hydrogen atoms and the 

corresponding chemisorption exotherm can be very similar for short alkanes10. Therefore, 𝑄, which is a 

combination of dehydrogenation endotherm and adsorption exotherm, was restricted to be the same 

during the fit. Furthermore, 𝛼𝑖 + 𝛿𝑖 ≥ 0.5 was also enforced with the assumption that it needs to dissociate 

as least one H atom to form a surface-bonded DP (see Figure 6). The applied restrictions can also be 

found in the footnotes of Table 1.

A total of 23 fitting parameters were determined with 112 experiments in differential reactors. 

Upon the completion of the model fitting, an analysis of the residuals revealed that the numbers 

possessed good normality (Figure 9B), indicating good quality of fit. The parity plots containing all the 

runs with various feeds (Figure 10A) and separated ones with individual feeds (Figure 10B-F) show that 

the data points are evenly distributed along the parity line, regardless of the feed. It demonstrated that 

the fitting was not biased toward specific feeds. Figure 11 compares the modeled and measured 

deactivation profiles in the space of normalized conversion activity (hydrogen conversion). The modeled 

curves very much overlap with the corresponding measured ones.

a) Restriction of 𝑄 values during the fit: ethane = propane = n-butane 

b) The value of 𝛼 for linear alkanes were fixed to two, which is projected by DFT simulation in Ref 8.   

c) Restriction of 𝛿 values during the fit: 𝛼 + 𝛿 ≥ 0.5 
d) Shared value for all species 

Table 1 lists the fitting parameters derived herein. The value of 𝑬𝒂 for n-butane is close to zero, 

which is consistent with the temperature insensitivity displayed in Figure 5. The activation energy (𝑬𝒂) of 

normal-alkane-induced deactivation follows ethane > propane > n-butane, and the pre-exponential factor 

(𝐴) follows ethane < propane < n-butane. It suggests that the rate of deactivation caused by linear alkanes 

increases with the carbon chain length. An akin trend can be found in the literature on the reaction rate 

of alkane hydrogenolysis6, which showed that the bond activation becomes easier as the carbon chain 

lengthens. Similarly, the 𝐵 value follows ethane < propane < n-butane, which is consistent with the higher 

tendency of chemisorption as the carbon chain grows6. It should also be noted that the 𝐸𝑎 value of i-

butane is quite negative, drastically different from those of linear alkanes. It implies that i-butane may 

undergo different deactivation pathways from those of linear alkanes shown in Figure 6. However, 

differentiating i-butane would result in tremendous numerical difficulty expressing the rate, from which 

the number of active site Θ can be separated and integrated. Addressing such difference would likely 

require more detailed studies on i-butane separately and is out of the scope of this study. 

The fitting results also show that i-butane loses two hydrogen atoms (α ≈ 1) to form its MASI, and 

its DP contains more hydrogen atoms than the MASIs (𝛿 < 0). As is shown by Iglesia and co-authors7, 

the C-C bond breaking of i-butane requires it to lose six hydrogen atoms before breaking a C–C bond. 

Therefore, the DP of i-butane, which could be only one H atom short of i-butane (2(α+δ) in Table 1), may 

not undergo C–C bond cleavage in the deactivation RDS. Similarly, propane needs to lose four hydrogen 

atoms before its C–C bond cleavage in hydrogenolysis6, which is one more hydrogen than its modeled 

DP. The propane deactivation RDS hence may not need to activate the C–C, either. The fitting results 



 

15 
 

Classification: Internal Use 

suggest, however, the DPs for ethane and n-butane are also their MASIs (δ ≈ 0), so the C–C bond 

activation cannot be ruled out from their deactivation routes. 

The  value is at 1.40, which is considerably larger than one. It means that the rate-determining 

step of deactivation may involve multiple surface hydrocarbon species. Consequently, coke formation 

cannot be excluded as a slow secondary reaction based on the current analysis. 

Table 1 suggests that i-butane, along with ethane, is a feed causing least deactivation. However, 

i-butane played an important role on the deactivation rate as a consequence of competitive adsorption. 

Figure 12 compares the deactivation rates at 570 K in the H2/C4H10-pressure space using feeds with 

different composition. The pure n-butane feed (Figure 12A) always has the highest deactivation rate in 

the entire plotted range, and the deactivation lessened as the share of i-butane in the butane mixture 

increased.

70% n-butane + 30% i-butane, and (C) 50% n-butane + 50% i-butane feeds.

H2/C4H10 = 2, and (C) H2/C4H10 = 5. The C4H10 feed is composed of 70% n-butane and 30% i-butane.

Figure 13 maps the deactivation rate constant in the temperature-pressure space at various 

H2/C4H10 (70% n-butane and 30% i-butane) ratios. At H2/C4H10 = 5, the deactivation rate increases with 

temperature in the entire pressure range in the map (Figure 13C). As the H2/C4H10 decreases, a zone in 

which the deactivation rate decreases with temperature emerges at the low-pressure end (Figure 13B). 

When H2/C4H10 = 1, the deactivation rate slightly decreases with temperature in the entire mapped range 

of pressures (Figure 13A). In industrial reactors, as the catalyst deactivates, it is a common practice to 

increase the reactor temperature incrementally to maintain the catalyst activity. As is shown in Figure 

13A, when operating at a sufficiently low H2/C4H10, it is possible to decelerate the deactivation as the 

reactor undergoes incremental temperature changes, which extends the catalyst lifetime. 

Figure 14 maps the deactivation rate constant in the H2/C4H10-pressure space at various 

temperatures. At any given temperature and pressure within the presented range in Figure 13, the 

deactivation rate reaches a maximum while increasing the H2/C4H10 from 1 to 10. At 550 K (Figure 14A), 

the deactivation rates are relatively slow, when H2/C4H10 and pressure are either both low or both high. 

As temperature increases, the deactivation rate remains slow in the low-H2/C4H10-low-pressure (LHLP) 

zone. In contrast, outside of the LHLP zone, the deactivation rate increases substantially with 

temperature. Therefore, the LHLP zone is the most desired window of operation to minimize catalyst 

deactivation. 

 
Figure 14. 2D map (H2/C4H10 and pressure) of deactivation rate constants at (A) 550 K, (B) 570 K, and 
(C) 590 K for a C4H10 feed composed of 70% n-butane and 30% i-butane. 

Figure 15 compares the deactivation rate and the reaction rate (from n-butane to ethane, see Ref 

8) at 570 K in the same ranges of H2/C4H10 and pressure. The most favorable range of operation is where 

slow deactivation rates overlap with fast reaction rates. According to Figure 15, such overlap can be 

accomplished in the range where H2/C4H10 and pressure are both low (bottom left corner). 

The model provides a powerful tool to predict the catalyst deactivation behavior. However, since 

the model was developed based on data generated from isothermal reactors, it did not consider the effect 

of temperature rise. Given the fact that the deactivation in butane hydrogenolysis is largely adsorption 

driven, a rising temperature could start to make the final step in Figure 6 reversible and hence desorb 

the deactivating species. Consequently, in a pilot or industrial reactor in which temperature increments 

are applied to maintain the catalyst activity, the deactivation may become partially reversible as the 

reactor temperature rises. Nonetheless, the model is sufficient to project the trend of deactivation as the 

4 6 8 10 12 14 16 4 6 8 10 12 14 16 4 6 8 10 12 14 16

−1)

/C

8

10
(A) T = 550 K (B) T = 570 K (C) T = 590 K

Classification: Internal Use 

reaction conditions change, such as the maps in Figures 13-15. Moreover, the model provides insights 

on the formula of MASI, the similarity/difference between MASI and DP, and the possibility of both 

monomolecular and bi-molecular deactivation routes. One may refer to the explanatory paragraphs of 

Table 1 for more details. 

 
Figure 15. 2D map of (A) deactivation rate constant (𝑘𝐷) and (B) reaction rate constant (𝑘𝑅) at 570 K in 
H2/C4H10-pressure space. The C4H10 feed was composed of 70% n-butane and 30% i-butane.  

 
Figure 16. The evolution of deactivation profiles at the H2/C4H10 goes below one at (A) 548 K and (B) 583 
K. The reactor pressure was kept at 7.9 bar. The feed was composed of 70% n-butane and 30% i-butane. 

The model was not developed to cover all possible conditions. Without limits on conditions, the 

model would project that the deactivation rate will continue to decrease monotonically as H2/C4H10 

decreases. However, severe deactivation would certainly occur when there is no H2 in the reaction gas. 

The model is most accurate when H2/C4H10 ≥ 1. Although reducing H2/C4H10 to below one can 

continuously decelerate deactivation to some extent, further decreasing H2/C4H10 would reverse the trend. 

As is shown in Figure 16A, at 548 K and 7.9 bar, the deactivation rate kept decreasing as H2/C4H10

Classification: Internal Use 

dropped from 1.01 to 0.58. Once the H2/C4H10 went below 0.58, the deactivation started to accelerate. It 

is noteworthy that the deactivation was still at a moderate rate when the H2/C4H10 was as low as 0.15. 

Similarly, at 583 K (Figure 16B), the deactivation rate kept dropping until H2/C4H10 reached 0.65. The 

deactivation started to rise with further decreasing H2/C4H10. The deactivation rate remained moderate at 

H2/C4H10 = 0.51, but accelerated substantially as H2/C4H10 went down to 0.38 and further to 0.15. 

As stated above, the most desirable condition to mitigate catalyst deactivation is hydrogen-lean 

(below the reaction stoichiometry). The single-bed butane conversion is hence limited. Additional reactors 

need to be sequenced to raise the overall butane conversion. It should also be noted that the ethane 

selectivity, as projected by the LH kinetic model8, decays as H2/C4H10 decreases (Figure 17). However, 

the loss of ethane selectivity can be effectively recovered by inter-stage H2 addition in a multiple-reactor 

setup. Such a setup is separately addressed in an invention disclosure14. 

 
Figure 17. The evolution of ethane selectivity as the H2/C4H10 goes below one at (A) 548 K and (B) 583 
K. The reactor pressure was kept at 7.9 bar. The feed was composed of 70% n-butane and 30% i-butane. 

4 Conclusions and future works 
The deactivation of an Ir-Pt catalyst in butane hydrogenolysis follows a unique trend, where it can 

be more stable in hydrogen-lean conditions than hydrogen-rich ones. Such a counter-intuitive 

phenomenon can be modeled and explained by a Langmuir-Hinshelwood deactivation model based on 

reasonably hypothesized surface reactions. The model aligns well with the experimental results in 

differential reactors. 

Compared to the previously used benchmark testing conditions, hydrogen-lean conditions can 

significantly extend the catalyst lifetime at a higher reaction rate. The learnings from this model can 

substantially shorten reactor downtime, shrink the reactor size to achieve the same production rate, and 

reduce the cost of separating H2. 

The model will be used to align with the existing pilot data and provide guidelines for future piloting 

trials.

0605.1 MF will investigate the possibilities for short sea shipments to Spain.
06.07: 40 ft container to Valencia (1700 €) and then from Valencia to
Tarragona (400 €)  which leads to transport costs of 95 €/t . If we add ware
house and custom costs we end up at 104 €/t which is significantly higher than
road transport. For Intermodal transport the costs are 59 €/t to Tarragona. If we
then add the road transport costs to the customer we also do not expect a saving compared to the actual transport costs. This of course is a specific situation for
Spain. Actions to evaluate EEC on CIP basis are still running.
0609: Romania: truck = € 110 / T, rail = € 110, short sea = € 90-100 CIP
We will start a trial with one container to Politub.
0611: 
    -Two deliveries intermodal were done. No feedback received yet.
    -A short sea shipment customer has to be selected
    -In order to save on transport costs, which can be of benefit to both Sabic and 

     Logstor, MF will investigate the possibilities for optimization.


MF
0612: Answer from S & C is not satisfactory. A meeting will be planned with
    Bus. Man. and DCM and S & C.
0607.2 R&D together with Production will evaluate the modified recipe for 4062R

production with lower H2/C2-ratio in the 1st reactor and come with a proposal for

further improvement if possible. S4 was at same level than previous material.

0609: M. Mattern made a proposal to H. Martens to set the split to 45 and adjust 

the H2/C2 in the 2nd reactor in order to reach a density which is one point lower.

Memo will follow. Production takes place 16 october.

0610: Quality is okay, Rn = 1-2-1, S4 normal. Mechanical test on pipes will be

done next week (week 44).

0611: S4 = 2,3 bar, cone test = 0 mm. First results look promising. Before next

campaign, mid Jan. 2007, we want to have a proposal for the recipe.

0612: Proposal was send by M. Mattern and H. Martens. Memo ??? Tests still

pending.

05 July 2007



Visit report of Plastic Pressure Pipes 2007, 25-27 June 2007   
From:

Hans Martens R&D MD

	Copy:

Keywords: AMI conference Plastic Pressure Pipe
1. Conference Statistics

Program: 

[image: image1.emf]C:\Documents and 

Settings\568517\Desktop\Programme AMI 2007 Pressure Pipes.pdf


Participants: 

· speakers: 20
· exhibition: 11
· delegates: 130
The following parties were attending the conference:

· raw material producers 
· additive producers

· Pipe producers

· Test institutes

· Utility companies

· Engineering/Machinery companies

Highlights

· The conference covered very well all different aspects of pipe business value chain
· Market overview has been given by
·  AMI (it was a well known overview of the market studies with some interesting statements regarding challenges and future) 

· Russian Polyplastic Group

· Our main competitors gave lectures promoting their new grades directly or indirectly:

· Super slow crack grades (Ineos and Basell)

· Low sagging grades (Borealis and Total)

· Different aspects of high-tech manufacturing and fusion techniques have been covered, all claiming more efficient processes.
· Cabot presented his specially developed carbon black for pipe applications.
Presentations in more detail:
Only lectures relevant to SABIC are discussed in more detail (PE, PP related). 

All lectures will be available in Livelink (after 15th July 2007)

http://livelink.intranet.europe.sabic.com/livelinkdav/nodes/26040822/
1. Markets and applications 

1. 1 Pressure Pipes- the prospects and challenges – Mr. E. Green (AMI Consulting UK) 


[image: image2.emf]E:\Session 1 - 

Markets and Applications\1.  AMI Consulting.pdf


· Markets: Shares, growths and challenges for Water and Gas PE pipes (and PVC) are given.

· For water the biggest challenges are: 

· Take a part of ductile iron market not by competing in pressure attainability but:
· Price competitiveness above 300mm

· Long, successful track record

· No corrosion and improved ductility
· Suitable for all ground conditions

· To develop higher value niches

· To deliver value and/or performance  - not “mee too”

· For gas the following challenges are identified:

· The biggest growth in Eastern Europe

· Cope with “boom and bust” nature of long term contracts

·  To assess the impact of changing energy policies

· Strategy Options for Pipe business future have been given from the following points of view:

· Geographic (Pipe growth moves East)

· Products (1. Multi-layer for brown field land (= polluted land), abrasion resistant pipes attack installed costs. 2. Light weight- can wall thickness reduction push PE’s cost competitiveness above 300 mm?)
· Manufacturing
1.2 – Development of PE pipe market in RUB (Russia, Ukraine, Belarus) -  Mr. M. Gorilovskiy, Polyplastic Group 


[image: image3.emf]E:\Session 1 - 

Markets and Applications\2.  Polyplastic Group.pdf


· A full picture o market has been given including a theoretical demand in coming 10 years

· Total market size is estimated to be ~270kt in 2007 with real growth rate of 17%

· Theoretical demand (based on kilometres of pipelines needed in coming 10 years is 1113kt (50% water, 20% sewage, 25% gas and 5% district heating) 
· Issues that play role in Russia are: 
· non-colored materials, second hand black pipes
· Constraints: Money, Lack of Control for many pipe producers, Tax (10%) is barrier for further growth  
· In private discussion with Mr. Gorilovskiy the following points were mentioned:

· They were rather enthusiastic about SABIC expansion. They are particularly interested to work with SABIC KSA (some delegation was already visiting them). They think that KSA materials will be more competitive with the local PE 100 producer in 2009.

· He told us about the local expansion plans with PE 100 ( this has been discussed via email and will be verified with P. v.d Ham) 
· They would be however interested to test our A6060R specially with respect to sagging. They do such tests on 1.2-2m diameter and would be happy with 50t of the material. They are curious to see the performance differences between SABIC and BASELL and specially Borealis LS. They see very small differences between CRP and Boreaslis LS grade, though LS seems to be a bit better (with respect to sagging).
· We also had an interesting discussion about C4 vs. C6 grades and production of big diameter pipes. It seems that C6 grades are difficult to process into nice and smooth pipes (huge amount of volatiles). This is why Mr. Gorilovskiy prefers C4 grades.

· Basell technology is preferred technology for him. He does not have fully confidence in Total and Ineos materials.
1.3 – Whole life costing model for large diameter water mains- Mr. C. Salles, Applic. Marketing Manager, Borealis France 

[image: image4.emf]E:\Session 1 - 

Markets and Applications\5.  Borealis.pdf


· Cost model for pipes made of different materials (Steel, PE, PVC, Asbest and cast iron) based pipes  on UK data has been made (no other more reliable data available) based on the Whole Life Cost model (WLC)
· This presentation is a nice basis to promote HDPE by installers and constructers indicating that the cheapest pipe is not always the lowest in whole life cost.

1.4 - Tangential extruded PE pipes: new standards, properties and applications, Mr. S. Füllgrabe, General Manager, Frank & Krah Wickelrohr Gemany 
· Historical development tangential extrusion technology

· Comparison Tangential vs. Axial extruded pipes: Discontinuous vs. Continuous, different cooling procedure, different calibration (inside vs. outside), different shrinkage behaviour etc.   

· Alternative test for long term internal pressure test (Hessel). Relation internal pressure vs. 2NCT behaviour (NCT specimen out of pipe)

· Examples of re-enforced pipes (PE/short&long fibres PE) produced with tangential extrusion incl. mechanical properties (tested by Becetel)
· Applications of tangentially extruded pipes (PE100, SDR 17/26   

2. Joining technology 

The following lectures have been given:

· Cost savings solutions for pressure pipes- Mr.M.Gulminelli  SICA S.p.a. Italy 
· New socketing technology (thermoenlarging): Explanation of technology, benefits and solving current problems using this technology)

· Reduction of  wall thickness achievable with PE100  (18% reduction of material)
· PVC pipes can be connected by many methods including fusion welding – Mr. J. Fumire, Solvin, Brussels (B) 
· Benefits/contra’s: Butt welding /Laser welding vs. fitting with electro-welding 

· Fusing at higher interfacial pressures – T.Striplin, McElroy Manufacturing, Tulsa USA
· Welding of PE piping: high fusion vs low fusion interfacial pressure w.r.t. beneficial aspect i.e. increased productivity without sacrificing quality      
· Influence of slow crack growth (SCG) resistance of PE pipe materials on the long term performance of welds made by electro socket fusion- Mr. M. Haager AGRU Kunststoftechnik, Austria 
· Presentation in cooperation with PCCL Leoben (R.Langer, G.Pinter), an institute to which SABIC EU (R&D, TM) does have already contacts with 
· Conclusion: high SCG performance has a positive effect on service life of elctro-socketing, thus material is decisive for long term performance!  

3. Materials and manufacturing 
3.1 A vision comes true: 50 years of pipes made from HDPE – Mr. U.Schulte Basell Germany 
· Historical view of PE pipes through Basell-eye 

· Standardization and quality assurance

· Last developments of HDPE for pipe: Hostalen CRP100 resist CR black (FNCT >> 10,000 hrs)

· Promotion of PE100+ Association (data linked to 23°C life)       

3.2 New PE100 with step-out stress cracking resistance for highly demanding piping technologies – Mr. P. Godon, Ineos Brussels

[image: image5.emf]E:\Session 3 - 

Materials and Manufacturing\2.  Ineos Polyolefins.pdf


· Eltex Superstress PE100 (TUB124N6000 & TUB125N6000): fine tuning of molecular design (focus on molecular branches, similar MWD as before), C6-comonomer (MFI 190/5 = 0.30)
· Superstress material promoted only in blue (water) and orange (gas). Why not in black? 
· Explanation of Notch pipe Test (NPT) and Point Load Test (according to Hessel with point load as simulation of smooth rock) using Arkopoal N100 and NM5 (Hessel detergent: composition?) NM=Netz Mittel

· Claim of of good correlation PLT vs. FNCT (both detergents) of typical Ineos PE100 vs. Superstress grade (claim of Superstress: FNCT > 8760 hrs (> 1 year) (Arkopal N100, 4Mpa, 80°C), PVT guarantee (PLT, NM5, 4MPa, 80°C > 8760 hrs) 
3.3 Technical performance requirements of black pressure pipes- the critical role of specialty P-type carbon blacks in compounds and masterbatches- Mr. S. Dougherty Cabot UK 
· Effect of key performance criteria: Particle Size, Microscopic dispersion, Moisture absorption, Chemical Impurities, Dispersability on performance of various CB types (Elftex P100, 254 vs. other CB)
· Improved performance of P-type w.r.t. extraction in water (low toluene, sulphur)
· Comment of Schulte (Basell): Basell grades only on Fully Formulated Approach  Route (No Pepper and Salt) (natural + MB= No Option)   
3.4 - New accelerated SCG resistance test methodology for high performance PE materials – Mr. K.Oliphant , Jana laboratories Canada 
· Objective of new SCG method: saving time + characterization of injection molding parameters for development and QC of injection molded fittings   

· Injection molded specimen are butt fused together to form pressure vessel for testing (build in stress concentrator). Testing under hydrostatic pressure using Rate Process Method for SCG behaviour (RPM still in development state: reproducibility and external/internal validation still needs to be done)) 
· Claim of correlation between RPM analysis (pressure vessel) vs. pipe. (some doubts of benefits of this method in comparison with e.g. FNCT- red.)
3.5   Low sagging PE100 for thick wall pressure pipes – Mr. P. Belloir, Total Petrochemicals , Feluy, Belgium 

[image: image6.emf]C:\Documents and 

Settings\568517\Desktop\PE100 LS 001.tif


· Promotion of their newest grade: XLS12B = Low Sagging PE100 (C6-based PE100) 
· Market segmentation and Position of PE100 

· Position sagging XLS12B (sagging) vs. market reference (LS grade: most probably Borealis): Methods used: 1. zero-viscosity (DMS). 2. strain at very low shear (stress rheometer). 3. melt strength visual via parison (240° under gravity). Result: better sagging performance XLS12B compared to reference 

· Examples of external trials processing and sagging  
· Full technical report available to customer upon request

4. Materials and manufacturing 
4.1 Polymer processing additives to enhance extrusion processing of bimodal HDPE for high pressure pipe applications – Mr. J. de Witte 3M Belgium-Dyneon 
· Benefits of Polymer Processing Additives (PPA): Dynamar FX5911 

· Reduction of melt pressure (shear stress), increase throughput (shear rate), improve surface quality 

· PPA much less effective in blue than in black materials (waxes in blue pigment)  

· Already contacts/experience of SABIC Europe R&D with Dyneon about PPA
4.2  Methane permeation through advanced high-pressure plastic and composite pipes – Mr. F.Scholten KIWA Gastec, Apeldoorn, the Netherlands
· Material: PA-12 Why? Safety issue 

· Model calculations 

· Results of permeation experiments at pipes: addition of 10% long chain polyamide additives decreases the permeation coefficient significantly (what about other properties??) – pure theoretical study

Common questions about PE


• Modern PE materials like 
Borealis HE3490-LS ( Low Sag) 
have been developed to enable 
cost-efficient production of  
thick-wall pipes


• PE pipes can be produced 
today up to 2m of diameter with 
wall-thickness up to 120mm


• Welding equipment are 
available


• Reliable fittings solution are 
developed as well


Are PE pipe systems available in large diameters?


Yes,  pipes available in the main european countries

Plastic Pressure Pipes 2007- 26th June 2007


Common questions about PE


• Old cast iron pipes have 
variable initial roughness 
increases with age


• New DI is cement lined 
with low roughness but 
future is unclear


• New PE has very low 
roughness factor and this 
remains virtually constant


• This means a smaller i.d. 
PE pipe has the same 
flow capacity as larger DI 0 0,5 1 1,5 2 2,5


PE old


PE new


DI old


DI new


CI old


CI new


Roughness factor ks


PE has lowest roughness


Are flow properties of PE as good as cast iron?


Yes even better – smaller PE pipe can be used

Plastic Pressure Pipes 2007- 26th June 2007


• Key cost elements in the 
installation are the width (W), 
surround & reinstatement


• PE is usually jointed above ground 
& snaked into a narrower trench


• DI and GRP require regular man 
entry jointing pits


• Well compacted level sand bed 
required for DI & GRP,  welded PE 
can accommodate uneven bed & 
ground movement


• Often in rural areas PE can be 
installed by trenchless methods


Is it more difficult/costly to install than DI or GRP?


W


No - narrower trench & lower cost with PE 


Common questions about PE

Plastic Pressure Pipes 2007- 26th June 2007


• Rigid material such as DI 
build up stress under soil 
loading


• Visco-elastic materials like 
PE deform under load 
allowing stresses to relax


• Pipe & soil interact and 
develop an equilibrium 
situation


• TEPPFA & APME have 
developed models to predict 
deformation levels


Is PE as structurally secure as rigid materials?


Yes - PE able to shed stresses for increased life


Common questions about PE

Plastic Pressure Pipes 2007- 26th June 2007


• PE has welded joints with 
full end load resistance


• Welded systems better 
withstand earth movement 


• PE resists hydraulic forces 
without the need for anchor 
blocks – lower cost


• PE pipes are supplied in 
longer lengths usually 12m 
or 18m sticks


• PE can be joined in parallel 
with trench preparation 


Does PE take longer/cost more to joint than DI?


No - PE often faster to install + benefits welded joints!

• There are various costs to be 
considered


• Pipe cost per metre
• Installed cost per metre
• Installed cost for a real project
• Whole life costs where all the costs 


(including future operation, 
maintenance & repair costs) are 
included at present day values


• We compared different pipe materials 
for a typical large project 400mm & 
900mm at 16 bar.

Plastic Pressure Pipes 2007- 26th June 2007


So what does WLC tell us? 


• Whole Life Costing provides a 
more rational way to select pipe 
materials for projects


• The cheapest pipe is not always 
the lowest in Whole Life Costing


• Model needs to be refined with 
better failure statistics as they 
become available


• Model can provide a good 
promotional tool for the use of 
large diameter PE and can 
easily be customised per country


Triple 500mm over-pumping to reservoir


Final thought relevant in rich developed countries


Some concluding thoughts & comments!

New Polyethylene Materials 
(Eltex® Superstress™ PE100) 


with Step-out Stress Cracking Resistance 
for Highly Demanding Piping Technologies


by Pascale Godon,
27th June 2007







Copyright ©INEOS 2006


1Highly Demanding Piping Technologies No-dig technologies – Sandless bedding







Copyright ©INEOS 2006


Depending of the pipe diameter, soil, ...costs are estimated as :


• Pipe     10 -25 %
• Sand bed    20 – 50 %
• Works        70 -25%


The Superstress™ are designed to be used with non conventional laying :  
without sand bed and/or in trenchless application 


=>  Saving







Copyright ©INEOS 2006


Polyethylene is ideal for trenchless technologies thanks its …
• Flexibility, weldability, coilability, corrosion resistance, low roughness, stress 


crack resistance…


Trenchless technologies are used for : 
• Renovation (close fit liner) or replacement of an old pipe 
• Installation of a new pipe by directional drilling, …







Copyright ©INEOS 2006


Incrustations







Copyright ©INEOS 2006


Corrosion







Copyright ©INEOS 2006


Leakages







Copyright ©INEOS 2006


Flexibility, coilability, weldability of HDPE







Copyright ©INEOS 2006


Rehabilitation of an old pipe (roll-down, sub-lining, U-lining, 
compact pipe,…)


Thanks to its toughness, possible diameter reduction or 
shape change by radial or axial stress to facilitate its 
introduction in the old pipe.


HDPE pipe is than reverted to initial status by internal 
pressure/elastic reversion.


Possible consequent additional stress : scratches on the 
pipe surface  







Copyright ©INEOS 2006


Replacement of an old pipe (pipe bursting, pipe splitting, …)


HDPE pipe is forced through the old hole. 


Consequent additional stresses : scratches on the pipe surface, local 
loading







Copyright ©INEOS 2006


Installation of a new pipe by trenchless technology


After drilling of a pilot bore, HDPE pipe may 
be pulled inside the ground.   


Consequent additional stresses : scratches 
on the pipe surface, local loading  


Directional drilling

Saving by trenchless technologies pipe installation cost







Copyright ©INEOS 2006


2
Critical properties of polyethylene


materials in no-dig







Copyright ©INEOS 2006


To resist to …
tensile and axial stresses during installation : high stiffness – Yield  strength
sudden and short term pressure increasing : high stiffness
long term low stresses : stress crack resistance (ESCR)


For trenchless application, best HDPE quality PE100 with high stress crack resistance
to resist to additional low local stresses caused by scratches and point loads is 
recommended


The property balance high ESCR/stiffness can only be optimised by 
fine tuning of HDPE molecular design







Copyright ©INEOS 2006


HDPE is a semicrystalline polymer which can be assume as a mixture of: 


• Crystalline phase, high density (998 Kg/m3), stiffness but also brittleness 
(easy propagation of fractures plane accross the cristal)


• Amorphous phase, low density ( 860 Kg/m3), toughness and ductility


Tie molecule = long molecule included in minimum 2 cristalline lamellae. 
Under long term low stress load, tie molecules strech and relax, before to break


High [ tie molecule ]=> ESCR improvement but … lower stiffness


Crystal lamellae
Amorphous phase


Tie molecule







Copyright ©INEOS 2006


Superstress™ process


The property balance 
high ESCR/stiffness


can only be optimised by 
fine tuning of HDPE molecular design. 


This is performed by polymerisation in 
2 reactors (bimodal process), in 
presence of hexene comonomer







Copyright ©INEOS 2006


3New HDPE material achievement







Copyright ©INEOS 2006


New Superstress™ PE100 blue (water) and orange (gas) compounds ready to 
use, developed by Ineos Polyolefins fully comply with current standards for gas 
(EN1555) and water distribution (EN12201):


– Classification MRS 10 determined  by regression curves following the ISO 9080, 
which allow to guarantee a lifetime of minimum 50 years, at 20°C, in normal 
conditions of use, with a hoop stress of 10 Mpa


– Stiffness : resistance at short term when submitted at high hoop stress (20°C, 
12.4 Mpa / 80°C, 5.5 Mpa)


– Resistance to rapid crack propagation: the propagation of the fracture caused 
by an impact on the pipe conditioned at 0°C, is stopped for any internal 
pressure up to 1.5 time the nominal pressure


– Stress crack resistance determined by notch pipe test (NPT) at 80°C, 9.2 bar 
higher than 165 hours…


Material properties







Copyright ©INEOS 2006


…But our new Superstress™ PE100 blue (Eltex® TUB124N6000) and orange 
(Eltex® TUB125N6000) grades supersede 50 times the 165 hours in NPT required 
by the norms


NPT, 80°C, 9.2 bars > 1 year

Copyright ©INEOS 2006


To put in evidence the potential of a polyethylene pipe material for the trench 
less applications, many different tests can be performed: 


• Notch pipe test to simulate the scratch 


• Point loading test to model the Point Loading solicitation by smooth rocks   
(like pebbles)


• FNCT to determine the intrinsic stress crack resistance of these compounds, 
against the overall slow crack growth mechanism which prevails in low-pressure 
long-term service life operation conditions in piping systems.

Stress crack resistance differentiation :
Full notch creep test (FNCT) - Intrinsic stress crack resistance


Principle: (see ISO DIS 16770 Standard)


• 6 specimens cut-on moulded plates


• 1.6 mm deep notches on four sides   
(razor blade)


• Tensile test 4 MPa, 80°C


• Detergent : Arkopal N100 or NM5


Result : failure time and mode

5Conclusions







Copyright ©INEOS 2006


New Superstress™ blue Eltex® TUB124N6000 and orange Eltex® TUB125N6000
developed by Innovene fully comply with international standards ISO and EN for 
gas and water applications. 


Compared with traditional PE100 : impressive stress crack resistance


• Notch pipe test results : 30 times higher =>reduction of stress crack failure 
due to scratch of pipe during relining installation  -


• Point loading results : tremendous improvement => better resistance to 
accelerated stress cracking due to external impingement and indentation


• FNCT exceptional results =>very high stress crack resistance against the 
overall slow crack growth mechanism which prevails in low-pressure long-
term service life operation conditions in piping systems.
Perfectly suited for stress intensive applications (trenchless) 


In addition 


• PE100 higher output, MOP, higher safety factor and/or wall reduction
• Very good rapid crack performances may use for P >>, ф >>, for gas

Plastic Pressure Pipes 2007, Slide 5


WATER







Plastic Pressure Pipes 2007, Slide 6


Water - Background
• Mature market 90-95% connection levels in most of 


Europe
• Hence new build demand is important
BUT:
• Leakage levels are still high – wasting a natural resource
• The pressure remains on to address this problem
• Prompted by droughts, many water utilities continue to 


invest in back up supplies







Plastic Pressure Pipes 2007, Slide 7


Water – Traditional Pipe Materials
• Cast iron, steel, fibre-cement and concrete were the 


traditional water pipe materials.
• Cast iron has been largely replaced by ductile iron –


remains very price competitive above 250mm diameters.
• Ductile iron is strong regionally- St. Gobain is a major force 


with excellent products and a well known name.
• Fibre-cement has been discontinued.
• Steel is mainly now used for high pressure, chemical 


resistant applications. 
• Concrete pipes are still used above 400mm – generally 


pre-treatment.







Plastic Pressure Pipes 2007, Slide 8


Water – Plastics Pipe Systems
• Plastics pipe systems have eroded the share of cast/ductile iron


substantially – they now have virtually 100% of the house 
connection and are strong up to 250mm.


• PVC has been losing share to PE for many years now because 
of longer lengths, installed cost savings and welded joints.


• PE100 has been embraced by pipe producers and their 
customers as a cost efficient material.  More of its share has 
been at the expense of PE80, however, not ductile iron.


• PE125 materials are believed to be developed but there is little
enthusiasm for further change.


• MoPVC systems have arrested PVC’s decline in some localities 
but they have also mainly replaced normal PVC more than 
ductile iron or PE.







Plastic Pressure Pipes 2007, Slide 9


Water – Share by Material <109mm







Plastic Pressure Pipes 2007, Slide 10


Water – Share by Material 110-299mm







Plastic Pressure Pipes 2007, Slide 11


Water – Share by Material >300mm







Plastic Pressure Pipes 2007, Slide 12


Water - The Market for PVC Pipe Systems

Minor 31.9 32.5 34.9 0.4 1.8
Scandinavia 7.4 6.5 5.3 -2.9 -5.0


Total 151.7 144.7 137.9 -1.2 -1.2







Plastic Pressure Pipes 2007, Slide 13


Water – PVC Pipe Systems
• The decline in PVC’s position as a water pipe material has 


mainly been caused by the acceptance of PE’s strengths –
flexibility, long lengths, less jointing, lower installed cost etc.


• Further damage has been done by the Greenpeace anti-
chlorine campaign and by the problems of lead stabiliser 
replacement.


• Both issues are being countered by the PVC industry and the 
anticipated further decline of PVC will be mainly due to PE.


• In the face of this decline, some producers may seek to reduce 
their ranges and even abandon PVC for pressure pipes.


• MoPVC systems will grow but locally and not by enough to halt 
PVC’s overall decline.

Plastic Pressure Pipes 2007, Slide 15


Water - MoPVC
• Two types of high performance PVC pressure pipes –


molecularly orientated and chemically modified.
• Same target as PE100 – higher pressure, thinner walls.
• Initiative came from the pipe producers – Uponor, Seperef.
• Can withstand 25 bars but are 2-3 times more expensive 


than ductile iron equivalents.
• 16 bar more common but still expensive.
• Processes are difficult and investment high.
• Total market in 2006 estimated at <16kt, main markets 


being the UK, France, Spain and Neths.
• Producers – at least 6 – continue to promote vigorously.

Plastic Pressure Pipes 2007, Slide 18


Water – PE Pipe Systems
• Will continue to grow, taking further share from PVC and 


ductile iron.
• Substitution more likely to be utility specific than industry 


wide; marginal improvements in materials may tip the 
balance but not prompt major changes.


• Drivers for change more likely to come from:
– new generation specifiers - within utilities or contractors
– re-appraisal of installed costs
– project specific success (or failure)
– success in the brown field segment - closed to normal PE

Plastic Pressure Pipes 2007, Slide 20


Water - High Performance Systems
• Overcapacity and poor prices in basic PE80 and PE100 


systems are spawning new technology products such as:
– multi-layer pipes for brownfield sites - a growing segment of 


the new build market (GPS “Protecta Line”)
– abrasion resistant pipes which offer savings on bedding 


costs - hence addressing the important issue of installed 
costs (Egeplast “SLM”, Uponor “Pro-Fuse”, Wavin “TS”)


• Sold as premium products - typically 2-3 times more than 
standard PE100.  Hence niche potential but growing well.


• Rehau and Wirsbo have tried promoting PEX for house 
connections but price premium of 3-4 times not justified by 
the benefits.







Plastic Pressure Pipes 2007, Slide 21


Water Pressure – the Challenges
• To erode further ductile iron’s market share:


– Price competitive above 300mm.
– Long, successful track record 
– St.Gobain dominates most markets – well connected.
– Good products - improved corrosion resistance and ductility.
– Suitable for all ground conditions.  


• To reduce overcapacity in PE systems
• To develop higher value niches
• To deliver value and/or performance – not “me too”.







Plastic Pressure Pipes 2007, Slide 22


GAS







Plastic Pressure Pipes 2007, Slide 23


Gas - Background
• Natural gas accounts for 25% of prime energy 


consumption - set to grow to 30% by 2025.
• Fits well with current “energy thinking”, although there 


could be pressure to scale down fossil fuels in favour of 
nuclear power and renewables.


• Domestic connection levels are highest in the Netherlands 
(95%) and the UK (85%).


• Undeveloped markets are the Scandinavian countries and 
Switzerland.  Gas seems likely to come to Scandinavia but 
possibly not for 6-7 years.


• Gas distribution far more concentrated than water - often 1 
national operator.







Plastic Pressure Pipes 2007, Slide 24


Gas - Materials Used
• Determined almost solely  by pressure:


– Transmission mains >40 bar, mainly steel, some ductile iron
– Street mains <5 bar - usually lower - mainly PE
– House connections <1 bar - all PE


• There is a small medium pressure market - 16 bar for city 
ring mains and this is contested by steel and PE.


• Cast iron has been phased out but ductile iron systems 
suppliers have a renewed interest in gas.  However, major 
setback in the UK (failure).


• Modified PVC is still used for gas pipes in the Netherlands 
- as popular as PE (and more profitable !)







Plastic Pressure Pipes 2007, Slide 25


Gas - The Market for PE Pipe Systems


Kt % Change Per Annum
2002 2006 2010 2006/02 2010/06

Plastic Pressure Pipes 2007, Slide 27


Gas - PE Pipe Systems
• Currently the biggest markets are the UK, Germany, Italy –


all around 20-22 kt.
• Some network extensions are expected in Spain, Portugal 


and Ireland, with longer term possibilities in Scandinavia.
• German market has declined from over 33kt to under 25kt 


in 5 years but may have reached its low point.  Saturated.
• Demand in Central Europe has also peaked - most 


networks are now in place.
• With the growing role of Russian gas, the volume potential 


is in Eastern Europe.







Plastic Pressure Pipes 2007, Slide 28


Gas Pressure – the Challenges
• To cope with the “boom and bust” nature of 


long term contracts.
• To decide whether or not to address the 


changing geography of opportunity.
• To assess the impact of changing energy 


policies – nuclear, renewables.
• Can the plastics industry attack copper and 


steel inside the house – as it has done in hot & 
cold water ?







Plastic Pressure Pipes 2007, Slide 29


CONCLUSIONS







Plastic Pressure Pipes 2007, Slide 30


Problems
• W.European growth markets are mature, growth rates 


declining.
• The scope for substituting traditional materials is narrowing –


– The trend is to reduce pressures – saving energy, increasing 
safety, reducing leakage - low pressure segments already 
penetrated.


• Water and gas pipes are commodity items – too many 
producers for the opportunity available.


• Overcapacity – esp. in PE100 – magnified by ever higher line 
speeds. 


• The pipes industry needs to innovate – but its customers hate 
change!







Plastic Pressure Pipes 2007, Slide 31


Overall Dilemmas


The Plastics Industry 
thrives on change


The Utilities and 
Builders hate it


Differentiation enables 
profitability


Differentiation 
confuses


Plastics pipe producers
seek substitution


Higher volume 
– lower margins







Plastic Pressure Pipes 2007, Slide 32


Strategy Options - Geographic
• Continue to service established markets.
• Look East for volume - but there are 


imponderables:
• Local production, acquisition, exporting via partner ?
• What to sell – pipes ? fittings ? systems ? technology ?
• Aspirations – mass market or niche ?
• Product range – does it meet the needs of the market ?
• Quality – is it appropriate to local needs ?
• Can the commitment be profitable ?







Plastic Pressure Pipes 2007, Slide 33


Strategy Options - Products
• Pipes, fittings, systems or technology ?
• Commodity pipes or specialities
• Materials – is PVC finished ?  Can PP challenge in pressure ?
• Technologies:


– Compact
– Multi-layer:


• barrier pipes address brownfield land needs
• abrasion resistant pipes attack installed cost
• other niches ????


– Light weighting – can wall thickness reduction push PE’s cost 
competitiveness above 300mm ?


• Are product ranges/technologies appropriate to the future 
needs of the market ?







Plastic Pressure Pipes 2007, Slide 34


Strategy Options - Manufacturing
• Is there scope for more specialisation ? 


Producers offer 20+ diameters of PE100 water 
pipe, prices are dragged down, valuable 
production time is lost with changeover.  Why 
not specialise and buy in the rest ?  More 
partnerships ?


• Efficiency – surely Egeplast’s “Quick Change”
is the way forward ?


• Matching capacity to demand.







Plastic Pressure Pipes 2007, Slide 35


Four Essentials


• Deliver value


• Deliver benefits


• Deliver service


• Address real needs







Plastic Pressure Pipes 2007, Slide 36

LD6 PLANT MODEL WORKSHOP- PART 1

Maryam Tamaddoni, Frans Visscher, Miran Milosevic

9 Feb 2015

No. 3

INTRODUCTION

Aspen Plus is the market-leading chemical process simulation

software used by different industries for the design, operation, and

optimization of manufacturing facilities.

What is flowsheet simulation?

 Use of a computer program to quantitatively model the

characteristic equations of a chemical process



No. 4

GENERAL SIMULATION PROBLEM

What is the composition of stream PRODUCT?

Mass balances? Energy balances? Thermodynamic properties? Reaction 

Kinetics? 

This is where the idea of a process model is helpful



No. 5

ADVANTAGES OF SIMULATION

Helps improve current process

• Answers “what if” questions

• Determines optimal process conditions within given constraints

• Assists in locating the constraining parts of a process (debottlenecking)

For LD6:

• Prediction of MWD, MFI and density of powder (example: to minimize the

required trial run and off spec materials for developing new grades)

• Developing heat & mass balances for feasibility studies, process

developments and optimization studies (examples: change of co-

monomer, change of diluent, change of operating conditions, energy

optimization, reduction of byproducts)



No. 6

PRACTICAL EXAMPLE - HAO STUDY

Distillation column for trial run

The column modeled with current components (butene/ hexane) and used for sensitivity

analysis to evaluate the maximum amount of feed that column can handle due to a shift

to hexene/heptane and meet the allowable specification (mole purity in bottom product)

Flash vessel

To define the amount of gas/ liquid separation and mass flow of components to the

second reactor

Butene recovery

To compare the amount of butene vs hexene recovered and recycled back to the

second reactor

Process vessels

To investigate the effect of temperature & pressure and to define the operating

conditions for the new diluent system e.g. to generate enough vapor for distillation

column re-boiler and in the wax recovery



EXAMPLE CASE 1



No. 8

ASPEN USER INTERFACE



No. 9

FILE TAB

New : Create a new simulation (blank or from a template).

Open : Open a simulation.

Save: Save the current simulation under its existing name.

Save As: Save the current simulation under a new name, and possibly as a new file 

type. 

Import: Import a file into the current simulation.

Export: Export a file from the current simulation. 

Print Preview: See how printed output will appear before printing.

Print: Print the active window.

Options: Open the Options dialog box to specify default options.

Exit: Close Aspen Plus.

No. 15

MAIN FLOWSHEET WINDOW

The Main Flowsheet window is where you create and display simulation flowsheets. To 

open it, click Open Flowsheet on the Home tab of the ribbon in the Simulation 

environment.

The process flowsheet window shows which blocks generated errors or warnings when 

last run



No. 16

THE MODEL PALETTE

Use the Model Palette to select unit operation models and icons that you want placed 

on the flowsheet. The Model Palette appears at the bottom of the workspace.



No. 17

No. 18

HELP

On any form or dialog box in Aspen Plus, you can obtain context-sensitive help by 

pressing the F1 key.

Review the model, input data and output results and confirm a list of missing data and

required modifications

material analysis

Validation of the model for one grade

month)

model to LD6 staff

transitions)

Documentation and developing model tutorials (to facilitate knowledge transfer and to

ensure its availability for future users)

No. 15

CAPABILITY – 3 GATE SYSTEM

Research Agreement with the Eindhoven Technical University

Fluidization tests with additives to avoid polymer agglomeration

• Contract signed

• Kick-off meeting scheduled for 30 April 2016 – review of goals and experimental plan

• Collecting polymer powder and polymer additives (e.g. Statsafe)

Research Agreement with the Iowa State University

Development of a computational fluid dynamic model for large-scale three-phase stirred-tank reactors

• Single phase simulations
• Reactor 1 (Dimpeller = 1.6 m) and Reactor 2 (Dimpeller = 1.4 m)

• Recirculation rate of liquid: 1 m3/s

• Multiphase (gas-solid-liquid) simulations
• Reactor 1 and Reactor 2

• Volumetric flow rate of slurry at outlet: 1 m3/s

• Down pumping

• Continue three-phase simulations with recirculation of slurry for both reactors, Study residence time 

distribution in the reactor. Study effect of different particle size.

Research Agreement with the ICT Prague

• Sorption of liquid n-hexane in HDPE samples at 70°C.

Research on ACP material

Mission Statement
The motivation of the butane hydrocracking program is on the development of a technology that fits within SABIC’s long-term business strategy.  To this end, the program is focused on maximizing ethylene production from a butane feedstock.  This technology holds promise in allowing SABIC to use a readily available feedstock to help fuel and grow their ethylene derivatives businesses.

Today’s presentation focuses on:
Programs alignment with SABIC’s business strategy
The process development and economic motivations for pursuing the directions of the program 
Provide a complete view of the process that needs to be developed



No. ‹#›


As crackers transition to heavier feeds (e.g. OtC) and refineries ramp up production, more C4s and C5s are generated with low value uses.  This opens the door for a technology that can increase the overall production of ethylene from these feedstocks.

Technology opportunity

Novel Hydrocracking Concepts


Butane hydrocracking as a feedstock for Ethane/Propane gas crackers


Hydrocracking of C4/C5 recycle within naphtha crackers






Novel Hydrocracking applications
Butane Hydrocracking as a Feedstock for Ethane/Propane
Ongoing experiments are positive – Selectively converted to ethane/propane (focus of presentation)

Higher ethylene production than butane steam cracking (55 wt% vs 35 wt%)

“Clean” product distribution (methane, ethane, propane) – ideal fit for gas cracker add-on

Technology has the ability to broadly impact SABIC (see next slide)



No. ‹#›


Fit of Butane hydrocracking within SABIC
An existing KSA cracker with excess capacity for ethane/propane
Reliability projects will help to free up capacity
Allocation of butane is available
Cheap insurance technology if allocation of ethane is cut

An existing KSA cracker that currently cracks butane and ethane, i.e. Saudi Kayan, and has a preference for cracking ethane over butane 
Higher ethylene yields can be attained through hydrocracker as opposed to direct butane cracking

“Green field” KSA gas cracker or furnace additions
Butane hydrocracker coupled with a new KSA gas cracker
Add additional furnaces/equipment at existing affiliates
Strategic technology to help reach 2025 target

	Ethylene	2400 KTA	1500 KTA
			
	NPV	$1,114 MM	$1,168 MM

Butane HC + SC produces more ethylene thus the equipment cost is higher

Butane feed rate kept constant in both cases

No. ‹#›


Energy Balance
Hydrogen content of fuel/tail gas is lower for butane hydrocracking option vs. conventional butane steam cracking
0.6 wt% vs. 1.4 wt% of effluent stream

Produced methane will supplement heating duty

An exercise around energy balance will be undertaken in stage 3/4 to verify

No. ‹#›


The catalyst



No. ‹#›


Hydrocracking catalyst history
Fully scaled catalyst already in hand
Catalyst composition originally designed and optimized for gasoline hydrocracking

Work with Zeolyst has produced several semi-commercial scale batches
Varying Pt content in order to study effect on activity and deactivation rate
Pt/ZSM-5 (Pt = 0.07, 0.15, 0.30 wt%)

results in low methane make

 C8 + C4 → C12 
C)

C12 → 4 C3

Process optimization



No. ‹#›


Process optimization
C4 HYDROCRACKING
C4H10 + H2                C2H6 + C3H8 


 
PROCESS OPTIMIZATION 

Catalyst: 0.07wt% Pt/HZSM-5


Bed temperature: 350 – 520 °C

WHSV(based on HC) : 2 – 12 hr-1

H2/HC molar ratio: 0.5 – 3

Pressure: 100 – 300 psi


No. ‹#›


Process Optimization – so far
Optimization based on maximizing ethane make and decreasing methane make

Maximize product value, i.e. ethylene


Optimized parameter windows:
Temperature: 420 – 470 °C
H2/HC: 0.75 – 1
WHSV: 4 – 8 hr-1
Product value, $/tonn
