Summary and path forward



No. ‹#›


2nd Generation catalyst program
Looking ahead to next generation catalyst to provide “step change” in performance
Increase ethane yield
Longer-term research effort

Investigating hydrogenolysis chemistry
Catalyst synthesis and screening program initiated
Reactor parameter investigation

Hurdles
Unselective reaction (high methane makes)
Higher hydrogen usages
Isomerization (isobutane results in high methane) 

Program recently initiated – data will be forthcoming



No. ‹#›


Summary
Butane hydrocracking technology provides a pathway to “organic” business expansion within KSA with a feedstock that is available.
Technology fits well with SABIC’s current business portfolio (higher ethylene yields compared to conventional SC)

Butane hydrocracking provides a very clean technology which can integrate easily with a conventional gas cracker.

An initial set of optimized process parameters has been identified to yield the highest product value and lowest deactivation rate.



No. ‹#›


Path Forward to Gate 4
Close out process parameter studies.
Looking at catalysts with varying Pt content

In coming months, we will be testing scaled-up catalysts in the form of extrudates at a feed rate of ~5 kg/day.
Deactivation studies

Development of a kinetic reactor model (support from ESD)

Initiating Gen-2 catalyst development efforts
Hydrogenolysis catalysts (bimetallic catalyst systems)

Planning for future – Assess heat balance of reaction within a multiple reactor adiabatic pilot unit (piloting unit in Geleen)
Stage 4 activity – Handoff and collaboration with the SBU

Hydrocrack butane feed to methane, ethane, propane
Ethane, propane are fed to the steam cracker

enhanced Butane Cracking

Higher value to SABIC’s strategy as an ethylene/derivatives producer

No. ‹#›


methodology
Use steam cracker material balance worksheet to identify products from steam cracker complex. Modify according to assumed disposition of products.
Butane steam cracking considers high value C4 products
Butane HC + Steam Cracking maximizes ethylene yields
Process layout for the variants and identify major equipment
Equipment cost estimates using literature data (costing by analogy method)



No. ‹#›


C4 hydrocracking – scale-up considerations
Rob Broekhuis


No. ‹#›


43


Current state of knowledge
Activities and selectivities being investigated in lab reactors
Integral reactors – but with some variation of WHSV
Isothermal – but with variation of temperature
Some effects of inlet composition demonstrated
Effect of particle size probed
Single catalyst system

More extensive reaction engineering/process development work undertaken for FHC project
Kinetic model developed based on HTE experiments (using PhysMix catalyst)
Pilot reactors allowing adiabatic operation
Aspen models including kinetics, heat transfer, reactors in series, etc.

Characterization of engineering problem
Relatively straightforward gas/solid catalytic process
Easily modelled given kinetic and thermodynamic data
Few intermediate steps required to commercial scale-up



No. ‹#›


Planned activities
Lab reactors
Characterization of catalyst variations?
Confirmation of (lack of) internal mass transfer dependence
Performance using iC4/nC4 feed mixture
Characterization of deactivation rate at various operating conditions
Operation at more differential conditions

Larger unit
Proof of concept at larger throughput
Characterization of deactivation rate
Isothermicity unclear

STC-G pilot unit
When available, for adiabatic studies at range of proposed commercial operating conditions


No. ‹#›


Required for confidence in scale-up 
Kinetics over selected catalyst
FHC kinetics can be starting point, but don’t capture current insights from C4HC studies
Will likely require ability to vary feed composition (besides just C4/H2 ratio)
Capture in manageable model that can be deployed in Aspen

Understand catalyst deactivation
As a function of operating pressure, temperature, composition
With real feeds
At least develop correlation – developing understanding preferred
Consider possibility of catalyst regeneration

Reactor and process modeling 
with kinetics, heat effects, pressure drop
Consider various reactor configurations – axial & radial flows, internal cooling
Consider process permutations – heat transfer, recycle, separation, H2 staging, etc.

Past Hydrocracking Projects


No. ‹#›


Great work done by the team in Europe laid the framework for similar chemistries to be applied to specific applications

51


Mild Hydrocracking (MHC) project – Benzene purification technology to replace the aromatics complex at Wilton  


Hydrocrack BTX coboilers (C6+ hydrocarbons) to LPG


Project evolved to become part of OtC designs


Feed Hydrocracking (FHC) project – Technology to convert naphtha into LPG upfront of a gas cracker


Utilize excess gas cracking capacity of KSA crackers


Pitfalls -


BTX still needs to be extracted downstream, i.e. makes a retrofit or add-on to a gas cracker increasingly “messy”


Only home for project found within Advanced OTC

Zeolite – focused on ZSM-5, why?
Known coke resistant – medium pore zeolite vs. large pore
Site (Al) conc. – important for reaction and coke formation – wide range available 
 Pt/ZSM-5 – Chosen catalyst platform

No. ‹#›


Novel Hydrocracking applications
Experiments were positive – showed mixed C4/C5 streams could effectively and selectively be converted to ethane/propane

Although ethylene production is higher, economics of C4/C5 Recycle Hydrocracking not overly advantageous over conventional recycling (@ given price set)

Con – Ethane furnaces within typical naphtha crackers are typically too small to accommodate increased gas volume 



No. ‹#›


Novel Hydrocracking applications
Application shelved for now
Technology works
Economics to be revisited
Process development halted (for now)

Core advantages of Butane to Ethane Technology

 Lower Capex (Capex of C4 HC + C2 cracker lower than C4 cracker)

 Significant shift towards ethylene (SABIC’s main building block for growth)

 Likely to secure additional feedstock allocation

 Increased carbon efficiency to target olefins

 Low propylene production

Disadvantages of Butane to Ethane Technology

Field butane stream: 70% n-butane/30% i-butane



3

Classification: Internal Use

 KEY – Identifying which feedstocks have low 

carbon efficiencies to valuable chemicals

 Feedstocks, which have low carbon efficiencies 

in a steam cracker, are the most attractive for 

using Hydrocracking-type technologies

 The technology itself will always make some 

portion of methane

 Propane and Butane are the least carbon 

efficient feedstocks for a steam cracker

 Target feedstocks for optimization

CONFIDENTIAL

STEAM CRACKING TECHNOLOGY – CARBON EFFICIENCY

Classification: Internal Use

CONFIDENTIAL

TECHNOLOGY PLATFORM

Distribution Hub (1st Technology Rollout – Demo)

• Centralized facility distributing ethane/propane (1000 KTA butane processing)

• 738 KTA Ethane

• 109 KTA Propane (fill spare capacity at SADAF and SHARQ)

Integration with a new build ethane cracker

• New build cracker – customized integration would further reduced the cost 

Integration with on-purpose MTBE

• Elimination of isomerization unit

• Technology could be married to an existing facility or new build

U.S. Shale Market

• Shale gas production is often limited by the over production of butanes –
Converting these butanes would unlock further gas production

• Fluor is ready to put us in contact with a potential interested party



5

Classification: Internal Use

CONFIDENTIAL

BUSINESS CASE LAYOUT

Butane Conversion Unit Integrated with Cracker Stand-alone Distribution Hub

1) Where does this sit on ethylene production cost curve?

 Our goal isn’t to be the cheapest – not to displace 
ethane cracking

 Our goal is to be a medium cost production 
technology – Quartile 2/3 – and push out the high 
cost producers in Quartile 4

2) Where does it sit relative to butane SC?
 Technology to displace butane SC for ethylene 

production

 No other alternative option/comparison
 Other than “status quo” operation

 Increase ethylene production by filling assets
 Spare capacity
 Preference ethane over propane cracking
 Allocation cuts

Other potential synergies for technology:
 OTC, MTBE, Shale Gas

• 15% lower total capital cost

• Uses 37% less butanes feed to obtain an equivalent ethylene production

STC-GELEEN PILOTING



11

Classification: Internal Use

 Four adiabatic reactors in series. A temperature rise of 20C is targeted per reactor giving a total n-butane 
conversion of about 50 to 60% T-rise limited to keep safety margin.

 Catalyst deactivation is mitigated by increasing the inlet temperature of each reactor to maintain a 

consistent T of 20C

CONFIDENTIAL

12

Classification: Internal Use

 Reactor configuration

 Catalyst: PtIr/ZSM5, 775 gram per reactor (3.1 kg 

in total)  62 cm bed height per reactor

 Feed rate: 6.2 kg C4 per hour (70% n-C4, 30% i-C4)

 WHSV: 2 /hr

 H2 flow rate: 6.0 nm
3/hr

 H2:C4 molar ratio of 2.5:1

13

Classification: Internal Use

 Startup of four reactors in series requires great 

caution:

 C4 hydrogenolysis highly exothermic: strong 

response to small inlet temperature variations 

 Preference: Slow and careful startup of 

reactors 1 by 1

CONFIDENTIAL

STARTUP

R4

Axial bed position

T
e

m
p

e
ra

tu
re

Strong response to 
small variations in 
inlet temperature

Fast 
deactivation 
due to low 
temperature 
exposure to 
C2&C3

 However: C2-C4 components easily adsorb on 

catalyst at low sub reaction temperatures 

causing deactivation due to green oil formation 

 Reduce exposure of catalyst to C2-C4 under non 

reacting conditions: fast startup required!

How to combine?
New and improved startup procedure required



14

Classification: Internal Use

New startup procedure

• Startup time reduced from over 1 

week to 2 days

• No intermediate shutdowns due 

to high temperature

• No startup induced deactivation

CONFIDENTIAL

IMPROVED STARTUP STRATEGY

1) Start reaction under low C4:H2
ratio’s simultaneously

2) Gradually bring up C4 feed 
and continuously adjust 
temperatures to keep T<25C

Smoother, safer and more efficient startup procedure:
• Less sensitivity of reactor temperature to inlet temperature at 

low C4:H2 ratio 
• Less exposure of catalyst to C2 and C3 under non reacting 

conditions
• Decreased startup time

17

Classification: Internal Use

 2 months of continuous operation with four 

reactors at 6.2 kg/hr (WHSV = 2/hr)

 Total n-butane conversion of 50-60% 

 no noticeable i-C4 conversion

 Catalyst deactivation mitigated by increasing 

reactor T

 deactivation rate: on average 2C/week

 Ethane selectivity of 78.1 to 77.4%

 slow decrease with increasing reactor 

temperature: about 0.1%/week

 Estimated catalyst cycle length: 4-6 months

 Integrated Butane Conversion Unit w/ Ethane Cracker (2300 KTA butane) 
• 1500 KTA ethylene production

2) Capital cost study between different steam crackers (ethane, 50:50 
ethane/propane, butane)
 Numbers are based on Fluor projects and SK data

19



Classification: Internal Use

Basis of Design

♦ Conversion and Yields set Unit design
– Catalyst converts 100% nC4 and 15% iC4 while producing a mixture of 

Methane, Ethane and Propane.  Hydrogen is consumed.  Additional 
hydrogen is circulated to minimize coke formation.

– Reaction is initiated at about 250°C.  The actual temperature depends on 
the activity of the catalyst and the compensation of the reactants.  The 
temperature rise should not be allowed to exceed 20°C across any one 
bed, as the reaction runs away if the temperature rise exceeds ~30-40°C.

20



Classification: Internal Use

Basis of Design (cont)

– The products are a light hydrogen rich fuel gas, an ethane stream, a 
propane stream, and an isobutane stream.  The isobutane stream can be 
exported or converted to n-butane and recycled.

21



Classification: Internal Use

BFD for the Distribution HUB (1,000 KTA)

22

Designed to be self-sufficient in H2
 In actuality there might be H2 available for use in Jubail



Classification: Internal Use

BFD for Integrated Case (2,300 KTA)

23

Designed to deliver 1500 kta ethylene integrated with cracker



Classification: Internal Use

Unit Design

♦ Basis unit design is a feed section, a reaction section, followed by 
product compression and product separation.  Supporting units include a 
Steam Methane Reformer (SMR), a Pressure Swing Absorption (PSA) 
Unit and an Isomerization Unit.
– The feed section consists of a Feed Surge Drum, Pump, Vaporizer, and Charge Heater.  

No feed treatment is required based on the feed composition provided.

– The reactor section has several beds and inter-stage coolers to ensure a proper 
temperature rise across the reactor beds.

24



Classification: Internal Use

Unit Design (Cont)

– The Product Compressor increases the pressure from the reactor outlet of 100 psig 
minus the piping and exchanger pressure losses, to the Demethanizer inlet pressure of 
650 psig. 

– The product separation section consists of a cryogenic demethanizer to strip almost all 
of the methane and hydrogen from the ethane and heavier streams;  A Deethanizer to 
recover a high purity ethane steam;  and a Depropanizer to separate the propane and 
butane streams.

– The excess hydrogen from the Demethanizer Off-Gas can be recovered via a PSA unit 
to minimize the hydrogen required to be produced by the SMR.

25



Classification: Internal Use

Unit Design (Cont)

– The unreacted isobutane can be converted to ethane and propane products by 
recycling the isobutane through an Isomerization unit to convert the 97% 
isobutane to a 60%/40% normal butane and isobutane stream.  A De-
isobutanizer (DIB) tower could be added to reduce the quantity of isobutane
recycled; however the DIB tower has a cost – the isomerization unit would be 
larger and the recycle isobutane has the benefit of helping to control the 
temperature rise across reactor beds.  Therefore, only a single pass 
Isomerization Unit is needed.

26



Classification: Internal Use

Reactor Design – External Exchangers

27



Classification: Internal Use

Reactor PFD

28



Classification: Internal Use

Quench Media

– Air -- This implies air coolers for the external coolers, which at 250°C 
would beyond the allowable temperature for aluminum fins. 

– Cooling Water -- Cooling water is not normally used above 80°C, high 
pressure water can be used, except 300°C requires a design pressure in 
excess of 1200 psig.

– Steam Generation – 300# Steam can be generated at these conditions, 
however there is no demand for the medium pressure steam.

29



Classification: Internal Use

Quench Media (cont.)

– Hot Oil  -- at 200°C to 300°C several commercial hot oils are available in 
the temperature range, and there may be one that is economical, 
however for the basis of this study they were not considered, for the 
following reasons:

• The high cost of the Hot Oil

• The cost of storing another commodity 

• The replacement cost of the Hot Oil as it degrades

– Molten Salt – excessive cost for this temperature range.

30



Classification: Internal Use

Quench Media (cont.)

– Feed – This was the selected option for the following reasons:
• The feed is always available, at no additional purchasing or storage cost.

• The feed is stable at these temperatures, no olefins or di-olefins

• The cost is for the additional capacity of the feed and vaporization systems and the 
condensing system to recover the quench material and return it to the Feed Surge 
Drum.

31



Classification: Internal Use

Estimating Methodology

♦ Butane Hydrocracker 

– ISBL – Class 4 type equipment factor type estimate utilizing Aspen Capital Cost 
Estimator CCETM for an assumed Jubail Saudi Arabia location. Estimate accuracy 
+30%/-30%. 

– Overall – Approximately 90% of mechanical equipment cost was capacity ratio from 
recent vendor quote. Construction labor rates and productivity based on current market 
data. 

♦ SMR & Isomerization 

– ISBL – Class 5 capacity factor type estimates from Fluor historical data for similar type 
units with an estimate accuracy of +40%/-40%. 

♦ OSBL

– Provision of 35% of ISBL costs allowed for utilities and offsites for all cases.

TECHNOLOGIES INVESTIGATED FOR BUTANE TO ETHANE CONVERSION

2. C-C lysis  Clean product slate (C1-C3)

3. Parallel reaction mechanism  WHSV independence

4. Potential to maximize C2 production

Classification: Internal Use

Catalyst innovation within the team provided the starting 
point for a “best in class” catalyst:

 ZSM-5 support optimized to lowest Al content

 DOE performed to optimize metal (Pt-Ir) content

 Patent application filed

CONFIDENTIAL

Catalyst Formulation: (0.3,0.3)wt%IrPt/ZSM-5 (Si/Al = 140)

Optimal reaction parameters per DOE: WHSV = 1/hr, P = 50-100 psig, T = 275°C, H2/HC = 2-2.5

Reactor performance studies revealed that, under specific sets 
of operating parameters, a reactive separation occurs:

 @300˚C, XnC4 = 100 %, XiC4 = 10 % 

 Product selectivities (mol%) : C2 = 76%, C1 = 15%, C3 = 9%

44

Classification: Internal Use

NEXT STEPS

Catalyst Characterization with Ayman Karim Group – Virginia Tech

 XAFS to examine the evolution of the Pt-Ir interaction in freshly calcined, spent, and agglomerated catalysts

 TEM to analyze the particle size distribution 

 H2 chemisorption to measure dispersion 

Reactor Testing of 1/8” Extrudates

 Next catalyst loading in the STC-Geleen pilot unit will be with the 1/8” extrudates 

 1/8” extrudates may become mass transfer limited under high reaction rates  may reduce risk of thermal runaway

 Use of 1/8” extrudates would reduce the pressure drop across the catalyst bed by a factor of 2 (not of great concern)

Catalyst Deactivation and Regeneration Studies

 Coke analysis is ongoing at STC-H 

 Residual coke analysis thus far shows <1% carbon deposition after six months on-stream (as measured by NDIR)

 Hydrogen stripping, oxidative treatments, and oxychlorination methods are being investigated for regeneration

Deactivation/Regeneration: Work in progress

Possible deactivation routes:

 Carbon deposition: Mechanism similar to green oil (C8-C30 

linear hydrocarbons) formation during acetylene 

hydrogenation

Unperturbed product distribution hints at the non accessibility of active sites resulting from carbon deposition as the potential 

deactivation mechanism

Potential route to deactivation: Carbon deposition

 Metal site sintering (unlikely at the temperatures of interest)

 Phase segregation: Changes in Pt-Ir interactions (unlikely as 

it would result in a change in product distribution)



48

Classification: Internal Use

CONFIDENTIAL

DEACTIVATION MECHANISM

Deactivation/Regeneration: Work in progress

Potential deactivation route:

 Carbon deposition: Mechanism similar to green oil (C8-C30 

linear hydrocarbons) formation during acetylene 

hydrogenation

Two types of coke species reported

1. Green oil: C4H6 (precursor), saturated C8-C25 linear 

hydrocarbons

2. Unsaturated HC intermediates strongly adsorbed on active 

sites making them inaccessible

Zheng et. al., Chem. Eng. Technol. 2016, 39, No. 5, 865-873

COKE CHARACTERIZATION 

Small et. al., J. Am. Chem. Soc. 2011, 133, 3582-3591

Work in progress

TGA-MS analysis of a spent catalyst:

 Mass spec detected m/z signals at 43 and 41 

typical for linear paraffins

 Studies in progress to analyze higher m/z 

confirming the presence of coke precursors



50

Classification: Internal Use

CONFIDENTIAL

REGENERATION STRATEGIES

Zheng et. al., Chem. Eng. Technol. 2016, 39, No. 5, 865-873

1. Hydrogen stripping: Helps with the removal of the strongly 

bound unsaturated carbonaceous deposits on metal sites. 

2. Low temperature oxidation: Burns coke and eliminates the 

complex oxychlorination step to re-disperse metal sites.

3. Oxychlorination (High temperature oxidation): Re-disperse 

metal if high temperature oxidation required

Catalyst replacement: Fallback strategy

Working on three regeneration strategies to combat deactivation by coke deposition

• Agglomerated catalyst: Due to a lack of spent catalyst, calcined a fresh catalyst at 550 °C for 4 h to agglomerate metal sites

Classification: Internal Use

• Hydrogenolysis is a highly structure sensitive chemistry - startup procedure can influence the activity and selectivity.

• Pre-reduction aids in the removal of chlorides from fresh catalyst, high temperature helps in completely eliminating the 

chlorides and efficiently activating the catalyst.

• Studies in progress:

 Pre-calcination → Reduction

 Reduction (high temperature) → Calcination → Reduction (low temperature)

REACTION SCHEMES

 C4 molecules dimerize then 

crack at low residence times, 

forming C3 and C5.

 C3 molecules dimerize then 

crack at high residence times, 

forming C2.

 Formation of aromatics at high 

residence times drives coke 

formation and deactivation of 

acid sites.

Classification: Internal Use

H2/C4H10 = 0.75, T = 488-491 °C, P = 100 psig

DETAILED MECHANISM AND KINETIC MODELING

Hydrogenation/Dehydrogenation [M]
1. C3H8 ↔ C3H6 + H2
2. n-C4H10 ↔ n-C4H8 + H2
3. i-C4H10 ↔ i-C4H8 + H2
4. C5H12 ↔ C5H10 + H2

Oligomerization/β-Scission [A]
5. 2 n-C4H8 ↔ C3H6 + C5H10
6. n-C4H8 + i-C4H8  ↔ C3H6 + C5H10
7. 2 i-C4H8 ↔ C3H6 + C5H10
8. n-C4H8 + C5H10 ↔ 3 C3H6

Protolytic Cracking [A]
9. 2 C3H6 + 3 H2 → 3 C2H6
10. n-C4H10 + H2 → C3H8 + CH4
11. i-C4H10 + H2 → C3H8 + CH4
12. C3H8 + H2 → C2H6 + CH4
13. C5H12 + H2 → C2H6 + C3H8

Isomerization [A]
14. n-C4H8 ↔ i-C4H8

Aromatization [A]
15. C3H6 + n-C4H8 ↔ C7H8 + 3 H2

[M] – metal sites; [A] – acid sites

CATALYST REGENERABILITY

 Coke on spent catalyst can be effectively removed with dilute (0.5-1%) O2 at 500 °C.

 Catalyst performance was maintained during five reaction cycles, which is equivalent to a lifetime of 2 years.

 Burn off coke in oxygen stream at low temperatures (~ 300 °C)

 Why 300 °C? Hydrogenolysis is a structure sensitive chemistry, higher temperatures alter the active site config./activity. 

 If proven to be successful, has the potential to significantly simplify the overall regeneration process by eliminating the need

for complex oxy-chlorination

 Questions to address: Reproducibility and optimal process conditions.

Classification: Internal Use

EFFECT OF TEMPERATURE AND WHSV ON ACTIVITY

1. Lower operational temperature can be used for hydrogenolysis (265 – 320 °C) than for hydrocracking (450 – 500 °C)

2. Higher ethane selectivities (~76wt% for hydrogenolysis vs ~ 50wt% for hydrocracking)

3. Ethane, propane and methane selectivities are independent of space velocity but vary significantly at high temperature.

Catalyst: IrPt(0.15,0.15wt%)/ZSM5, 103017-C4-01. Conditions: WHSV 4 hr-1. H2/HC = 2.5. Feed: 70% n-butane, 30% iso-butane.

Classification: Internal Use

CONFIDENTIAL

NATURE OF ACTIVE SITE

Small et. al., J. Am. Chem. Soc. 2011, 133, 3582-3591

Pt

Ir

Top view Side view Cross sectional
Hemispherical cuboctahedron morphology 

• Iridium core

• Surface Platinum atoms (low surface energy of Pt compared 

to Ir (2.489 J/m2 vs 3.048 J/m2)

Exposure to air at higher temperatures ~ 400 °C, results in the formation of large IrO2 crystallites which on subsequent reduction 

converts to large crystallites of iridium. The catalyst will then consist of a mixture of highly dispersed Pt or Pt-rich clusters and 

large crystallites of Ir. (Sinfelt et. al. J of catalysis 1979, 56 1 -11)

Ir remains anchored to the support and Pt precursor is mobile in 

an oxidizing environment. A mixed metal oxychloride results from 

the mobility of Pt during calcination. Bimetallic species result 

from the reduction of these oxychlorides. (Subramanian et. al. 

Appl. Catalysis 1991, 74, 65-81)

BUTANE TO ETHANE – PROGRAM UPDATE



2

Classification: Internal Use

UNLOCKING FEEDSTOCK FOR ETHYLENE PRODUCTION

CONFIDENTIAL

Few outlets for 
Butanes

Global supply 
increase

Poor ethylene 
production from 

Butane SC

Feedstock 
flexibility

Lack of Ethane 
Allocation 

(KSA)

Butane SC 
Reliability

Carbon 
Efficiency

Core advantages of Butane to Ethane Technology

 Lower Capex (Capex of C4 HC + C2 cracker lower than C4 cracker)

 Significant shift towards ethylene (SABIC’s main building block for growth)

 Likely to secure additional feedstock allocation

 Increased carbon efficiency to target olefins

 Low propylene production

Disadvantages of Butane to Ethane Technology

Field butane stream: 70% n-butane/30% i-butane



3

Classification: Internal Use

 KEY – Identifying which feedstocks have low 

carbon efficiencies to valuable chemicals

 Feedstocks, which have low carbon efficiencies 

in a steam cracker, are the most attractive for 

using Hydrocracking-type technologies

 The technology itself will always make some 

portion of methane

 Propane and Butane are the least carbon 

efficient feedstocks for a steam cracker

 Target feedstocks for optimization

CONFIDENTIAL

STEAM CRACKING TECHNOLOGY – CARBON EFFICIENCY



4

Classification: Internal Use

CONFIDENTIAL

TECHNOLOGY PLATFORM

Distribution Hub (1st Technology Rollout – Demo)

• Centralized facility distributing ethane/propane (1000 KTA butane processing)

• 738 KTA Ethane

• 109 KTA Propane (fill spare capacity at SADAF and SHARQ)

Integration with a new build ethane cracker

• New build cracker – customized integration would further reduced the cost 

Integration with on-purpose MTBE

• Elimination of isomerization unit

• Technology could be married to an existing facility or new build

U.S. Shale Market

• Shale gas production is often limited by the over production of butanes –
Converting these butanes would unlock further gas production

• Fluor is ready to put us in contact with a potential interested party

Classification: Internal Use

CONFIDENTIAL

BUSINESS CASE LAYOUT

Butane Conversion Unit Integrated with Cracker Stand-alone Distribution Hub

1) Where does this sit on ethylene production cost curve?

 Our goal isn’t to be the cheapest – not to displace 
ethane cracking

 Our goal is to be a medium cost production 
technology – Quartile 2/3 – and push out the high 
cost producers in Quartile 4

2) Where does it sit relative to butane SC?
 Technology to displace butane SC for ethylene 

production

 No other alternative option/comparison
 Other than “status quo” operation

 Increase ethylene production by filling assets
 Spare capacity
 Preference ethane over propane cracking
 Allocation cuts

Other potential synergies for technology:
 OTC, MTBE, Shale Gas

Classification: Internal Use

 Four adiabatic reactors in series. A temperature rise of 20C is targeted per reactor giving a total n-butane 
conversion of about 50 to 60% T-rise limited to keep safety margin.

 Catalyst deactivation is mitigated by increasing the inlet temperature of each reactor to maintain a 

consistent T of 20C

13

Classification: Internal Use

New startup procedure

• Startup time reduced from over 1 

week to 2 days

• No intermediate shutdowns due 

to high temperature

• No startup induced deactivation

CONFIDENTIAL

IMPROVED STARTUP STRATEGY

1) Start reaction under low C4:H2
ratio’s simultaneously

2) Gradually bring up C4 feed 
and continuously adjust 
temperatures to keep T<25C

Smoother, safer and more efficient startup procedure:
• Less sensitivity of reactor temperature to inlet temperature at 

low C4:H2 ratio 
• Less exposure of catalyst to C2 and C3 under non reacting 

conditions
• Decreased startup time

Classification: Internal Use

 1.5 month of continuous operation with for 

reactors at 6.2 kg/hr (WHSV = 2/hr)

 Total n-butane conversion of 50-60% 

 no noticeable i-C4 conversion

 Catalyst deactivation mitigated by 

increasing reactor temperature

 deactivation rate: on average 2C/week

 Ethane selectivity of 78.1 to 77.6%

 slow decrease with increasing reactor 

temperature: about 0.1%/week

 Improved startup procedure for increased 

safety and minimized catalyst deactivation 

 applicable to commercial scale

Butane to Ethane Technology Design

2 May 2019 
Presentation to SABIC



Classification: Internal Use

Fluor Collaboration Structure

1) Process design and buildup robust ISBL numbers (work product 
complete)
 Distribution Hub Demo (1000 KTA butane)

 Integrated Butane Conversion Unit w/ Ethane Cracker (2300 KTA butane) 
• 1500 KTA ethylene production

2) Capital cost study between different steam crackers (ethane, 50:50 
ethane/propane, butane)
 Numbers are based on Fluor projects and SK data

17



Classification: Internal Use

Basis of Design

♦ Conversion and Yields set Unit design
– Catalyst converts 100% nC4 and 15% iC4 while producing a mixture of 

Methane, Ethane and Propane.  Hydrogen is consumed.  Additional 
hydrogen is circulated to minimize coke formation.

– Reaction is initiated at about 250°C.  The actual temperature depends on 
the activity of the catalyst and the compensation of the reactants.  The 
temperature rise should not be allowed to exceed 20°C across any one 
bed, as the reaction runs away if the temperature rise exceeds ~30-40°C.

18



Classification: Internal Use

Basis of Design (cont)

– The products are a light hydrogen rich fuel gas, an ethane stream, a 
propane stream, and an isobutane stream.  The isobutane stream can be 
exported or converted to n-butane and recycled.

19



Classification: Internal Use

BFD for the Distribution HUB (1,000 KTA)

20

Designed to be self-sufficient in H2
 In actuality there might be H2 available for use in Jubail



Classification: Internal Use

BFD for Integrated Case (2,300 KTA)

21

Designed to deliver 1500 kta ethylene integrated with cracker



Classification: Internal Use

Unit Design

♦ Basis unit design is a feed section, a reaction section, followed by 
product compression and product separation.  Supporting units include a 
Steam Methane Reformer (SMR), a Pressure Swing Absorption (PSA) 
Unit and an Isomerization Unit.
– The feed section consists of a Feed Surge Drum, Pump, Vaporizer, and Charge Heater.  

No feed treatment is required based on the feed composition provided.

– The reactor section has several beds and inter-stage coolers to ensure a proper 
temperature rise across the reactor beds.

22



Classification: Internal Use

Unit Design (Cont)

– The Product Compressor increases the pressure from the reactor outlet of 100 psig 
minus the piping and exchanger pressure losses, to the Demethanizer inlet pressure of 
650 psig. 

– The product separation section consists of a cryogenic demethanizer to strip almost all 
of the methane and hydrogen from the ethane and heavier streams;  A Deethanizer to 
recover a high purity ethane steam;  and a Depropanizer to separate the propane and 
butane streams.

– The excess hydrogen from the Demethanizer Off-Gas can be recovered via a PSA unit 
to minimize the hydrogen required to be produced by the SMR.

23



Classification: Internal Use

Unit Design (Cont)

– The unreacted isobutane can be converted to ethane and propane products by 
recycling the isobutane through an Isomerization unit to convert the 97% 
isobutane to a 60%/40% normal butane and isobutane stream.  A De-
isobutanizer (DIB) tower could be added to reduce the quantity of isobutane
recycled; however the DIB tower has a cost – the isomerization unit would be 
larger and the recycle isobutane has the benefit of helping to control the 
temperature rise across reactor beds.  Therefore, only a single pass 
Isomerization Unit is needed.

24



Classification: Internal Use

Reactor Design – External Exchangers

25



Classification: Internal Use

Reactor PFD

26



Classification: Internal Use

Quench Media

– Air -- This implies air coolers for the external coolers, which at 250°C 
would beyond the allowable temperature for aluminum fins. 

– Cooling Water -- Cooling water is not normally used above 80°C, high 
pressure water can be used, except 300°C requires a design pressure in 
excess of 1200 psig.

– Steam Generation – 300# Steam can be generated at these conditions, 
however there is no demand for the medium pressure steam.

27



Classification: Internal Use

Quench Media (cont.)

– Hot Oil  -- at 200°C to 300°C several commercial hot oils are available in 
the temperature range, and there may be one that is economical, 
however for the basis of this study they were not considered, for the 
following reasons:

• The high cost of the Hot Oil

• The cost of storing another commodity 

• The replacement cost of the Hot Oil as it degrades

– Molten Salt – excessive cost for this temperature range.

28



Classification: Internal Use

Quench Media (cont.)

– Feed – This was the selected option for the following reasons:
• The feed is always available, at no additional purchasing or storage cost.

• The feed is stable at these temperatures, no olefins or di-olefins

• The cost is for the additional capacity of the feed and vaporization systems and the 
condensing system to recover the quench material and return it to the Feed Surge 
Drum.

29



Classification: Internal Use

Estimating Methodology

♦ Butane Hydrocracker 

– ISBL – Class 4 type equipment factor type estimate utilizing Aspen Capital Cost 
Estimator CCETM for an assumed Jubail Saudi Arabia location. Estimate accuracy 
+30%/-30%. 

– Overall – Approximately 90% of mechanical equipment cost was capacity ratio from 
recent vendor quote. Construction labor rates and productivity based on current market 
data. 

♦ SMR & Isomerization 

– ISBL – Class 5 capacity factor type estimates from Fluor historical data for similar type 
units with an estimate accuracy of +40%/-40%. 

♦ OSBL

– Provision of 35% of ISBL costs allowed for utilities and offsites for all cases.

TECHNOLOGIES INVESTIGATED FOR BUTANE TO ETHANE CONVERSION

HydrogenolysisHydrocracking

1. Bifunctional catalysis (metallic + acid sites)

2. Oligomerization step  complex product slate (C5+)

3. Potential to tune C2/C3 product ratio

1. Monofunctional catalysis (metallic sites)

2. C-C lysis  Clean product slate (C1-C3)

3. Potential to maximize C2 production

Classification: Internal Use

EFFECT OF TEMPERATURE AND WHSV ON ACTIVITY

1. Lower operational temperature can be used for hydrogenolysis (265 – 320 °C) than for hydrocracking (450 – 500 °C)

2. Higher ethane selectivities (~76wt% for hydrogenolysis vs ~ 50wt% for hydrocracking)

3. Ethane, propane and methane selectivities are independent of space velocity but vary significantly at high temperature.

Catalyst: IrPt(0.15,0.15wt%)/ZSM5, 103017-C4-01. Conditions: WHSV 4 hr-1. H2/HC = 2.5. Feed: 70% n-butane, 30% iso-butane.

Classification: Internal Use

Catalyst innovation within the team provided the starting 
point for a “best in class” catalyst:

 ZSM-5 support optimized to lowest Al content

 DOE performed to optimize metal (Pt-Ir) content

 Patent application filed

CONFIDENTIAL

Catalyst Formulation: (0.3,0.3)wt%IrPt/ZSM-5 (Si/Al = 140)

Optimal reaction parameters per DOE: WHSV = 1/hr, P = 50-100 psig, T = 275°C, H2/HC = 2-2.5

Reactor performance studies revealed that, under specific sets 
of operating parameters, a reactive separation occurs:

 @300˚C, XnC4 = 100 %, XiC4 = 10 % 

 Product selectivities (mol%) : C2 = 76%, C1 = 15%, C3 = 9%

Deactivation/Regeneration: Work in progress

Possible deactivation routes:

 Carbon deposition: Mechanism similar to green oil (C8-C30 

linear hydrocarbons) formation during acetylene 

hydrogenation

Unperturbed product distribution hints at the non accessibility of active sites resulting from carbon deposition as the potential 

deactivation mechanism

Potential route to deactivation: Carbon deposition

 Metal site sintering (unlikely at the temperatures of interest)

 Phase segregation: Changes in Pt-Ir interactions (unlikely as 

it would result in a change in product distribution)



44

Classification: Internal Use

CONFIDENTIAL

DEACTIVATION MECHANISM

Deactivation/Regeneration: Work in progress

Potential deactivation route:

 Carbon deposition: Mechanism similar to green oil (C8-C30 

linear hydrocarbons) formation during acetylene 

hydrogenation

Two types of coke species reported

1. Green oil: C4H6 (precursor), saturated C8-C25 linear 

hydrocarbons

2. Unsaturated HC intermediates strongly adsorbed on active 

sites making them inaccessible

Zheng et. al., Chem. Eng. Technol. 2016, 39, No. 5, 865-873



45

Classification: Internal Use

CONFIDENTIAL

REGENERATION STRATEGIES

Zheng et. al., Chem. Eng. Technol. 2016, 39, No. 5, 865-873

1. Hydrogen stripping: Helps with the removal of the strongly 

bound unsaturated carbonaceous deposits on metal sites. 

2. Low temperature oxidation: Burns coke and eliminates the 

complex oxychlorination step to re-disperse metal sites.

3. Oxychlorination (High temperature oxidation): Re-disperse 

metal if high temperature oxidation required

Catalyst replacement: Fallback strategy

Working on three regeneration strategies to combat deactivation by coke deposition

 Treating the spent catalyst with H2 rich stream. Widely employed in hydrocarbon based processes.

 Alters the properties of residual carbonaceous deposits through hydrogenation, increasing the mobility of coke (desorption).

Classification: Internal Use

 Burn off coke in oxygen stream at low temperatures (~ 300 °C)

 Recent data from last week – Will investigate further

Proof of concept

LATEST BREAKING DATA! – LOW TEMPERATURE OXIDATION 

 Preliminary studies showed a positive effect of low temperature oxidation on catalyst activity.

 Questions to address: Reproducibility, optimal process conditions, tailor catalyst pretreatment.

Classification: Internal Use

 Burning off coke in an oxygen stream results in a thorough removal of carbon, but may cause metal agglomeration.

 Metal agglomeration would require an oxychlorination step to re-disperse the metal sites post oxidation.

Proof of concept

• Agglomerated catalyst: Due to a lack of spent catalyst, calcined a fresh catalyst at 550 °C for 4 h to agglomerate metal sites

Classification: Internal Use

IrPt–ZSM5, 100 psig, H2/C4H10 = 2.5, n-C4H10/i-C4H10 = 7/3. WHSV varied to keep n-butane conversion below 50%. CONFIDENTIAL

DEACTIVATION MODEL OF BUTANES HYDROGENOLYSIS

 In the temperature window of 275 – 325 °C, butanes hydrogenolysis appears to have negative apparent activation energy on 
the Ir-Pt catalyst, which is likely due to strong adsorption of reaction intermediates.

 Numeric expression of deactivation rate is being developed.

kr: reaction rate constant
Kr,0: reaction rate constant at t = 0
t: time
Θ(t): normalized amount of active site *, Θt=0 = 1

kd: deactivation rate constant
α: reaction order with respect to Θ

Ad: pre-exponential factor of deactivation rate constant
Pi: Partial pressure/surface concentration of compound i
βi: Pressure dependency of compound i
T: temperature
R: ideal gas constant
Ea,d: activation energy of deactivation

Classification: Internal Use

BUTANES HYDROCRACKING CATALYST

 Rework of bifunctional catalyst from mild hydrocracking project

• 0.3 wt.% Pt on H-ZSM-5 w/ Al2O3 binder, Si/Al = 15, multiple batches from Zeolyst

 Process conditions optimized for hydrocracking of mixed butanes feed

• Low space velocity, high temperature

 Catalyst scaled up to 1 MT

• Consistent performance with in house made catalyst and good reproducibility

CATALYST LIFETIME AND REGENERABILITY

 Maintained a constant ethane selectivity for ~ 6 months by incremental temperature (~0.4°C/day).

 Spent catalyst can be regenerated with dilute (0.5-1%) O2 at 500 °C.

 Catalyst performance was maintained in five reaction cycles, equivalent to a lifetime of 2 years

4

Classification: Internal Use

Hydrocracking catalyst system (initial system 2016)

 Ready for 2nd Stage Pilot or Skid unit (Demo Unit)

 Highly robust system in terms of both catalyst lifetime and regeneration cycles

 Indiscriminately converts both n-butane and isobutane

 Flexible ethane/propane product distribution depending reaction conditions

 Green Field design integrating ethane furnaces and a PDH reactor with common separations (High 

Chemical efficiency)

 Initial piloting effort at SwRI proved safe operation and technology worked

 Passed catalyst scaling requirements – 1 MT of catalyst made at Zeolyst

 Ideal for Saudi Kayan Feed Transformation Project

CONFIDENTIAL

HYDROCRACKING CATALYST SYSTEMS



5

Classification: Internal Use

Hydrogenolysis catalyst system

 Currently piloting at STC-Geleen (Pilot needed at least until end of 2020)

 Currently understanding catalyst lifetime and regeneration in more detail

 Pt-Ir/ZSM-5 (SAR = 280)

 Highly selective towards ethane (75 – 78 wt%)

 Preferentially converts n-butane (couple with isobutane isomerization reactor for full conversion)

 Combining technology with Ethane Cracker to give a low CAPEX alternative to a butane steam cracker -

Giving a product slate similar to that of an ethane cracker (high ethylene)

CONFIDENTIAL

HYDROGENOLYSIS CATALYST SYSTEM



6

Classification: Internal Use

 Capital cost study between different steam crackers (ethane, 50:50 ethane/propane, butane)

• Numbers are based on Fluor projects and SK data

 Process design and buildup robust ISBL numbers (work product complete)

• 1500 KTA ethylene production (common comparison for all cases)

CONFIDENTIAL

PRE-PDP COLLABORATION WITH FLUOR

Butane to Ethane + 
Ethane Cracker

Butane Steam Cracker

Butanes Feed (KTA) 2300 3641

Ethylene Production (KTA) 1500 1500

Total ISBL ($MM) $1,935 $2,279

 Compared to the Butane Steam Cracker, at the same ethylene production:

• The Integrated Cracker has 15% lower cracker ISBL

• The Integrated Cracker uses 37% less butanes feed to obtain an equivalent ethylene production

 Downstream processing units after the cracker, i.e. PE, PP, PC, etc., have not yet been taken into account

• Due to it’s wide complex product slate the butane cracker will have an even higher total investment cost 



7

Classification: Internal Use

 The butane to ethane technology provides the opportunity to transform an unconventional feedstock into a 

value chemical feedstock that SABIC is short on.

 Unlocking ethane feedstock through this technology gives SABIC the opportunity to invest in growth projects 

in KSA that produce a familiar product slate that is core to SABIC.

 Using the butane to ethane technology and investing in an ethane cracker versus a butane cracker would 

result in a significant CAPEX savings, especially, when you include the investment needed for downstream 

chemicals processes.

 On a common basis of a world scale cracker, i.e. 1500 KTA ethylene, an ethane cracker integrated with the 

butane to ethane technology would use 37% less butanes compared to a butane cracker.

 Technology would have a good fit with an OTC type concept, as OTC produces a lot of C4s.

CONFIDENTIAL

STC-GELEEN PILOTING



13

Classification: Internal Use

 Four adiabatic reactors in series. For the current run, we are assessing the deactivation profile at various H2 to 

C4 ratios as guided by our kinetic & deactivation model. 

 Catalyst deactivation is mitigated by increasing the inlet temperature of each reactor to maintain a consistent 

desired T and conversion.

CONFIDENTIAL

CURRENT STATUS

 High ethane selectivity: 74-78 w% depending on 
conditions and catalyst age

 Potential increase in process efficiency demonstrated 
(improved catalyst utilization and H2 usage)

 Catalyst cycle: >> 6 months demonstrated

16

Classification: Internal Use

Operation at higher WHSV (23 /hr) and reduced H2 ratio with interstage H2 dosing resulted in:

 Increased catalyst utilization (consistent with our models)

 Reduced H2 usage

Changes in process characteristics:

 Reduced reactor temperatures

 Increased reactor T (2328C)

 Slightly reduced C2 selectivity

17

Classification: Internal Use

 Improved start-up procedures along with optimization of heating controls have resulted in smooth and safe 

pilot plan operation.

 Optimization of process parameters, consistent with our models, has resulted in overall improved process 

efficiency through 1) reduced deactivation rate, 2) increased space velocity, and 3) reduced H2 usage.  

 The ethane selectivity ranges from 74–78 wt% depending on process conditions and catalyst age.

 Our estimates for catalyst cycle length are well over 6 months.

 The faster deactivation for reactor 1 has been identified to be the result of trace sulfur impurities (<1 ppm) 

in the feeds.  A sulfur guard bed will be installed upstream of the catalyst for the next trail run.

 One batch of catalyst (reactor 2) has seen over 200 days of operation and one regeneration cycle – the 

performance is still good with no issues.

 Regeneration procedure needs further improvement and optimization. Pilot catalyst samples are being 

examined and laboratory studies are in progress to optimize regeneration procedure

CONFIDENTIAL

SUMMARY AND OUTLOOK

HYDROGENOLYSIS CATALYST 

DEVELOPMENT



19

Classification: Internal Use

Catalyst innovation within the team provided the starting 
point for a “best in class” catalyst:

 ZSM-5 support optimized to lowest Al content

 DOE performed to optimize metal (Pt-Ir) content

 Patent application filed

CONFIDENTIAL

Catalyst Formulation: (0.3,0.3)wt%IrPt/ZSM-5 (Si/Al = 140)

Optimal reaction parameters per DOE: WHSV = 1-4/hr, P = 50-100 psig, T = 275°C, H2/HC = 2-2.5

Reactor performance studies revealed that, under specific sets 
of operating parameters, a reactive separation occurs:

 @300˚C, XnC4 = 100 %, XiC4 = 10 % 

 Product selectivities (mol%) : C2 = 76%, C1 = 15%, C3 = 9%

21

Classification: Internal Use

NEXT STEPS

Catalyst Characterization with Ayman Karim Group – Virginia Tech

 XAFS to examine the evolution of the Pt-Ir interaction in freshly calcined, spent, and agglomerated catalysts

 TEM to analyze the particle size distribution 

 H2 chemisorption to measure dispersion

 Test the use of a sulfur guard bed upstream of the catalyst to capture sulfur components in feed

 Optimize regeneration protocol at STC-H and perform regeneration at Pilot

Catalyst Deactivation and Regeneration Studies

 Coke analysis is ongoing at STC-H 

 Residual coke analysis shows <0.5% carbon deposition after six months on-stream (as measured by NDIR)

 A novel oxidative regeneration procedure has been discovered by the team (more details in later slides)

(3) i-C4H10 + H2 → C3H8 + CH4
(4) C3H8 + H2 → C2H6 + CH4
(5) C2H6 + H2 → 2CH4
(6) n-C4H10 ↔ i-C4H10

Needs careful temperature control 
to avoid thermal runaway

Classification: Internal Use

OPTIMIZATION OF REACTOR CONDITIONS

 Progressive H2 injection (case2) mitigates 
deactivation in the first reactor, while 
simultaneously maintaining a high C2 selectivity.

 The C2 selectivity increases with hydrogen 
addition.

 At low H2/C4 ratio, higher temperatures are 
required in latter reactors for similar conversions.



27

PROCESS OPTIMIZATION FROM 

DEACTIVATION MODEL



28

Classification: Internal Use

THE DEACTIVATION CHALLENGES

Conventional Approach

• Catalyst deactivation is modeled by an empirical formula

• Deactivation becomes faster as temperature rises

• Increasing H2 partial pressure mitigates metal catalyst 
deactivation in hydrocarbon processing

Goals

→ Model catalyst deactivation based on a theory

→ Explain the temperature insensitivity

→ Interpret the non-monotonic trend of deactivation rate with 
partial-pressure changes

 Alkane hydrogenolysis is known to have relatively fast catalyst deactivation

 Excessive H2 only brings marginal mitigation on deactivation and increases separation cost



29

• Deactivation rate is modeled using a Langmuir-Hinshelwood
rate expression; the RDS involves a hydrocarbon surface species and an 
open site

• The model allows for the species involved in the RDS to be different from 
the MASI.

• Develop novel way to incorporate deactivation into a Langmuir-
Hinshelwood model by introducing σ𝜽𝒊 = 𝚯 𝐭 , in which Θ is the 
normalized number of active sites as a function of time

• All the hydrocarbon species contribute to deactivation.

Regeneration effects

 Complete activity recovered

 Stable active sites with a slowed down 

deactivation after regeneration

 Effect is repeatable over multiple cycles

Proposed mechanism

1. Burns trace carbon on surface (<0.5wt%)

2. Rearranges Pt-Ir atoms in the active site as 

oxygen is expected to pull Ir to the surface. 

3. Treating the oxidized sites with 

hydrocarbon (butane) results in 

stabilization of nanoparticles

REFERENCE:

PEP Report 29H SEC 5 (AP)

Process Economics 11-09-2019

2019 Q1 data

© IHS 2019

Common carrier pipeline ethane is filtered, dried, and de-pressured from 1000 psia to 50 psia in a turbogenerator. It is then 

passed through a UOP silver coated mol sieve bed for removal of residual mercury. The feed is combined with recycle 

ethane and dilution steam, then pre-heated and cracked in 8 dual cell pyrolysis furnaces. The cracked gas is quickly 

quenched in transfer line exchangers, and further cooled in exchangers to produce dilution steam. The cooled cracked gas 

is directly quenched with scrubbing water, with the quenched water steam stripped before being sent to wastewater 

treatment. Recovered oil in the quench drum upper layer is filtered, coalesced, and sold as C3+ salable product. Cracked 

gas is re-pressured to 450 psia in a 4-stage centrifugal compressor driven by a gas turbine. The 3rd stage discharge is caustic 

scrubbed, chilled using propylene and fed to a front end de-ethanizer that hydrogenates acetylene using CDHYDROTM 

reactive distillation. The overhead is fed to the 4th stage compressor inlet, while the bottoms is recovered as C3+ salable 

product. The 4th stage discharge stream is dried, chilled using ethylene, and fed to a de-methanizer. Hydrogen is purified 

from de-methanizer overhead using UOP PolyBed PSA mol sieve technology, with the raffinate de-pressured using a 

turbogenerator, and used as furnace fuel gas. De-methanizer bottoms is fed to an ethylene splitter operating on vapor 

recompression. Splitter overhead is high purity ethylene product, while the bottoms product stream is recycled to the 

cracking furnaces as an ethane rich cracking feed stream.

Cost of raw material, by-product and utilities Overall cost structure

Unit Cost Unit Consumption Capacity

per TONNE (THOUSAND TONNE / year)

The process economics for the CTR process are similar to the high pressure tubular process (LDPE production by a high-

pressure tubular process similar to Exxonmobil Process) evaluated in the referenced PEP Report, except for the lower 

polymerization pressure, Do/Di, and ethylene conversion per pass, 38% instead of 40%. In addition, instead of using a low-

pressure quench to cool the reactor effluent downstream of the letdown valve, a cooler is used. The process description is 

similar to the description except for the process changes noted.

8

Classification: Internal Use

 The Butane to Ethane technology has the potential to increase bottom line EBITDA contribution by 

providing highly valued ethane feedstock to affiliates operating below capacity.  

 The technology can also have a positive impact on ethylene production by feeding ethane instead 

of propane to affiliates.

 Business case analysis shows a minimum sized Ethane Distribution Hub producing approximately 

150-170 KTA of ethane will have a positive financial impact. (3 crackers each @ 97% operating rate)

 CAPEX numbers are conservatively estimated.  

 E&PM group used 100% factor for OSBL estimation.

 SMR is unlikely to be needed in Jubail region with H2 from crackers (~20% of CAPEX)

 The business case is most sensitive to 1) butane price, 2) available ethane capacity, and 3) LDPE 

price.

 The business case is insensitive to the ethane price.

 The technology development is progressing well in the piloting stage.

Classification: Internal Use

Operation at higher WHSV (23 /hr) and reduced H2 ratio with interstage H2 dosing resulted in:

 Increased catalyst utilization (consistent with our models)

 Reduced H2 usage

Changes in process characteristics:

 Reduced reactor temperatures

 Slightly reduced C2 selectivity

16

Classification: Internal Use

 Improved start-up procedures along with optimization of heating controls have resulted in smooth and safe 

pilot plan operation.

 Optimization of process parameters, consistent with our models, has resulted in overall improved process 

efficiency through 1) reduced deactivation rate, 2) increased space velocity, and 3) reduced H2 usage.  

 The ethane selectivity ranges from 74–78 wt% depending on process conditions and catalyst age.

 Our estimates for catalyst cycle length are well over 6 months.

 The faster deactivation for reactor 1 has been identified to be the result of trace sulfur impurities (<1 ppm) 

in the feeds.  A sulfur guard bed will be installed upstream of the catalyst for the next trail run.

 One batch of catalyst (reactor 2) has seen over 200 days of operation and one regeneration cycle – the 

performance is still good with no issues.

 Regeneration procedure needs further improvement and optimization. Pilot catalyst samples are being 

examined and laboratory studies are in progress to optimize regeneration procedure

CONFIDENTIAL

SUMMARY AND OUTLOOK

Classification: Internal Use

Catalyst innovation within the team provided the starting 
point for a “best in class” catalyst:

 ZSM-5 support optimized to lowest Al content

 DOE performed to optimize metal (Pt-Ir) content

 Patent application filed

CONFIDENTIAL

Catalyst Formulation: (0.3,0.3)wt%IrPt/ZSM-5 (Si/Al = 140)

Optimal reaction parameters per DOE: WHSV = 1-4/hr, P = 50-100 psig, T = 275°C, H2/HC = 2-2.5

Reactor performance studies revealed that, under specific sets 
of operating parameters, a reactive separation occurs:

 @300˚C, XnC4 = 100 %, XiC4 = 10 % 

 Product selectivities (mol%) : C2 = 76%, C1 = 15%, C3 = 9%

NEXT STEPS

Catalyst Characterization with Ayman Karim Group – Virginia Tech

 XAFS to examine the evolution of the Pt-Ir interaction in freshly calcined, spent, and agglomerated catalysts

 TEM to analyze the particle size distribution 

 H2 chemisorption to measure dispersion

 Optimize regeneration protocol at STC-H and perform regeneration at Pilot

Catalyst Deactivation and Regeneration Studies

 Coke analysis is ongoing at STC-H 

 Residual coke analysis shows <0.5% carbon deposition after six months on-stream (as measured by NDIR)

 A novel oxidative regeneration procedure has been discovered by the team (more details in later slides)

Global reactions

(1) n-C4H10 + H2 → 2C2H6
(2) n-C4H10 + H2 → CH4 + C3H8
(3) i-C4H10 + H2 → C3H8 + CH4
(4) C3H8 + H2 → C2H6 + CH4
(5) C2H6 + H2 → 2CH4
(6) n-C4H10 ↔ i-C4H10

Exothermic reactions

Needs careful temperature control 
to avoid thermal runaway

25

Classification: Internal Use

OPTIMIZATION OF REACTOR CONDITIONS

 Progressive H2 injection (case2) mitigates 
deactivation in the first reactor, while 
simultaneously maintaining a high C2 selectivity.

 The C2 selectivity increases with hydrogen 
addition.

 At low H2/C4 ratio, higher temperatures are 
required in latter reactors for similar conversions.



26

PROCESS OPTIMIZATION FROM 

DEACTIVATION MODEL



27

Classification: Internal Use

THE DEACTIVATION CHALLENGES

Conventional Approach

• Catalyst deactivation is modeled by an empirical formula

• Deactivation becomes faster as temperature rises

• Increasing H2 partial pressure mitigates metal catalyst 
deactivation in hydrocarbon processing

Goals

→ Model catalyst deactivation based on a theory

→ Explain the temperature insensitivity

→ Interpret the non-monotonic trend of deactivation rate with 
partial-pressure changes

 Alkane hydrogenolysis is known to have relatively fast catalyst deactivation

 Excessive H2 only brings marginal mitigation on deactivation and increases separation cost



28

Classification: Internal Use

• Deactivation rate is modeled using a Langmuir-Hinshelwood
rate expression; the RDS involves a hydrocarbon surface species and an 
open site

• The model allows for the species involved in the RDS to be different from 
the MASI.

• Develop novel way to incorporate deactivation into a Langmuir-
Hinshelwood model by introducing σ𝜽𝒊 = 𝚯 𝐭 , in which Θ is the 
normalized number of active sites as a function of time

• All the hydrocarbon species contribute to deactivation.

 A Langmuir-Hinshelwood deactivation model was derived from 
reasonably hypothesized surface reactions.

 Hydrogen-deficient conditions favor catalyst stability.
Significantly increased cat. lifetime (right & bottom-middle figures)

conditions are overlapping at low pressure low H2.

20wt% Alumina binder (SAR = 280)

adsorption

Regeneration protocol

CONFIDENTIAL

OXIDATIVE REGENERATION WITH HYDROCARBON DOSING

Reaction 
temp.

300 °C

2.5 °C/min

H2, 100 psigN2N2 10% O2

5 min

2 hr2 hr

Reaction 

temp.
HC

5 

min

5 

min

Regeneration effects

 Complete activity recovered

 Stable active sites with a slowed down 

deactivation after regeneration

 Effect is repeatable over multiple cycles

Proposed mechanism

1. Burns trace carbon on surface (<0.5wt%)

2. Rearranges Pt-Ir atoms in the active site as 

oxygen is expected to pull Ir to the surface. 

3. Treating the oxidized sites with 

hydrocarbon (butane) results in 

stabilization of nanoparticles

changes

dosing is critical to recover the activity and 

achieve stable active sites (1st in art).

• The regeneration effect is reproducible over 

multiple cycles

Classification: Internal Use

 Four adiabatic reactors in series. For the current run, we are assessing the deactivation profile at various H2 to 

C4 ratios as guided by our kinetic & deactivation model. 

 Catalyst deactivation is mitigated by increasing the inlet temperature of each reactor to maintain a consistent 

desired T and conversion.

CONFIDENTIAL

CURRENT STATUS

 High ethane selectivity: 74-78 w% depending on 
conditions and catalyst age

 Potential increase in process efficiency demonstrated 
(improved catalyst utilization and H2 usage)

 Catalyst cycle: >> 6 months demonstrated

12

Classification: Internal Use

Operation at higher WHSV (23 /hr) and reduced H2 ratio with interstage H2 dosing resulted in:

 Increased catalyst utilization (consistent with our models)

 Reduced H2 usage

Changes in process characteristics:

 Reduced reactor temperatures

 Increased reactor T (2328C)

 Slightly reduced C2 selectivity

CONFIDENTIAL

13

Classification: Internal Use

 Improved start-up procedures along with optimization of heating controls have resulted in smooth and safe 

pilot plan operation.

 Optimization of process parameters, consistent with our models, has resulted in overall improved process 

efficiency through 1) reduced deactivation rate, 2) increased space velocity, and 3) reduced H2 usage.  

 The ethane selectivity ranges from 74–78 wt% depending on process conditions and catalyst age.

 Our estimates for catalyst cycle length are well over 6 months.

 The faster deactivation for reactor 1 has been identified to be the result of trace sulfur impurities (<1 ppm) 

in the feeds.  A sulfur guard bed will be installed upstream of the catalyst for the next trail run.

 One batch of catalyst (reactor 2) has seen over 200 days of operation and one regeneration cycle – the 

performance is still good with no issues.

 Regeneration procedure needs further improvement and optimization. Pilot catalyst samples are being 

examined and laboratory studies are in progress to optimize regeneration procedure

CONFIDENTIAL

SUMMARY AND OUTLOOK

HYDROGENOLYSIS CATALYST 

DEVELOPMENT



15

Classification: Internal Use

Catalyst innovation within the team provided the starting 
point for a “best in class” catalyst:

 ZSM-5 support optimized to lowest Al content

 DOE performed to optimize metal (Pt-Ir) content

 Patent application filed

CONFIDENTIAL

Catalyst Formulation: (0.3,0.3)wt%IrPt/ZSM-5 (Si/Al = 140)

Optimal reaction parameters per DOE: WHSV = 1-4/hr, P = 50-100 psig, T = 275°C, H2/HC = 2-2.5

Reactor performance studies revealed that, under specific sets 
of operating parameters, a reactive separation occurs:

 @300˚C, XnC4 = 100 %, XiC4 = 10 % 

 Product selectivities (mol%) : C2 = 76%, C1 = 15%, C3 = 9%

 Residual coke analysis shows <0.5% carbon deposition after six months on-stream (as measured by NDIR)

 A novel oxidative regeneration procedure has been discovered by the team (more details in later slides)

Global reactions

(4) C3H8 + H2 → C2H6 + CH4
(5) C2H6 + H2 → 2CH4
(6) n-C4H10 ↔ i-C4H10

Exothermic reactions

Needs careful temperature control 
to avoid thermal runaway

22

Classification: Internal Use

OPTIMIZATION OF REACTOR CONDITIONS

 Progressive H2 injection (case2) mitigates 
deactivation in the first reactor, while 
simultaneously maintaining a high C2 selectivity.

 The C2 selectivity increases with hydrogen 
addition.

 At low H2/C4 ratio, higher temperatures are 
required in latter reactors for similar conversions.



23

PROCESS OPTIMIZATION FROM 

DEACTIVATION MODEL



24

Classification: Internal Use

THE DEACTIVATION CHALLENGES

Conventional Approach

• Catalyst deactivation is modeled by an empirical formula

• Deactivation becomes faster as temperature rises

• Increasing H2 partial pressure mitigates metal catalyst 
deactivation in hydrocarbon processing

Goals

→ Model catalyst deactivation based on a theory

→ Explain the temperature insensitivity

→ Interpret the non-monotonic trend of deactivation rate with 
partial-pressure changes

 Alkane hydrogenolysis is known to have relatively fast catalyst deactivation

 Excessive H2 only brings marginal mitigation on deactivation and increases separation cost



25

Classification: Internal Use

𝛽+

• Deactivation rate is modeled using a Langmuir-Hinshelwood
rate expression; the RDS involves a hydrocarbon surface species and an 
open site

• The model allows for the species involved in the RDS to be different from 
the MASI.

• Develop novel way to incorporate deactivation into a Langmuir-
Hinshelwood model by introducing σ𝜽𝒊 = 𝚯 𝐭 , in which Θ is the 
normalized number of active sites as a function of time

• All the hydrocarbon species contribute to deactivation.

Classification: Internal Use

EXPERIMENTS VS MODELING

T: 255 – 325 °C, P: 50 - 160 psig, H2/HC: 1 – 10, WHSV = 3 - 200 h
-1, HC conversion < 30%; Feed: ethane, propane, isobutane, butane and combinations hereof

 Excellent alignment between model and lab data; excellent fitting quality

Reaction

 A Langmuir-Hinshelwood deactivation model was derived from 
reasonably hypothesized surface reactions.

 Hydrogen-deficient conditions favor catalyst stability.
Significantly increased cat. lifetime (right & bottom-middle figures)

 Deactivation rate can be temperature insensitive (bottom-left figure).

 Slow deactivation (bottom middle) and fast reaction (bottom right) 
conditions are overlapping at low pressure low H2.

Ability to reduce the reactor size

 Novel discovery – ID filed

Classification: Internal Use

CONFIDENTIAL

CATALYST CHARACTERIZATION

* Small et. al., J. Am. Chem. Soc. 2011, 133, 3582-3591

Catalyst: Ir(0.3 wt%) Pt (0.3 wt%) ZSM5 extrudates with 

20wt% Alumina binder (SAR = 280)

Fresh catalyst metal dispersion: ~60% assuming 1:1 H/M 

adsorption

Average particle size: ~ 1.4 nm (TEM images on JEOL 

JEM2100 based on 56 particles)

Classification: Internal Use

Regeneration protocol

CONFIDENTIAL

OXIDATIVE REGENERATION WITH HYDROCARBON DOSING

Reaction 
temp.

300 °C

2.5 °C/min

H2, 100 psigN2N2 10% O2

5 min

2 hr2 hr

Reaction 

temp.
HC

5 

min

5 

min

Regeneration effects

 Complete activity recovered

 Stable active sites with a slowed down 

deactivation after regeneration

 Effect is repeatable over multiple cycles

Proposed mechanism

1. Burns trace carbon on surface (<0.5wt%)

2. Rearranges Pt-Ir atoms in the active site as 

oxygen is expected to pull Ir to the surface. 

3. Treating the oxidized sites with 

hydrocarbon (butane) results in 

stabilization of nanoparticles

Ease of scalability

 The proposed protocol is easy to accomplish 

in commercial plants

 All the steps involved can be carried out in 

situ

 Relatively small required temperature 

changes

Novel discovery: Our studies revealed that HC 

dosing is critical to recover the activity and 

achieve stable active sites (1st in art).

• The regeneration effect is reproducible over 

multiple cycles

No. ‹#›


MT catalyst platform In ONE page
In stage 3
Started as platform project: 3 spin-off projects so far
	MT precipitation kinetics  new collaboration with ETH Zurich
	MT4/6+donor (gate 4 meeting, 12/2014)
	MT catalyst modification for reduced formation of waxes (in stage 3, 09/2014)

Business case rests on stepwise introduction of MT8.5 catalyst to bimodal plants in Yansab (2015) and Saudi-Kayan (2019), both with NPC of 400 PE kt/a


MT8.5 is capable to produce the whole polymer portfolio
	pipe (PE100, RC, LS) grades are produced successfully at LD6
	blow molding and injection molding grades have been commercialized
	HAV grades (PE100+, high abrasion resistant) under development
	ACP grades under development

Future opportunities:
Optimization of the catalyst recipe to the needs of new polymer grades in close collaboration with material development


No. ‹#›


Legal consideration and Product stewardship 
No legal limitations within the MT catalyst platform 
(FTO: N. Friederichs, M. Schmeetz, 2010-272)

No patent protection  company secret

Use of 1,2-diethers during HDPE polymerization is possible for MT
Two patents filed regarding the use of 1,2-diethers together with MT and MTX

No product stewardship concerns for MT-like catalysts
Food approval is valid for polymers produced using this catalyst.

The application of DMB as donor will yield polymer products within the current food approval specifications.
Future donor compounds will be assessed by product stewardship (M. Bosma).

SABIC CONFIDENTIAL


  Highlights:

Catalyst with narrow MWD and improved polymer powder morphology found

Donor compounds may be added at any stage of polymerization process and still improve the catalyst


  Lowlights:
Alteration of catalyst starting materials changes particle size 








 Priorities for Next Period:

Quantify advantage of narrow MWD for a commercial grade (Q4)
High throughput screening to find donor compounds that offer improved comonomer incorporation (in progress)



 Management Support Required:

Decision, where to commercially produce MT
Pilot plant needed, especially for larger quantities of testing materials

No. ‹#›


NEW GENERATION OF F3-CATALYST
	Surface Area	700 m2/g
	Pore Volume	1.7 ml/g
	Pore Diameter	120 Aº
	A.P.S	33 µm

H302F Silica-AGC, Japan

Superior spherical morphology with 20 %  increase in  resin bulk density & Upper fluidized bulk density (Expected Bed Wt increase: 100 to 120 T). Rx Drop size expected to increase, causing production rate increase from 44 T/h to 52 T/h.
Enhanced 1-hexene co-monomer incorporation by no less than 23 % since high level of LCB can be observed. 
Superior physical-mechanical properties (ESCR exceeded Slurry by 20% in HIC grade) due to unique silica features.    
The new silica supports from A.G.C, Japan with superior physical properties of ultra high surface area, increased pore volume and unique spherical morphology were utilized for the new SABIC F3 Cat generation.



No. ‹#›


Scaled up to 2 kg for Pilot Plant Trial 



ENHANCED PROPERTIES
The newly modified F3-catalyst based on AGC, Japanese silica support of superior morphology consists of identical spherical primary particles creating uniform & symmetrical pore structure. In turns this uniformity in the micro & macro structure of the silica support gives uniformity in the produced polymer resin (reducing irregular & non-uniform polymer lamella structure) which leads to the enhancement in the physical and mechanical properties of the final polymer product.  



H302F Silica support by AGC, Japan                                                                                                955W Silica by Grace



Surface Pores
H302F
Inner Pores
H302F

Capability to produce all HDPE grades from 1 FI to 12 FI of high density (0.956 to 0.945) in Gas Phase process at high bed temp (High prod rate) for the first time in SABIC KSA.

Strength/Weakness
SABIC CONFIDENTIAL


  Strength:

1. Producing Drum & IBC grades at high bed temp
2. High catalyst activity with superior morphology 
3. Increased resin bulk density for higher PY
4. Superior mechanical properties (ESCR & Izod)
5. C6 incorporation increased by more than 26%. 

  Weaknesses:

1. Silica support of high cost 10 SR of std catalyst/Ton      HDPE vs. 12.5 SR for new F3/Ton HDPE.
2. Single source (A.G.C, Japan)

No. ‹#›


Preliminary Technical Assessment for Commercial the Trial
Conclusion: It is highly recommend to conduct at least the trial run at Yanpet since they have all the facilities required to synthesizes F3 catalyst, but most importantly the level of experience that exists at Yanpet to run F3. PK & Sharq can face a lot of problems facing a brand new catalyst system with completely new reactor conditions. 
The initial study was done to asses the possibility  of running the new F3 catalyst system at SABIC Commercial Plants with lowest possible risk. PK, Sharq and Yanpet are the main candidates since these plants produce HDPE using Chromium catalyst and have a good deal of experience.
		PK	Sharq	Yanpet
	Titanation Step	DCR required to fit a connection for Titanate addition via special drums.	DCR required to fit a connection for Titanate addition via special drums.	Cat Mix Vessel already designed for Titanation addition.
	Activation at 750-800°C	Dehydrator design to operate only at 700°C  (not applicable).	Dehydrator design rated up to 1000°C. 	Dehydrator designed. for F3 activation rated up to 1000°C.
	Process Experience	Lack of experience with F3 reactor conditions.	Lack of experience with F3 reactor conditions.	More than 30 years experience running F3 system.
	Preparation for the Run	Expected to take no less than two years	Expected to take no less than 12 months	Expected to be within the range of no more than 3 months.
	Production Rate	Decrease from 58 T / h to 52 T / h	Same production rate of 52 T/h 	Increase from 44 T/h to 52 T/ h  

	Plant ownership	100 % SABIC Plant	51/49 SABIC-Mitsubishi
joint venture	50/50 joint venture with Exxon-Mobil

Reactor modified LDPE  - Approach and overview
To explore the potential of functionalized LDPE by copolymerizing functional co-monomers in high-pressure free-radical process targeting high-added value products.
Each year one or more concepts will be used as a spin-off for new development projects.

SABIC CONFIDENTIAL


No. ‹#›


Patent situation
Functional copolymers
DOW, BOREALIS and ExxonMobil are very active. Main applications seen are Extrusion Coating (DOW, BOREALIS, Exxon, LyondellBasell), functionalized polymers for film (DOW). Also these competitors (at least Dow and ExxonMobil) are taking the advantage on in-house high pressure facilities.

COC’s
Patent from Union Carbide claiming Norbornene and its substituents at high pressure (1963)
Patent from Societe Chimique des Charbonnages-CdF Chimie on cyclohexene and cyclooctene in high pressure (1976)
Patent from Spencer Chemical Company on cyclohexene as CTA in high pressure (1960)

Controlled Radical Polymerisation
SABIC is leading here in high pressure, two patents filed, although it is still in a very early research state

Legal consideration and Product stewardship 
No legal limitations within the MT catalyst platform 
(FTO: N. Friederichs, M. Schmeetz, 2010-272)

No patent protection  company secret

Use of 1,2-diethers during HDPE polymerization is possible for MT
Two patents filed regarding the use of 1,2-diethers together with MT and MTX

No product stewardship concerns for MT-like catalysts
Food approval is valid for polymers produced using this catalyst.

The application of DMB as donor will yield polymer products within the current food approval specifications.
Future donor compounds will be assessed by product stewardship (M. Bosma).

Evaluation of MT6 with 1,2 Diether External 
Donors for Bimodal HDPE Pipe  

 
 
From:    Geert-Jan Meppelder (Geert-Jan.Meppelder@SABIC-Europe.com) 

T&I, HDPE Bimodal base resin, STC Geleen 
 
Reviewed by:   Nic Friederichs 
    Jacques Tacx 
    Maria Soliman    
 
Contributions by:  Erik Janssen - Supervision of bench scale experiments  
    Robert Chan - Catalyst preparation 

Priya Garg – Material evaluation 
 
Discussion partner:  Rudy Deblieck 
 
To: HDPE Bimodal Team members 

Nic Friederichs 
Maria Soliman 
Jacques Tacx 
Michel Wintraeken 
 

CC: Francesco Bertola 
Dieter Bilda 
Munif Al-Munif 
Hans Pierik 
Klaas Remerie 

 
Project Number: RP-HDPE-NPI-031 MT4-6 + Donor 

 
Executive Summary 
 

A catalyst recipe based on MT6 in combination with a donor and TiBA co-catalyst was 
developed capable of producing RELY5922 and Advanced PE100-like bimodal grades with 
commercially feasible catalyst activity. Using a very low molar Donor/Ti ratio, a 20-40% reduction in 
side product formation compared to MT8 was achieved. The advantages of using MT6 and a donor 
on the MMD (FRR and PDI) and side-product formation were found to coincide, rather than stack at 
the chosen Donor/Ti ratio. To produce the bimodal grades of sufficiently low MFI however, the 
presence of a donor is required.  

Bimodal RELY5922-mimics (with a split of 55) were produced in specification using MT6 with 
donor added in R1 or R2. The material properties of these materials is very similar. Thus, donor 
addition in R1, R2, or even before R1 is feasible.  

Their less pronounced high molar mass tail and slightly higher MFI most likely lower the 
performance of the material. Surprisingly, despite these effects the performance of MT6/DMB-based 
RELY is at least equal to MT8. Nevertheless, the objective of improved material performance was 
not achieved. Possibly the negative effects are compensated by a more narrow molar mass 
distribution and/or more narrow chemical composition distribution (CCD) of the reactor 2 material. 
Especially, the effect of the catalyst modifications on the CCD still remains to be investigated. 
 



STCG-2014-219 
SABIC Technology Center Geleen 
CONFIDENTIAL
