Technology & Innovation 3/30 

 

1. Recommendations 
 

� To determine whether the presence and amount of a donor narrows the broadness of the 
chemical composition distribution (CCD) compared to MT8, cross-fractionation of unimodal 
or bimodal materials would be recommended.  

� More accurate data on the performance of the catalyst and side-product formation can be 
gained from running experiments in a continuous setup such as CUBE. Furthermore, 
information can be gained on the amount of donor that remains in the diluent. This information 
can be used to assess the risk of donor accumulation in a commercial plant, where the mother 
liquor is recycled. 

� Successive self-nucleation and annealing (SSA) DSC experiments may give more insight 
into the mechanical performance of the bimodal materials.  
 
 

2. Introduction/Background 
 
LD6 is currently the only Hostalen plant where SABIC produces bimodal HDPE using its MT8 

catalyst in combination with TiBA co-catalyst. The two plants in KSA are still operated using catalysts 
licensed from Lyondell-Basell and use TEA as co-catalyst. In accordance with the SABIC strategy 
to move away from being a pure technology user, the MT8 catalyst is to be rolled out to these assets 
and supported by construction of an MT catalyst plant.  

 
In the development of a next-generation MT catalyst bimodal materials with superior 

mechanical properties and reduced formation of side products, such as waxes and ethane. To 
achieve these properties a catalyst that can produce a narrower molecular mass distribution was 
targeted (Figure 1).*,1 In September 2012, the MT catalyst platform project (RP-HDPE-PLF-005) was 
reviewed to identify suitable leads.2   

 
Figure 1. Simplified material concept for bimodal materials with superior performance and 
processability. 
 
Two leads to improve MT8 in the desired fashion were identified. The MT catalyst is 

generated from a soluble magnesium-titanium alkoxide (MGT) solution in hexanes by precipitation 
and reduction with EtAlCl2 (EADC). The Al/Ti molar ratio used in the catalyst synthesis influences 

 
                                                
* More recently, the material concept for a high-performance bimodal HDPE was updated. To achieve the best balance 

between mechanical performance and processability, a catalyst is required that can produce materials with narrow 

chemical composition distribution, narrow molecular mass distribution, and statistical (non-blocky) comonomer 

incorporation. For more information, see reference 1 



STCG-2014-219 
SABIC Technology Center Geleen 
CONFIDENTIAL 

 

 

Technology & Innovation 4/30 

 

the molecular mass distribution (MMD) of the resulting polymer. The Al/Ti ratio of commercial MT8 
is optimized with respect to catalyst yield. A polymer with a narrower molecular mass distribution can 
be produced at lower Al/Ti ratios, albeit at lower activity.3 Plant trials and bench scale results have 
shown that the broader MMD of MT12 did not improve the mechanical properties of pipe and blow 
molding materials.4 Although it is believed that the more narrow MMD of MT<8 may provide materials 
with better ESCR and impact properties than MT8, A6060 bench scale results were inconclusive.5 It 
has been shown though that MT<8 generates less ethane and incorporates the comonomer 
differently. 

A second promising approach is the use of electron donors. For PE as well as for PP, donor 
molecules are believed to interact with sterically open active sites on the catalyst to modify or block 
their reactivity. Such active sites produce relatively short chains with high comonomer content that 
are not contributing to the mechanical properties of the product. MT8 with methyl eugenol (ME) as 
internal donor was found to lower MFI, reduce ethane formation, and change the comonomer 
distribution as measured via hexane extractables.6 A6060 produced with this catalyst showed 
improved impact and strain hardening performance. The presence of 1,2-diether functionality in the 
donor was found to be responsible for the advantageous effects.7 On the downside, donor-
modification of MT8 also reduces catalyst activity, especially in the first polymerization stage. It was 
shown however that addition of ME as external donor in the second stage of polymerization still gave 
A6060 with reduced MFI and improved low-temperature impact performance.8  

A project (MT4-6 + Donor, RP-HDPE-NPI-031) was spun off from the MT catalyst project with 
the aim to develop a next generation catalyst based on MT<8 in combination with a donor for pipe 
materials with superior mechanical properties and/or to reduce side product formation. 

 In the first part of this report MT<8 +donor catalyst recipes are explored and their 
performance in production of HAV pipe recipes compared to MT8. In the second part of this report 
the properties of these materials are compared to similar offerings based on MT8. An in-depth 
investigation of the performance of MT6 without donor with different co-catalysts is reported 
elsewhere.9 

 
 

3. Experimental Setup 
 

 General considerations  
 
All experiments were performed in the TOPS, a 20L semi-batch reactor, operating typically 

with 10L of purified hexanes as diluent. The reactor pressure is controlled by the ethylene feed. The 
TOPS is equipped with an online GC for accurate headspace measurement of hydrogen and 1-
butene concentrations and is used to control the H2/C2 and C4/C2 ratios during polymerization. 
Typically about 1 kg of bimodal product is obtained per experiment, following a general protocol for 
the production of bimodal HDPE.10 
 

 Catalyst considerations  
 
In the development of an MT<8 + Donor recipe the following parameters were investigated 

(Table 1). In all experiments the Al/Ti ratio was fixed at 6 (MT6), which strikes a balance between 
lower catalyst activity and the desired polydispersity.11 MT6 was previously employed in the PE2.1 
and PE2.2 unimodal plants in combination with TEA, to produce injection molding grades. 



STCG-2014-219 
SABIC Technology Center Geleen 
CONFIDENTIAL 

 

 

Technology & Innovation 5/30 

 

 
Table 1. Catalyst recipe parameters 
Al/Ti (EADC/MGT) ratio MT6 
Co-catalyst TEA / TiBA 
Co-catalyst concentration 0.2 mM (TEA) / 0.8 mM (TiBA)  
Donor DMB / ME 
D/Ti ratio - 
Donor addition R2 (R1 vide infra) 

 
Since SABIC has a joint venture with Albemarle (SOCC) in KSA for the production of TEA 

the choice of co-catalyst has some economic considerations. Recent results show that for MT8 TiBA 
is the co-catalyst of choice and that HAV pipe grades cannot be produced with TEA.12 Catalytic 
activity of MT6 however at low concentrations of TEA co-catalyst or high concentrations or TiBA is 
comparable to MT8 in unimodal copolymerization experiments. Therefore, performance of MT6 with 
donor was investigated for both TEA and TiBA. The co-catalyst concentrations were fixed at levels 
that gave the highest catalyst activity. 

From previous donor investigations methyl eugenol (ME) and 1,2-dimethoxybenzene (DMB) 
were found to give good results with MT8.7 An initial EHS evaluation by Product Stewardship of 
these donors in the early stages of the project recommended against the use of methyl eugenol in 
food-contact applications (e.g. water pipes) in light of its genotoxicity, even though it is present in 
significant amount in many natural food components, such as herbs and spices.13a DMB is not 
genotoxic and received a positive advice from EHS.13b,c  Therefore, the current investigation mainly 
focusses on the use of DMB as donor. More recently however, new insights have cause Product 
Stewardship to reevaluate its opinion on ME, which now also is deemed suitable for use. Because 
both DMB and ME are not on the food-approved list of the European Food and Safety Authority 
(EFSA) there are limits on the amount of donor that is allowed to migrate out of the HDPE. 
Preliminary migration simulations based on expected D/Ti ratios and catalyst yields however suggest 
that these limits will not pose a problem. Real-life migration testing will have to be done however 
when larger amounts of material become available from (pilot) plant trials. 

 
 MT6 synthesis 

 
MT6 catalysts were prepared in a 1L glass bench scale reactor that is a scaled down model 

of the reactor used in the Kontakt Anlage.5,14 Lab-made MGT and EADC obtained from Chemtura 
were used in the synthesis and standard conditions used for the synthesis of MT8 in the lab were 
applied (Table 2). These conditions are translated from those used in the KA to produce MT8 for 
LD6. It should be noted here that MT6 was last produced in the KA in 1999 following a recipe that 
does not translate to the current lab-scale synthesis.15  

 
Table 2. MT6 preparation parameters 

MGT concentration 0.094 M 
Reactor total volume 619 mL 
Stirrer speed 1400 rpm 
EADC addition time 15 min 
n(EADC) 338.5 mmol 
n(MGT) 56.5 mmol 

 



STCG-2014-219 
SABIC Technology Center Geleen 
CONFIDENTIAL 

 

 

Technology & Innovation 6/30 

 

The resulting catalysts were analyzed using Neutron Activation Analysis (NAA) and GC after 
hydrolysis to determine the composition (Table 3). Compared to MT8, MT6 has much lower chlorine 
content and higher alkoxide content. These values are consistent with less EADC being available to 
exchange these groups on the catalyst. Both MT6 catalysts show very similar elemental 
compositions, with slightly more alkoxides present on catalyst RC16.

4. Results and Discussion 

 
 Unimodal copolymerization experiments 

 
The effect of D/Ti ratio was investigated in unimodal copolymerization using 1-butene 

comonomer. In these experiments TiBA and TEA co-catalysts and DBM and ME external donors 
were tested. All catalyst combinations were tested under standard process conditions. The donor 
solution in hexanes was added separately to the reactor before the catalyst was injected. The results 
are summarized in Table 4.

mM. Density measured on powder. 

 
 
MT8 with TiBA is significantly more active and gives somewhat lower MFIs than MT6 with 

TiBA or TEA. In line with earlier reports, addition of 0.25 equivalent of DMB to MT8 reduces both 
MFI as well as activity. Table 4 confirms that donor addition to MT6 also gives products with reduced 
MFI and activity. The response of MT6 towards electron donors appears to be higher than MT8. At 



STCG-2014-219 
SABIC Technology Center Geleen 
CONFIDENTIAL 

 

 

Technology & Innovation 7/30 

 

a D/Ti ratio of 0.5, MT6/TiBA/DMB shows a large decrease in MFI, but catalyst activity also 
decreases by 90% and for MT6/DMB/TEA no catalyst activity was observed at all at a D/Ti ratio of 
0.25. A D/Ti ratio of 0.10 was found to give the best balance between catalyst activity and MFI, but 
compared to MT8 activities were low.  

The results do not show a clear preference for either one of the donors, but the use of TEA 
generally results in higher MFI values. Thus, the use of TEA in bimodal experiments might reduce 
the MFI capability of the catalyst.  Unimodal copolymers produced using TEA also have slightly 
higher densities. For MT8/TEA the density in unimodal copolymerization was shown to vary with the 
co-catalyst concentration (A/Ti ratio).12 

In contrast to previous results, no significant decrease of the flow rate ratio (FRR) was 
observed. Conversely, the lower FRR of MT6 without donor compared to MT8 is in line with previous 
results. It is interesting to note though that addition of a donor to MT6 does not appear to give an 
additional effect. This observation and the high donor sensitivity of MT6 are consistent with the 
hypothesis that going from MT8 to MT6 less sterically open active sites susceptible to blocking by a 
donor are present.  

 

  
Figure 2. SEC-dv of selected unimodal copolymer samples. 

 
The molar mass distributions of MT8 and MT6 with and without DMB based on SEC-DV 

(universal calibration) are shown in Figure 2; the molar mass data are summarized in Table 5. The 
SEC-dv data are consistent with the MFI and FRR values observed for MT8 with donor and MT6 
(with donor). Donor addition increases Mn and Mw values for MT8 and MT6 (with donor) and 
decreases Mw/Mn for MT8, but not for MT6. Interestingly, Mz values of the donor-modified catalysts 
are lower compared to their reference materials. This is due to a less pronounced high-molecular 
weight tail, present in the unmodified materials, which is known to contain long-chain branched 
material.16  

 
 
 



STCG-2014-219 
SABIC Technology Center Geleen 
CONFIDENTIAL 

 

 

Technology & Innovation 8/30

SEC-IR data (Figure 3) shows that at comparable density, the comonomer content for MT8 

is higher than for MT6-based catalysts. This suggests that the comonomer in MT6-based catalyst is 
incorporated in a more efficient (i.e. statistical) fashion. The presence of a donor or the co-catalyst 
used in combination with MT6 does not appear to have much effect on the average comonomer 
incorporation over the molecular mass distribution. To determine whether the presence of a donor 
affects the broadness of the chemical composition distribution compared to MT8, cross-fractionation 
of unimodal or bimodal materials would be recommended. 

 

 
Figure 3. SEC-IR of selected unimodal copolymer samples. 

 
 Stage 1 homopolymerization experiments 

 
A new MT catalyst recipe for multimodal pipe applications must be capable of producing all 

pipe recipes currently available and under development. The most demanding grade currently in 
production is the updated recipe for RELY5922.17 Compared to the first reactor settings of the current 
LD6 pipe portfolio the J-value of the new recipe was increased from 75 to 85 cm3/g. Therefore, in a 
second set of experiments the capability of MT6 with DMB to produce RELY5922-like materials with 
TiBA and TEA co-catalyst was evaluated. The results for the first stage homopolymerization are 
shown in Table 6.  



STCG-2014-219 
SABIC Technology Center Geleen 
CONFIDENTIAL 

 

 

Technology & Innovation 9/30

Experiments were run for 120 min. with 40 mg catalyst MT6 (RC16) at T = 88 °C; [TiBA] = 0.8 mM or [TEA ] = 0.2 mM. Density was 

measured on powder according to DHPE003. The settings of highlighted experiments were used in subsequent bimodal experiments.  

* Catalyst MT6 (RC10) was used instead.  

 
Unexpectedly, in contrast to the copolymerization results the catalyst yields of MT6 in stage 

1 homopolymerization are equal or better than the MT8 reference. In part this is because the activity 
profiles of MT6/TiBA and MT6/TEA show much less decay in activity than MT8.  It is therefore 
expected that in stage 1 of bimodal experiments, where the residence time is ~3h instead of 2h, 
good MT6 activity will be obtained. Even with the addition of DMB as external donor in stage 1 
catalyst yields are acceptable, which makes donor dosing in or even before stage 1 of a bimodal 
experiment a realistic option. Since the hydrogen sensitivity of the MT catalysts is known to increase 
in the order MT12<MT8<MT6, the lower H2/C2 ratio applied to the MT6-based experiments thus also 
contributes to their good stage 1 catalyst yields. 

 

 
Figure 4. Stage 1 activity profiles for MT8 and MT6-based catalysts 

 
After initial adjustment, an H2/C2 ratio of 2.0 was found to give acceptable MFI and J-values 

for both MT6/TiBA as well as MT6/TEA. This is in line with expectations, since in stage 1 chain-



STCG-2014-219 
SABIC Technology Center Geleen 
CONFIDENTIAL 

 

 

Technology & Innovation 10/30 

 

transfer to hydrogen is the predominant mechanism and the contribution of chain-transfer to co-
catalyst is negligible. The presence of DMB on the catalyst also leads to slightly increased molecular 
weights in stage 1 homopolymerization. An increase in H2/C2 ratio from 2.0 to ~2.3 was required to 
obtain comparable MFI values to MT6 without donor. The highlighted experimental settings were 
used in subsequent bimodal experiments. Since the MFI of experiment 140620-b1a was still on the 
low side, a H2/C2 ratio of 2.4 was used for bimodal experiments instead. 

Ethane formation was monitored over time using the online GC measurement of the 
headspace. Going from MT8 to MT6 >40% less ethane is generated per kg of polymer. Since ethane 
formation for MT6 and MT6/DMB are comparable, it appears that the reductions in ethane formation 
using either MT6 or a donor do not stack. Furthermore, within the accuracy of the measurement it 
does not appear to matter whether TiBA or TEA co-catalyst is used.   

This increased side-product efficiency represents a significant cost benefit over MT8. It was 
estimated that in LD6 the majority of the hydrogen in the first reactor is consumed to generate ethane, 
which accumulates in the first reactor and increases total reactor pressure.18 As much as 20-25% of 
the gas cap in the first reactor consists of ethane. Reduced ethane formation can therefore also 
decrease  the total pressure in the first reactor, which could allow the plant to increase the catalyst 
yield by raising the ethylene partial pressure. 

For all stage 1 bench scale experiments the amount of oligomeric side products (waxes) was 
determined in two ways. Firstly, a sample of the diluent after filtration of the polymer was evaporated 
to estimate the wax fraction that is soluble at 30°C. Unfortunately, it has proven to be rather 
challenging to reliably and reproducibly determine the soluble waxes on the bench scale.19  

Additionally, the fraction of oligomers that is soluble at reaction conditions and precipitates 
on the polymer during cooling was determined via soxhlet extraction from boiling hexane. Both 
methods are complementary in the determination of the total wax content of the polymer. The so-
called hexane extractables however can serve as a qualitative indication for the soluble wax content 
(higher extractables, higher soluble wax content). Hexane extractables results from Table 6 clearly 
show lower values (tentatively ≥20% less) for MT6, with or without donor, especially when TiBA is 
used.  

 
 Bimodal experiments 

 
The highlighted first-stage settings from Table 6 were used to prepare bimodal materials that 

target the new RELY5922 specifications. Really, the lower end of the specification is usually targeted 
(0.17 ±0.01) to ensure that strain hardening values are sufficient to qualify the product as RC 
(resistance to slow crack-growth) material. The high split in combination with the low MFI however 
requires a very high molecular weight copolymer in the second polymerization stage. This puts very 
high demands on the performance and MFI capability of the catalyst. Even the current commercial 
MT8 catalyst requires very little to no hydrogen, which makes the commercial process more difficult 
to steer. Since the most promising results from Table 5 and Table 6 were achieved using TiBA 
cocatalyst, the main focus of the bimodal experiments will be on the MT6/DMB/TiBA combination. 
The results of the bimodal experiments are shown in Table 7.  

 



STCG-2014-219 
SABIC Technology Center Geleen 
CONFIDENTIAL 

 

 

Technology & Innovation 11/30

RELY5922        0.20±0.04   948±2   

a Experiments were run with 40 mg catalyst RC16 at the following stage 2 conditions: Split = 55; T = 78°C. Density was measured on 

powder according to DHPE003; b Results already reported elsewhere9; c 50 mg of catalyst was used instead. Polymer obtained from 

highlighted experiments were submitted for material analysis. 

 
In view of the low catalyst yields of MT6 with DMB in the unimodal copolymerization 

experiments, low activity in the second stage of the bimodal experiments was expected. To ensure 
sufficient catalyst activity in the presence of donor the partial pressure was initially increased from 
1.7 to 5.0 bar. Furthermore, to assess the MFI capability of the catalyst combinations the H2/C2 ratio 
was set to zero. Surprisingly however, with DMB added in stage 2 catalyst activity with TiBA was 
better than expected. Therefore, a RELY 5922 mimic (140613) was produced at the reference PC2 
of 1.7 bar. To RELY 5922 with DMB added in the first stage (140624), a pC2 of 3.0 bar is required in 
the second stage to achieve an acceptable residence time. 

Compared to the MT8 bench scale reference 130405 and MT6 without donor 131129, the 
MT6-based RELY mimics with DMB, 140613 and 140624, require a higher C4/C2 ratio to achieve the 
same density.9 Furthermore it is clear that the addition of 0.10 equivalents of DMB to MT6 
significantly lowers the MFI of the bimodal product, despite higher H2/C2 and C4/C2 ratios. These 
observations are consistent with inhibition by the donor of the sterically open active sites that 
generate chains of relatively low molecular weight and high comonomer content that are detrimental 
to the mechanical properties.  

A bimodal experiment without hydrogen using the alternative methyl eugenol donor (140424) 
instead showed that MT6/ME/TiBA is equally capable of producing RELY5922 or even future 
Advanced PE100-like products. Unfortunately a higher D/Ti ratio was used in this experiment. In a 
similar fashion an experiment using the MT6/DMB catalyst was in combination with TEA cocatalyst 
(131202) showed that also this catalyst combination has sufficient operating window to produce all 
the required products with sufficient activity. 

It has to be noted however, that for MT6/TEA several experiments had to be discarded 
because the catalyst showed very low or no activity. After catalyst injection a variable induction 
period of several minutes was observed before the catalyst started consuming ethylene or in some 
cases no polymerization activity at all was observed. This behavior was not observed for MT6/TiBA. 
The combination of MT6/TEA however has been used commercially in PE2.1 and PE2.2. Therefore, 



STCG-2014-219 
SABIC Technology Center Geleen 
CONFIDENTIAL 

 

 

Technology & Innovation 12/30 

 

the bench scale protocol for these experiments should be further investigated if this catalyst 
combination is to be used in the future.  

The experiments where the donor is dosed externally in the second stage show that concerns 
for low catalyst activity MT6 with a donor are unfounded. Although the ethylene partial pressure in 
the first stage 1 had to be increased, Table 7 shows that external dosing of the donor in or even 
before the first polymerization stage is a feasible option.  

Similar to the stage 1 homopolymerization results, MT6 provides a >40% reduction in ethane 
formation per kg of polymer compared to MT8. Due to the somewhat larger scatter in the results, no 
significant difference is observed between DMB and ME, dosing of the donor in stage 1 or stage 2 
of the polymerization or which co-catalyst is used. These results corroborate that the main advantage 
is gained moving from MT8 to MT6. 

Measurement of the hexane-extractable fraction of the bimodal powders as a measure for 
the amount of waxes shows a similar picture. Moving from MT8 to MT6 leads to a reduction (≥25%) 
in hexane extractables. Again, the choice of donor or cocatalyst does not significantly change the 
amount of extractables within the accuracy of the measurement. The fact that these values are 
comparable for MT6-based products with MFIs between 0.09 and 0.30 indicates that the amount of 
hexane extractables is mainly determined by the first-stage material. Analysis of the extracted 
material by SEC analysis may confirm this. Furthermore, these results are based upon single 
experiments done on the bench scale. More accurate data on the performance of the catalyst and 
side-product formation can be gained from running experiments in a continuous setup such as 
CUBE. 

 
 

5. Material Evaluation 
 
The results of the material evaluation of the highlighted bimodal HDPEs from Table 7 are 

grouped in two sets of materials of comparable MFI and density. The first group is based on the 
RELY 5922 (split 55) specifications on MFI and density; the second group contains lower MFI 
products of similar density that more resemble Advanced PE100 materials. 

 
 RELY5922 mimics 

 
The first group of products is comprised of RELY5922 materials produced by MT6 / TiBA with 

the DMB donor added in the first stage (140624) and second stage (140613), and  MT8 (130405). A 
RELY-like material of higher MFI, made using MT6 without donor, was added for comparison. 

 
6.1.1 Density and MFI 

 
After stabilization and granulation of the selected materials, density and MFI were 

determined. The results are shown in Table 8. In line with expectations, going from powder MFI to 
granule MFI the melt flow index of all samples decreases by ~10%. Compared to the RELY5922 
specification the granule MFI of MT8 reference 130405 is too low, while the MT6/DMB samples 
140624 and 140613 are in specification. 

 In contrast to the results of the unimodal copolymer experiments, the FRR for the MT6-based 
products is not lower than that of reference 130405, with the exception of 140624. At such low MFI 



STCG-2014-219 
SABIC Technology Center Geleen 
CONFIDENTIAL 

 

 

Technology & Innovation 13/30 

 

values however, the melt flow ratio is not a good measure for the rheological broadness of the 
product anymore, since this ratio will change by 2-3 points when the MFI5 changes with 0.01 dg/min.

Annealed powder density was measured according to DHPE003; annealed granule density was measured according to 

DHPE012.  

 
The granule densities of the MT6-based materials are on the high side of the RELY 

specification. Between powder- and granule density values an increase of ~1 point is expected 
because of the differences between the DHPE003 and DHPE012 measurement methods (higher 
compression molding temperature and slower cooling rate for DHPE012).20 The lower granule 
density of 130405 is due to the fact that this sample was measured at SPO while the other samples 
were measured at Intertek. It is known that there is ~1-1.5 point difference between the granule 
densities measured in both labs. 

 
6.1.2 Size Exclusion Chromatography 

 
The molar mass distributions of the RELY5922 mimics based on MT8 and MT6 were 

measured by SEC-DV using a universal calibration (Figure 5). A summary of the molar masses is 
given in Table 9 and the Mark-Houwink plots are shown in Figure 6.

The molar mass distributions for the RELY grades prepared with MT6/DMB (140624 and 

140613) are narrower compared to the MT8-based reference (130405). They contain less low molar 
mass material as well as less very high molar mass chains, which is reflected in higher Mn and lower 
Mz values. Furthermore, Mw/Mn values for samples 140613 and 140624 are also lower than for 
130405. Since Mw/Mn is strongly determined by the low Mn values however, these values however 
should be considered with care and be confirmed by rheology.   

The molar mass distribution of the MT6 samples with donor added in R1 (140624) and donor 
added in R2 (140613) are similar. Sample 140613 is slightly broader at the very high molar mass 
end (>5.106 g/mol). The reported Mw of sample 140624 is surprisingly low, considering that the MFI5 
and MFI21 of this sample are very similar to samples 140613 and 130405. Possibly, this may be due 
to suppression of long-chain branching by the presence of DMB in the first polymerization stage.  

In comparison, on the low molar mass side the bulk of the molar mass distribution for MT6 
without donor (131129) is comparable to MT6 with donor, but shows some tailing below 1 kg/mol. 
Because of the higher MFI of the material the distribution for 131129 is narrower on the high molar 
mass side than the other samples. Consequently, due to the increased overlap of the MMDs of stage 
1 and -2 the visual split of the material appears to be lower. Surprisingly, also high-molar mass tailing 
is present. The exact reason for this is unknown, but these observation are reflected in the low Mn 
and high Mz of the product compared to 140624 and 140613. 

  
 

 
Figure 6. Mark-Houwink plot for the RELY5922 mimics. 

 



STCG-2014-219 
SABIC Technology Center Geleen 
CONFIDENTIAL 

 

 

Technology & Innovation 15/30 

 

In the Mark-Houwink plot (Figure 6) all samples show slight deflection from the linear PE 
behavior at high molar masses. Within the experimental error, the amount of deflection from linear 
PE behavior is very similar for all samples. This could be due to high comonomer content in the 
products or an indication of long chain branching in the products.  

The short chain branching (SCB) distribution over molar mass for the RELY mimics was 
measured using SEC-IR (Figure 7). At high molar mass the comonomer content of none of the 
samples was high enough to explain the deflection observed in the Mark-Houwink plot. However, 
SEC-IR only gives the average comonomer content for a particular molar mass fraction. CCD 
analysis of the material should be able to determine whether high comonomer content is responsible 
for the deflection from linearity.  

There appears to be little difference between the average SCB content as function of molar 
mass of MT8- and MT6-based samples, with exception of the sample produced by MT6/DMB R1. At 
these SCB-levels however, the resolution of the IR measurement is not very high and additional 
confirmation for this observation is required. 

 

 
Figure 7. Molar mass distributions and comonomer distribution measured by SEC-IR 
 

6.1.3 NMR Spectroscopy 
 
The end groups, comonomer content and unsaturations were measured by 1H NMR. The 

results are summarized in Table 10. The number of CH3 end groups measured depends not only on 
the average molar mass of the polymer, but also on the rate of chain-transfer to co-catalyst. Chain-
transfer to aluminium generates Al-polymeryl species that give saturated chain ends when the (co)-
catalyst is quenched. Thus, at similar melt flow rates of the MT8- and MT6-based products the higher 
amount of CH3 end group observed for sample130405 suggests that for the MT6-based catalysts 
chain-transfer to co-catalyst is reduced. 

The overall 1-butene content is slightly lower for 140624 and 140613 compared to the 
materials prepared without donor. Although the difference may in part be explained by the slightly 
lower density of the latter, there is a strong indication that the presence of the DMB donor improves 
the efficiency of how the density can be controlled with comonomer. The lower comonomer content 
of 140624 is also in line with the SEC-IR data.  



STCG-2014-219 
SABIC Technology Center Geleen 
CONFIDENTIAL 

 

 

Technology & Innovation 16/30 

 

Thus, to achieve a certain density MT6/DMB requires a higher comonomer feed (C4/C2 ratio, 
Table 7) than MT8, but uses less. Use of this catalyst system in Hostalen technology would then 
require an increased comonomer feed to reactor 2 and comonomer recovery. Based on the NMR 
data, the comonomer consumption however would be reduced slightly. Although at the current low 
temperature of the post reactor little catalyst activity is expected, it would be of interest to investigate 
if the lower comonomer sensitivity of MT6/DMB can be used to generate polymer in the post reactor 
that contributes to the mechanical properties of the product. 

The number of unsaturations measured for samples 140624 and 140613 are somewhat lower 
compared to MT8 or MT6 without donor. Typically, vinyl unsaturations in the range of 8-11 are 
measured in an unmodified MT8-catalysed product. This observation is consistent with the 
hypothesis of the donor blocking the sterically most open active sites, which can easier 
accommodate the transition states required to generate these unsaturations. Donor-inhibition of 
chain-transfer reactions increases the average molar mass of the polymer, which has been observed 
experimentally.

6.1.5 Rheology 

 
DMS measurement was carried at 190°C for the experi mental samples. Overlays of the 

complex viscosity and phase angle as a function of frequency are shown in 

 
Figure 8. 
  



STCG-2014-219 
SABIC Technology Center Geleen 
CONFIDENTIAL 

 

 

Technology & Innovation 18/30 

 

 
Figure 8. Complex viscosity and complex modulus (top) and phase angle (bottom) as a function of frequency 

 
In line with its lower MFI, DMS measurements show that the sample prepared using MT8 has 

a higher complex viscosity over the entire frequency range, compared to the MT6-based sample. 
The complex viscosities at low frequencies of the materials prepared with MT6/DMS is lower, but 
the rheological behavior at higher frequencies is comparable. Thus, these materials appear to be 
rheological narrower compared to RELY produced without donor. Flow rate ratio values and the high 
molar mass end of the SEC spectra support these observations.   

The phase angles for MT6 with donor are higher compared to MT8 over the entire frequency 
range, indicating that these samples show a less elastic, more viscous response. The lower storage 
modulus (G’) of these samples translates to a lower network density that can be attributed to the 
absence of a high molar mass tail present in the MT8-based sample.From the DMS spectra, a Shear 
Thinning Index (SHI2.7/210) and Shroff parameters were calculated ( 

Table 12). The SHI expresses the rheological broadness of a sample as ratio of the complex 
viscosities at two predefined (high and low) complex moduli,21 which in essence is a measure for the 



STCG-2014-219 
SABIC Technology Center Geleen 
CONFIDENTIAL 

 

 

Technology & Innovation 19/30 

 

shear sensitivity of the material. The Shroff ER and PDR parameters are expressions for the 
rheological broadness of the high-molar mass end of the MMD and the entire MMD, respectively.22 
In fact, the PDR value is an expansion of the SHI where besides the shear sensitivity also a measure 
of the curvature of the complex viscosity as a function of frequency is included.†  
 

Table 12. Shroff parameters and shear thinning index (SHI) for the selected materials 
Experiment Catalyst 

 
SHI 

(2.7/210) 
Shroff 
PDR 

Shroff 
ER 

130405 MT8 129.5 71.9 2.5 
131129 MT6   87.5 37.4 2.6 
140624 MT6 / DMB R1   39.4 17.6 1.7 
140613 MT6 / DMB R2   53.6 23.2 1.8 

 
The values for SHI and PDR in Table 12 clearly show that the rheological broadness of the 

materials decreases in the order MT8 > MT6 > MT6/DMB. Moreover, both SHI and PDR show that 
addition of the donor in the first polymerization stage gave a material that was narrower compared 
to donor addition in stage 2. This perfectly matches the trend of Mw/Mn values observed from SEC-
DV. In addition, lower Shroff ER values again clearly show MT6/DMB-based materials to be 
rheological narrower on the high molar mass side, which is also well-reflected in lower Mz/Mw values 
for these materials compared to MT6 and MT8.

performed and the notched Charpy impact performance and strain hardening modulus were 
measured. The results are summarized in

Technology & Innovation 20/30 

 

140624 MT6 / DMB R1 36.8 ±0.5 18.5 ±0.4 62.7 ±2.7 97 9 ±32 22.9 ±0.4 
140613 MT6 / DMB R2 39.6 ±0.8 18.0 ±2.5 65.6 ±2.8 99 8 ±18 22.8 ±0.4 

 
 
The low-temperature impact performance, strain hardening modulus and tensile properties 

of the RELY5922 mimics produced with MT8 and MT6/DMB are comparable. Due to its higher MFI, 
SH and impact performance of the MT6-based materials are on a lower level. The slightly lower MFI 
of MT8 reference 130405 compared to MT6/DMB-based samples 140624 and 140613 will give 
Charpy and SH values that are somewhat high in comparison. Furthermore, 140624 and 140613 
show a less pronounced high molar mass fraction and slightly lower comonomer content. Since 
these generally lower the effective network density, lower SH and Charpy values compared to MT8 
might be expected. The fact that this is not the case suggests that there are positive effects as well 
that are not immediately apparent from the current analyses.  

One such effect may be the envisaged interaction of the donor with the active sites on the 
catalyst that generate low molar mass chains with high comonomer content. Absence of this low-
molar mass stage 2 copolymer fraction increases the effective network density. A second effect may 
be that 140613 and 140624 have a more narrow chemical composition distribution, which would 
increase the fraction of chains that can contribute to the effective network density.1 Successive self-
nucleation and annealing (SSA) DSC experiments and cross-fractionation of these materials may 
give more insight into their mechanical performance. 

Creep tests were also performed on the RELY5922 mimics in order to get a qualitative idea 
about the pressure resistance performance of these samples. Creep tests are one of the SMART 
test methods used to evaluate the pipe properties from a small quantity of sample.23 The results are 
summarized in Table 14. 

 
Table 14. Creep test results for the RELY5922 mimics. 

Experiment Catalyst 
 

Creep strain 
@5.4 MPa 

[%] 

Creep strain 
@6.3 MPa 

[%] 

Time to 50%  
strain @6.3 MPa 

[min] 

130405 MT8 12.5 ±0.1 3/3 samples yielded 17 ±6 
131129 MT6 13.1 ±0.5 3/3 samples yielded 14 ±4 
140624 MT6 / DMB R1   9.5 ±0.5 35.6 ±0.5 >60 
140613 MT6 / DMB R2 10.2 ±0.1 2/3 samples yielded 47 ±10 

 
 
The creep test values given here are comparable to those measured for a standard PE100 

grade based on unmodified MT8.5 catalyst. At 5.4 MPa, a standard PE100 grade shows strain% 
between 8-12% and at higher loads, the sample yields. The creep tests in combination with the 
tensile properties reveal that the pressure resistance of the experimental grades will be maintained 
at a PE100 level. 

At 5.4 MPa load none of the materials went into yield indicating PE100 pressure resistance 
level for all materials. Creep strain levels were slightly lower for MT6/DMB. While at 6.3 MPa samples 
130405 (MT8) and 131129 (MT6) yielded, the MT6/DMB samples 140613 went only partially into 
yield and 140613 did not yield at all. The longer times to reach 50% strain for 140613 and 140624 
suggest that the MT6/DMB-based samples may show improved IPT performance compared to 
reference sample 130405.

SABIC Technology Center Geleen 
CONFIDENTIAL 

 

 

Technology & Innovation 21/30 

 

 
 Low-MFI materials 

 
A second group consists of two materials produced with MT6 and different donors and co-

catalysts. These materials were produced to assess the MFI-capability of the MT6/Donor catalyst 
combination. Although they are based on the split and density of the RELY5922 recipe, the lower 
MFI of these products more resembles Advanced PE100 materials. Unfortunately, no comparable 
hypothetical product based on MT8 (from the 1-butene DoE) was found that could serve as a 
possible reference sample. 

 
6.2.1 Density and MFI 

 
The density and MFI of the experimental grades is given in Table 15. The MFIs and density 

of the experimental grades are very comparable. The very high FRR shows that the products are 
very broad, due to the combination of high split, reactor 1 product and low overall MFI. There is no 
difference in the amount of hexane extractables between these experimental grades (Table 7). This 
implies that the combination of different donors and co-catalysts used here does not influence the 
amount of low molar mass products.

6.2.2 Size Exclusion Chromatography 
 
The molar mass distributions of these materials were measured by SEC-DV using a universal 

calibration (Figure 9). A summary of the molar masses is given in Table 16 and the Mark-Houwink 
plots are shown in Figure 10.  

The molar mass distributions (Figure 9) for both experimental grades are comparable to each 
other. Compared to sample 140423, 131202 is slightly broader on the low molar mass side as well 
as on the high molar mass side. This is also reflected in a higher Mw/Mn value. Within experimental 
error, no significant difference in the calculated molar masses (Mn, Mw and Mz) of the experimental 
grades is seen. Compared to the RELY5922 mimics (e.g. 140613) the molar mass of the second 
reactor fraction is much higher. Whereas the Mn values of these product groups are comparable, Mw 
values are 100-150 kg/mol higher for the low-MFI materials and Mz values are approximately twice 
as high.

indication of long chain branching in the products. Since the Mark-Houwink plot of sample 130405 
(MT8/TiBA) also shows this deflection from linear PE behavior (Figure 6), the deflection seen in 
Figure 10 is not unique to the combination of donors and co-catalysts.

The short chain branching (SCB) distribution over molar mass for both experimental grades 

was measured by SEC-IR (Figure 11). Within the error of the method, there is no difference visible 
in the average SCB as function of molar mass profiles for both low-MFI materials as well as with the 
MT6/DMB-based RELY mimic. This implies that, although the Donor-Titanium ratio is different, the 
combination of DMB/TEA and ME/TiBA gives comparable comonomer incorporation over molar 
mass.

The molar mass of the experimental grades as well as the number of CH3 end groups are 

comparable for both materials. It therefore appears that the use of different combinations of co-
catalyst and donor with the MT6 catalyst does not really change the rate of chain-transfer to co-
catalyst. The overall incorporated comonomer amount is also comparable for both grades. This is in 
line with the SEC-IR results where no significant difference in the average SCB distribution over the 
molar mass was seen.  

As expected for MT6/Donor-based products (Table 10), the number of vinyl unsaturations 
measured for the low-MFI materials grades comparable to samples 140624 and 140613, which were 
lower than those seen for an MT8-catalyzed material. There is no significant difference in the number 
of vinylidene and vinylene unsaturations for these products.

6.2.5 Rheology 
 
DMS measurement was carried at 190°C for the experi mental samples. Overlays of the 

complex viscosity and phase angle as a function of frequency are shown in Figure 12. DMS 
measurements show that sample 131202 has a higher complex viscosity at lower frequencies than 
sample 140423. At higher frequencies, both samples show comparable rheological behavior. Thus, 
in line with FRR values and polydispersity values from SEC-dv, sample 131202 is rheologically 
broader. The lower phase angle for sample 140423 is in line with these observations.  

 

 
Figure 12. Complex viscosity and complex modulus (top) and phase angle (bottom) as a  
function of frequency 

 
As for the RELY5922 mimics, SHI and Shroff parameters were calculated from the DMS data. 

The results are shown in Table 19. Surprisingly, much higher values were obtained compared to the 
RELY mimics. A plot of Log(G*) vs. Log(Eta*) in Figure 13 however shows that at the low reference 



STCG-2014-219 
SABIC Technology Center Geleen 
CONFIDENTIAL 

 

 

Technology & Innovation 26/30 

 

G* (2-3 kPa) the complex viscosity of the low-MFI materials increases by an order of magnitude. In 
contrast, at the high G* reference (2.0-2.2 *105 Pa) the increase in complex viscosity is within the 
same order of magnitude. Thus, much higher PDR and SHI numbers are obtained at lower MFI. 
 

Table 19. DMS and Shroff parameters and shear thinning index (SHI) for the selected materials 
Experiment Catalyst 

 
Shroff 

ER 
Shroff 
PDR 

(2.0/20/200) 

SHI 
(2.7/210) 

131202 MT6 / TEA / DMB 1.9 286.2 338.0 
140423 MT6 / TiBA / ME 2.0 205.7 252.6 

 
 
Unfortunately, Figure 13 also shows that to calculate PDR and SHI values for such low-MFI 

materials, a large extrapolation of the existing data is required. Normally, small extrapolations can 
be done accurately using a 3rd order polynomial fit of the existing data. Here however, extrapolation 
of the 3rd order fit is not accurate anymore and appears to lead to overestimations of the complex 
viscosity. Therefore, no scientific importance should be attached to these values. Instead, to be able 
to compare all samples, different reference values for G* could be used that are (nearly) covered by 
measurements.  

Although ER values are also calculated by extrapolation of measured DMS data, the extent 
of extrapolation is comparable for low-MFI materials and RELY mimics. The obtained values for 
MT6/Donor-based low-MFI materials are in line with values obtained for the MT6/DMB-based RELY 
mimics.

Due to their very low MFI, the impact and strain hardening values are very high. There is little 

difference between the impact performance of these experimental grades. Furthermore, the tensile 
properties are also comparable. The most pronounced difference is seen in the strain hardening 
modulus, whereby sample 131202 shows a higher value than sample 140423. As shown previously, 
the total incorporated comonomer amount and the average SCB distribution over the molar mass 
are comparable for both grades. Most likely, the higher strain hardening modulus can be attributed 
to the slightly lower MFI of sample131202.  

Compared to a standard PE100 grade based on an unmodified MT8.5 catalyst, the impact 
and strain hardening modulus values of the experimental grades are very high. This can be attributed 
to the higher MFI5 of a standard PE100 grade, which is typically ~0.3 dg/min.

Creep tests were also performed on the experimental grades. The results are summarized in 

Table 21. At 5.4 MPa load, the experimental grades did not yield. The total strain at the end of the 
measurement is comparable for both grades. At higher load (6.3 MPa), the samples yielded. There 
is no difference in the time to reach 50% strain. Despite the much lower MFI of these samples, these 
creep test results given here are comparable to the creep results of the RELY mimics (Table 14) or 
those measured for an MT8-based standard PE100 grade. 

 
 

6. Summary and Conclusions 
 

• A catalyst recipe striking an optimal balance between reduced catalyst activity and lower MFI 
was developed using MT6 with an external donor at a D/Ti ratio of 0.10. This D/Ti ratio is much 
lower than observed for MT8. While 1,2-dimethoxybenzene (DMB) and methyl eugenol (ME) 
donors were found to give comparable results, TEA was found to be a less suitable co-catalyst 
than TiBA.  
 

• Use of MT6 in combination with TiBA co-catalyst and a donor was found to give much less side 
product formation. Compared to MT8, MT6/DMB gives >25% less hexane extractables (a 
measure for wax formation) and >40% less ethane formation.  

 



STCG-2014-219 
SABIC Technology Center Geleen 
CONFIDENTIAL 

 

 

Technology & Innovation 28/30 

 

 
• In unimodal and bimodal experiments, the advantage of using MT6 and a donor on FRR, PDI, 

and side-product formation were found to coincide rather than stack at the chosen D/Ti ratio. The 
exception is the effect of the donor on the MFI.  
 

• Without use of a donor the required low-MFI pipe grades cannot be produced with MT6. At the 
chosen D/Ti ratio of 0.10, both RELY5922 as well as Advanced PE100-type materials can be 
produced.  
 

• In stage 1 homopolymerization, the catalyst activity profile show much less decay than MT8. 
Consequently, the external donor can be added anywhere in the Hostalen process. 
 

• Bimodal RELY5922 (split 55) was produced using MT6 with donor added in reactor 1 or 2. 
Compared to the MT8 reference, the molar mass distribution of MT6/Donor-based RELY are 
narrower on both the low- as well as on the high molar mass side. The less pronounced high 
molar mass tail of MT6/DMB also results in a lower rheological broadness. Furthermore, at 
comparable density MT6/DMB-based RELY appear to contain slightly less comonomer. 
 

• The material properties of MT6/Donor based RELY5922 are very similar. Thus, donor addition 
in R1, R2, or even before R1 is feasible.  

 
• Their less pronounced high molar mass tail and slightly higher MFI most likely lower the effective 

network density of the product, and thus the performance of the material. Surprisingly despite 
these effects, the impact, strain hardening and tensile creep performance of MT6/DMB-based 
RELY is at least equal to MT8. Nevertheless, the objective of improved material performance 
was not achieved. Possibly the reduction in effective network density is partially compensated 
by the narrowing of the MMD and/or narrowing of the chemical composition distribution (CCD) 
of the R2 material. Especially, the effect of the catalyst modifications on the CCD still remains to 
be investigated.

Material Evaluation of Injection Molding Products from LD6 Trial Run AX7611 

 

STC number: STCG-2014-61 

Date: March 2014 

 

Author:  Haika Hildebrandt (HDPE Bimodal) 

 

 

 



 

SABIC   

T&I Technology & Innovation      
                              

Confidential 

  2

                      
 

 

Material Evaluation of Injection Molding Products from LD6 trial run AX7611 

 

From:  Haika Hildebrandt (Haika.Hildebrandt@SABIC-Europe.com) 

 

Contribution: Philippe Rasquin (TM) 

Thei Rauch (TM) 

 

 

Project: RP-HDPE-NPI-035; Bimodal HDPE for Injection Molding 

 

 

To:  Copy:  

HDPE Bimodal team members Dieter Bilda  

Nic Friederichs  Francesco Bertola  

Gert Drummen  Munif Al-Munif  

Hans Pierik  Greg Godziela  

Philippe Rasquin  Michael Mattern  

Thei Rauch  Gerd Wollermann  

  Chris Meiboom  

 

Keywords: Injection Molding, bimodal HDPE, Caps and Closures, Carbonated Soft Drinks, LD6, trial run 

 

Executive Summary: 

In order to enlarge SABIC’s bimodal HPDE portfolio of LD6 in Gelsenkirchen, an injection molding grade 

dedicated for the caps and closure market was trialed for the first time in LD6. In total, four batches were 

produced under the trial run code AX7611. All batches were produced within the density specification 

952 ± 2 kg/m
3
. However, the MFI2.16 of the granules was 1.7 g/10 min and thus slightly below the specification 

of 2.0 ± 0.2 g/10min.   

The material evaluation of the granules showed that the plant conditions were very stable. No significant 

differences between the four batches were observed in terms of molecular structure and mechanical 

properties. In comparison to Basell’s grade ACP5331H, the LD6 material shows a better environmental stress 

crack resistance (ESCR) and better flow properties. 

 

 

  



 

SABIC   

T&I Technology & Innovation      
                              

Confidential 

  3

1. Introduction 
 

SABIC owns three plants for the production of bimodal HDPE, two in KSA and one in Germany. All plants are 

based on the same Hostalen slurry process technology, which is licensed from Lyondell-Basell. The LD6 in 

Germany started its production in 2008 as a follow up of the PE2.3. Up to now, the product portfolio was 

restricted to pipe grades, since the large differences in MFI and density of blow molding, injection molding 

and pipe grades would lead to high amounts of off-spec materials when switching production from one 

segment grade to another. However, dramatically reduced sales in the building and construction sector 

resulted in a sense of urgency and it became necessary to implement grades for other segments as well.  

First aim was to enlarge the portfolio by blow molding grades for the household and industrial container 

market. Two bottle grades with a density of 958 kg/m
3
 and HLMI’s of 22 g/10 min and 28 g/10min, were 

produced on the TOPS bench scale installation and trialed in LD6. 

Next step will be the introduction of an injection molding grade dedicated for caps and closures. This is a 

higher added value market, showing a significant growth especially for PE. In addition, the trend goes more 

and more into the direction of multimodal materials and so far, SABIC has no bimodal injection molding grade 

in its portfolio. Along with that, it is SABIC’s ambition to take here a leadership position in the next years.  

Consequently, a short term project was initiated with the aim to test the feasibility of producing a caps and 

closure grade for carbonated soft drinks. A grade with a density of 953 kg/m
3
 and a MFI2.16 of 2.0 g/10 min 

was successfully produced on bench scale. Material properties were at par or better compared to competitor 

material.
1
 Hence, it was decided to go for a plant trial in LD6, which took place under the trial code AX7611 in 

November 2013. In this report the material evaluation of the granules is summarized. 

 

 

2. Results and discussion 

 
The following product specification was targeted for AX7611. 

 

Table 1: Specification for trial run product AX7611. 

Density annealed, method SPO 953 ± 2 kg/m
3
 

MFI2.16 2.0 ± 0.2 g/10 min  

J1- value 130 cm
3
/g 

Split 50 

 

Four different batches were produced during the AX7611 trail run in LD6. Consequently, all four batches were 

evaluated with regards to molecular structure and mechanical properties. The same analyses were performed 

on ACP5331H from Basell. Some caps made of CAP508 from Ineos were available, too. But due to the low 

amount of material only SEC and NMR measurements could be performed. Comparisons were made as well 

with the products made on bench scale. 



 

SABIC   

T&I Technology & Innovation      
                              

Confidential 

  5

                      
 

 

In Table 2 densities and MFI’s of the products are summarized. Annealed densities of the trial run products 

were measured at Intertek and range from 954 kg/m
3
 to 955 kg/m

3
. Non-annealed densities were measured 

at the quality laboratory in Gelsenkirchen and resulted in a density of 953 kg/m
3
. As expected, the values of 

the annealed specimens are lower. However, the differences range from 0.7 to 1.7 and the values do not 

follow the same trend. Therefore it can be concluded, that the error of the measurement is higher than the 

batch to batch variation of the samples. In comparison to the competitor material, the densities are lower, 

compared to the bench scale products densities are higher. But, since it was decided to target a non-annealed 

density of 953 kg/m
3
, the specification is fully met.  

The MFI’s are as well very consistent for the four batches. Nevertheless, the MFI2.16 is below the specification 

of 2.0 ± 0.2 g/10 min. The values are also lower compared to the bench scale results and the ACP5331H 

competitor sample. The FRR indicates that the LD6 material is rheologically broader than all other samples. 

This could be beneficial for processabilitiy and might compensate the lower MFI2.16 values.

Figure 1: Overlay of SEC elution diagram and Mark-Houwink plots of the four bench scale samples. 

 

 

The differences in molar mass distribution of the four batches are within the experimental error. The 

measurements reflect the MFI data and show that the trial run was done under stable plant conditions. A 

deviation from the Mark-Houwink relation for linear polyethylene is visible in the high molecular weight 

region for all materials, which indicates the presence of long chain branching (LCB). This was as well observed 

for the bench scale products and the ACP5331H, as reported previously.
 1,2

T&I Technology & Innovation      
                              

Confidential 

  9

                      
 

 

The molecular weight Mw of the LD6 batches is comparable to the ACP5331H, but Mn and Mz values of the 

ACP grade are different. The Mn is higher and the Mz is lower. Consequently, the molecular weight 

distribution is narrower for the ACP grade. The CAP 508 grade shows in comparison to the LD6 batches lower 

values in all molecular structure parameters. Especially the Mn and Mz values are significantly lower. This is 

reflected in the SEC elution diagrams. However, since the data are derived from a cap, it might be that the 

material was partially degraded during the injection molding process. Therefore the data have to be 

interpreted with caution.  

The bench scale samples have a significantly higher Mn, but Mw and Mz are slightly lower, resulting in a 

narrower MWD. This is in line with the MFI data. The differences in Mn might be a result of the different 

J1-values. The bench scale samples were produced with a J1-value of 130 g/cm
3
 (MFI1.2 = 6.3 g/10 min), 

whereas the LD6 batches were produces at 124 g/cm
3
 (MFI1.2 = 7g/10 min).

c) NMR 
1
H NMR analyses were carried out to determine the comonomer incorporation and the formation of

0000172513 -0 5.2 2.1 2.6 1.02 12 1 1

No significant differences in the number of end groups for LD6 batches are observed. All materials contain 

about 2.0 methyl end groups per 1000 C. The number of end groups is higher in comparison to the Basell 

grade, but lower in comparison to the CAP508 grade. This is in line with the Mn values from SEC data. The 

amount of comonomer in the LD6 batches ranges from 2.4 to 3.0 branches/1000C. These small differences 

are not reflected in the densities, since a lower co-monomer content should result in a higher density and 

vice versa. This is not observed here for the density measurements that were done in Gelsenkirchen and at 

Intertek. The amount of comonomer is comparable to the Ineos grade. Basell’s ACP5331H has a lower 

amount of ethyl branches, which matches with the density measurement.  

The number of end groups of the bench scale products is lower compared to the DL6 batches and 

corresponds to the Mn values of SEC data. The amount of co-monomer is lower compared to the bench scale 

products. This is line with the higher density of the LD6 material. 

 

 



 

SABIC   

T&I Technology & Innovation      
                              

Confidential 

  12

b) Strain hardening 

The strain hardening modulus serves as an indicator for Environmental Stress crack resistance (ESCR) and has 

been determined for all materials. In Figure 6 the calculated <Gp> values are plotted. 

0 1 2 3

Figure 6: Results of tensile test. 

 

A strain hardening value of about 13.3 MPa was calculated for all samples. The values are comparable to the 

bench scale products. Obviously, the lower comonomer content is compensated by the lower molecular 

weight of the LD6 material. In comparison to Basell’s ACP5331H, which has a strain hardening modulus of 

12.1 MPa, the performance of LD6 material is better. 

 

  



 

SABIC   

T&I Technology & Innovation      
                              

Confidential 

  14

                      
 

 

 

c) Bell Test 

 

The bell test is also a measure for ESCR performance and is mainly used for blow molding and injection 

molding materials. However, the results cannot be correlated to the <Gp> modulus, since different 

mechanisms of crack formation are involved. 

 

 

0 1 2 3
0

10

40

50

60

80

 

B

te
st

 F
5

0
 [
h

]

batch number

 
Figure 7: Results of Bell Test according to ASTM 1693. 

 

As one can see in Figure 7 the F50 values vary between 56 and 81 hours. Batch number three has the highest 

MFI and lowest comonomer content, whereas batch two has the lowest MFI and a higher comonomer 

content. This might explain the differences seen in the F50 value. However, taking the large error into 

account, the differences are not significant. In comparison to the bench scale samples, the values are a bit 

higher. But it has to be taken into account that the samples were not measured at the same time and it has 

been observed frequently in the past that difficulties with reproducibility exist.
3,4

T&I Technology & Innovation

2.3 Spiral Flow 

Spiral flow was measured at the analytical lab in BoZ. The measurements were done at 220 °C and a pressure 

of 1200 bar. The results are shown in Figure 8. For comparison not only the LD6 batches were measured, but 

as well ACP5331H from Basell and Sabic’s commercial unimodal HDPE grades for caps and closures.

Figure 8: Spiral flow measurements of LD6 batches, ACP5331H from Basell and SABIC’s unimodal HDPE caps 

and closure grades. 

 

All LD6 samples show as expected the same fluidity. The material flows better than ACP5331H. The 

differences are more pronounced at higher thicknesses. In comparison to the unimodal grades, the flow is 

much better compared to CC253, which has a comparable MFI. The flow behavior of the LD6 material is close 

to M40053, an unimodal grade with a MFI of 5.1 g/10 min. Correlation of the data shows that the AX7611 

material flows like a unimodal material with a MFI of 4 g/10 min. 

  



 

SABIC   

T&I Technology & Innovation

2.4 Volatile organic content (VOC) 

The volatile organic content was measured according to EPA524.4. The results are shown in Table 6. 

 

Table 6: Results of VOC measurements.  

Substance Amount [μg/L] 

2-Butene (CAS 107-01-7) 0,68 

Methyl acetate (CAS 79-20-9) 0,10 

Branched alkane C6H14 0,29 

Hexane (CAS 110-54-3) 0,13 

Unknown alkene or cycloalkane 0,14 

 

The amount of 2-butene is quite high. However, this should not be a problem, since the butene will come out 

of the material during injection molding. The methyl acetate is most probably a contamination from the 

sampling process. The total amount of the branched alkanes, hexane and alkenes is 0.56 µg/L. Although this is 

a low amount, it is at the border of the Danone requirement of 0.5 µg/L. Therefore it is recommended to take 

care that the values are improved or at least stay at the same level. 

2.5 Organoleptic test 

The organoleptic test was carried out at the lab in Gelsenkirchen. All four batches passed the test. The 

method was performed according to Danone requirements. Thereby granules are incubated in Evian water. In 

a test panel odor and taste of a dilution series of the water is evaluated. 

 

2.6 Customer feedback 

Customers are interested in the new grade. T Plast has been the first to test AX7611. They ran the material on 

their new full electric machine in comparison with the SCGH555JA and have noticed that they were capable 

to reduce the energy consumption of about 15%. This shows that there is a lot of room for process 

improvement at customers. Other samples have been already sent but no feedback was available yet. 

 

 

  



 

SABIC   

T&I Technology & Innovation      
                              

Confidential 

  18

                      
 

 

 

3. Conclusion and Recommendations 
 

The analyses of the AX7611 trial run batches showed that the plant conditions were very stable during the 

trial run. No significant batch to batch variations could be detected. Furthermore, the mechanical properties 

such as impact strength and ESCR were within the expected range. In comparison to Basell’s grade 

ACP5331H, the LD6 material shows even a better environmental stress crack performance (ESCR) and better 

flow properties, which are the key parameters for a caps and closure material.  

For the next trial run, it is recommended to adjust the plant settings. The density should be reduced slightly 

to be on midpoint specification. Additionally, the MFI should be increased at least by 0.1 g/10 min to meet 

the target specification. Due to the melt drop during extrusion, the powder MFI2.16 has be at least 

1.9 g/10 min in order to obtain the lower limit of the MFI granule specification. With regard to the organic 

volatile content, it has to be taken care that a level of 0.5 µg/L is not exceeded to achieve the Danone 

requirement.

Technology & Innovation 2/8 
 

 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 

Summary  
 
With the completion of the CUBE installation, for the first time bimodal materials could be produced on small 
scale via a continuous process. With this an extra step in between the batch-wise preparation of recipes on 
benchscale and the commercial scale production was introduced. To probe the capability of the CUBE of 
producing materials that would resemble those produced in the plant, 3 CUBE produced A6060 mimics were 
compared to the properties of A6060 from LD6 and a benchscale A6060 mimic. The analyses clearly indicate 
that it is possible to produce materials on the CUBE that resemble the commercial material in many aspects 
pretty well.  
 
 
 
  



STCG- 
SABIC Technology Center Geleen 
Confidential 

 

 
 

Technology & Innovation 3/8 
 

Contents 
 
 

1. Introduction ..................................................................................................................................................  

2. Experimental description ..............................................................................................................................  

3. Results and Discussion ................................................................................................................................  

4. Conclusions .................................................................................................................................................  

 
 
 
 
  



STCG- 
SABIC Technology Center Geleen 
Confidential 

 

 
 

Technology & Innovation 4/8 
 

1. Introduction 
 
During the first half of 2015 bimodal HDPE was produced in the CUBE. During this period experiments from 
2014 were repeated to demonstrate the stability of the system. A material was targeted which has similar 
values for MFI1.2 for reactor 1, MFI5 for the final product and split, and density as the commercial A6060 grade 
to investigate how well such material would compare to the commercial material.  
This report describes the evaluation of the material properties of these materials and their comparison to a 
similar A6060 mimic produced at the benchscale installation as well as to the A6060 specifications.  
 

2. Experimental Description 
 
Reactor settings 
The reactor settings used to produce BIM33C (one of the materials produced) were as follows: 
Reactor 1: 

Exp.  P  P C2  C2 flow  H2 flow  C2  H2 
H2/C2 

  bar(g)  bar(g)  g/h  mg/hr  mol%  mol% 
BIM033C  11.2  1.34  800  1.35  12.0  53.8  4.48 

     
Reactor 2: 
 

P  T  P C2  C2 flow   H2   C4   C2  H2   C4  
H2/C2  C4/C2 

bar(g) 
oC  bar(g)  g/hr  mg/hr  g/hr  mol% mol% mol%

3.6  80  1.21  770  0  75  33.5  1.30  2.00  0.039  0.060
 
 
Density and MFI 
Density measurements were recorded via method DHPE012 at Intertek, MFI measurements were performed 
at 190 oC, with the respective loads as indicated for 10 minutes. 
 
Strain hardening 
For strain hardening: plaques (100*110*0.3 mm) were pressed according to ISO 1872-2 at 180°C, cooled at 
15°C/min, annealed for 1 hour at 120 ± 2°C and slowly cooled to room temperature 
Tensile bars were punched from the plaques and conditioned at 23°C for 16-96 h.  
 
Notched Charpy 
Samples were pressed according to ISO 1872-2 at 180°C and cooled at 15°C/min, bars were cut and 
conditioned at 23°C for 16-96 h. The time between notching and testing was between 1 to 8 h, for notched 
Charpy -30°C the sample should be stored at least 1 h at the required temperature after notching. 
 
Tensile Creep 
Compression molding of 2 mm plaques creep according to ISO 1872 (180°C, cooling 
rate 15°C/min), Punching out ISO 527- 1Ba test bars and measuring thickness of test bars. Subsequently the 
material was loaded either with 5.4 MPa or 6.3 MPa to study the creep after 60 minutes and time to 50 % 
elongation respectively.

Density and MFI 
The values reported below for CUBE A6060 mimics BIM033, BIM033C and BIM043 (Table 1) were all recorded 
at Intertek, Geleen.i It should be noted that the density values obtained by Intertek in general are 1-1.5 points 
higher than the values obtained by the Gelsenkirchen quality lab due to differences in the procedures applied. 
For comparison, data on the two materials used as benchmark are reported, too.

The density data obtained on the materials from the CUBE were on par with the commercial material taking 
into account a 10 point increase upon addition of carbon black and a 1-1.5 higher values recorded as compared 
to the quality lab of the plant. The MFI21 is also in line with the commercial material, with the MFI5 being on 
the low side for BIM033 and BIM033C, which results in a broader flow rate ratio. This is also reflected in a 
broader molecular weight distribution as obtained from GPC (Table 2).

of 1.0 is lower than what is specified for A6060 (1.1 – 1.3), which is in line with the density for BIM033 being at 
the high-end of the specification for A6060. In the spectrum an unknown signal (singlet) at 7.24 ppm was 
observed, the origine of this presumably aromatic compound is not clear.

material. It is not clear where this originates from.

The benchscale material clearly showed worse improvement and would be closer to PE80 in termes of creep

DMS 
 
DMS data were recorded and are displayed in Figure 2. The DMS data for A6060 were not recorded.  
 

 
Figure 2. DMS data as recorded for the CUBE and benchscale materials.  
 
From Figure 2 it can be concluded that at high shear rates the materials act very similar. At low shear rates the 
CUBE materials display higher viscosity than the 130214 material. This is also confirmed by the phase angle, 
which is close to 63 degrees for the CUBE materials and close to 67 degrees for the benchscale material. The 
130214 material has been demonstrated to have a narrow molecular weight distribution compared to the A6060 
reference sample, which might explain its lower melt elasticity.iv 
 

4. Conclusions 
Materials can be produced in the CUBE that resemble well their commercial counterpart A6060. The BIM043 
being very close in most measured properties, whereas the BIM033 and BIM033C had a (too) broad molecular 
weight distribution and rather low MFI5. The materials produced on CUBE in addition resemble the commercial 
A6060 closer than the 130214 benchscale A6060 mimic.

Executive summary 
During the first half of 2015 bimodal HDPE was produced in the CUBE. During this period experiments from 
2014 were repeated to demonstrate the stability of the system. The belt filter was temporarily replaced with a 
rented decanter. Minimum moisture content achieved was 10%. Next, the maximum run length of a single 
production run was increased to >11 days. Experimental programs were executed investigating the polymer split. 
Also 25 kg of three different steel pipe coating products was produced thereby shortening the time to market. 
Next, A material was produced which has similar values for MFI1.2, MFI5, split, and density as the commercial 
A6060 grade.

Technology & Innovation 3/26 
 

2. Introduction 
2.1. CUBE installation 
The bimodal extension of the CUBE exists from two reactors in series, separated by a flash vessel. Fresh catalyst 
is dosed to the first reactor, and is used to control the ethylene partial pressure in reactor 1 (Visscher, Milosevic, 
STCG-2014-33). In the first reactor a low molecular weight homopolymer, and in the second reactor a higher 
molecular weight ethylene/1-butene copolymer is produced. The design (Frans Visscher, Erik Janssen, Henk 
Stiphout, 2014) and the experimental results obtained in 2014 (Frans Visscher, Erik Janssen, Henk Stiphout, 
2014) have been described elsewhere. 

2.2. Planning and targets 
The CUBE installation shares its DCS with other installations, therefore CUBE is operated continuously in blocks 
of several weeks.  
 

Campaign 1: May 26th 2014 – July 18th 2014. 
Campaign 2:  November 24th 2014 – January 16th 2015. 
Campaign 3:  April 7th 2015 – July 20th 2015. 

 
Several targets were defined prior to the start of the 3rd campaign: 
 

(1) Reproducibility results of campaign 1.  
(2) Produce granules with an MFI, split and density specification similar to A6060. 
(3) Understand melt-drop when producing products. 
(4) Improve solid-liquid separation downstream of the installation. 
(5) Understand split control in the CUBE installation and how to relate this to LD6. 
(6) Vary the 1-butene feed flows to investigate the 1-butene incorporation in the polymer. 

  



SABIC Technology Center Geleen 

STCG-2015-XX 
CONFIDENTIAL 

 

 

 
 

Technology & Innovation 4/26 
 

3. Summary experiments  
SABIC’s proprietary MT8.5 catalyst was used from different batches. All batches were produced in the Kontakt 
Anlage in Gelsenkirchen. One of the reasons to use different catalyst batches is to improve the understanding 
what happens if a slightly different batches and concentration are used. There is a known batch-to-batch 
difference in all samples received from the Kontact Anlage (Geert-Jan Meppelder, 2013). To distinguish between 
the different batches, the following names will be used: MT-trial catalyst (which has a higher catalyst 
concentration), Catalyst batch 1, catalyst batch 2; CUBE catalyst (batch as also used in the 2014 campaign). 
Each batch passed the quality control in Gelsenkirchen. A particle size distribution of a catalyst batch was 
measured at DSM-ACES, yielding a d10 = 3.9 µm, d50 = 6.2 µm, and d90 =12.1 µm. 
 
A full overview of the different experimental runs that were performed is added to the Appendix, Chapter 9. For 
this report several experiments will be discussed in detail, of which settings are given in Table 1 and Table 2 for 
reactor 1 and reactor 2. For each experiment samples were drawn after reaching a fully developed steady state 
situation in both reactors.  
 
BIM028 was produced while the second reactor was operated in “sleeping mode”. For this purpose, the reactor 
2 temperature was lowered to 30oC, which is approximately the temperature of the demi water used for cooling. 
This way the activity of the catalyst is minimized. Cold hexane is fed to the second reactor in order to provide 
though flow. BIM27B is added to show in more detail the effect of the 1-butene addition to BIM029. BIM027D 
shows the effect of adding additional hydrogen to reactor 2 for the product of BIM027B. BIM029, BIM030 and 
BIM031 are together used to study the average split in the polymer produced as a function of ethylene feed flow 
ratio. BIM033 was made such that the MFI, split and density of A6060 where targeted (Table 4). Also BIM036 is 
added because of its relevance for the split measurements. 
 
Table 1. Experimental settings of reactor 1, all at reactor temperature of 85oC, a C2 flow of 800 g/hr, a H2 flow of 
1.35 g/hr.

4. Key learning points 
4.1. H2/C2 ratio vs MFI1.2  
MFI1.2 on the reactor 1 products collected after the flash vessel, as well as density measurements are measured 
upon request. In daily operation this means that this is measured after making a modification in the C4 dosing. 
From the GC-measurements the H2/C2 ratio in reactor 1 is obtained. The relation between the H2/C2 ratio and 
the MFI1.2 is shown in Figure 1. It can be observed that catalyst batch 1 has a higher hydrogen sensitivity: at 
corresponding ratio a higher MFI1.2 is achieved. Based on Figure 1 a correlation is obtained between the MFI1.2 
and H2/C2-ratio measured on products from the CUBE-installation (Figure 2). 
 

 
Figure 1. MFI1.2 as a function of H2/C2 in reactor 1 for different catalyst batches applied. 
 

 
Figure 2. MFI1.2 as a function of the H2/C2 ratio in reactor 1. 

The H2/C2 ratio versus MFI1.2 on different installations is shown in Figure 3. A power law is fitted for the relation 
(Seavey, 2013).

Figure 3. H2/C2 ratio versus the MFI1.2 as measured on the TOPS installation, LD6, and CUBE. Fitted are for 
TOPS: MFI1.2 = 2.59*(H2/C2 

2.77), for CUBE: MFI1.2 = 0.47*(H2/C2

2.91). The 
correlation for TOPS is obtained from the available experimental data.  
 
Figure 3 shows a spread in the MFI measurements at constant H2/C2-ratio for the higher H2/C2 ratios. This  spread 
is most likely due to batch-to-batch variations. When using a single catalyst batch, at constant H2/C2 for several 
hours a more stable MFI is measured. For example for experiment BIM028 (72 hours) an average MFI1.2 was 
measured of 93 ± 6 dg/min, with the notification that the H2/C2 was 4.39 ± 0.04 dg/min. For BIM028 it can be 
seen that the MFI1.2 follows the H2/C2 ratio in the headspace closely (see Appendix 5, chapter 14). The relation 
between the H2/C2 ratio and MFI1.2 is different for the TOPS, and CUBE/LD6. The reason for this difference is 
still unclear.  
 

4.2. The influence of nitrogen  
The Henry coefficients of nitrogen and ethylene in hexane are published in open literature (Poston & McKetta, 
1966) (Katayama & Nitta, 1976) (Zhuze & Zhurba, 1960). The Henry coefficient increases with temperature, and 
thus the solubility of nitrogen and ethylene in hexane decreases. For hydrogen the opposite trend is observed. 
A storage tank for hexane is located outside building 20, and an intermediate storage is located inside building 
20 from where it is continuously dosed by nitrogen overpressure.  
 
If operated at a higher temperature the hexane dosed to reactor 1 will thus contain a lower nitrogen concentration. 
As a result the nitrogen partial pressure pN2 in the reactor is lower at higher temperature. This affects the total 
pressure (pTOT =  pH2 + pC2 + pC6 + pINERTS). This implies that the total pressure in reactor is affected by the 
outside temperature. This can be seen in the appendix 4, chapter 13, where the nitrogen concentration equals 
16.5±1.5 vol% over a timespan of 4 days, with a oscillation frequency of ± 12 hours. The maximum value in the 
headspace is obtained at 1900h.  
 
The partial pressure of ethylene (pC2 = CC2 x PTOT) depends on the total pressure. Given that the nitrogen partial 
pressure equals approximately 2 bar, with a fluctuation of 10%, the total pressure fluctuates with 0.2 bars over 
time. In commercial plant the pC2 (= CC2 x PTOT) is continuously controlled via the catalyst feed (Visscher, 
Milosevic, STCG-2014-33), whereas in CUBE the catalyst feed is only manually adjusted if required to maintain 
a given pC2. If the pC2 would be adjusted automatically, similar oscillations could have a (minor) effect on the 
cat dosing required to reach the desired set point. The nitrogen partial pressure is beneficial for the operation of 
reactor 2. There the total pressure is lower, and the partial pressure of nitrogen has a bigger contribution. This 
helps to increase the pressure difference between the downstream unit and the second reactor.
