4.3. MFI over time 
The MFI5 value of the powder produced is measured every two hours at the installation. This is used to decide 
if a change in the H2/C2-ratio is required to reach a targeted set-point. A graph with the MFI5 (on powder) values 
is shown in Figure 4. For convenience also the hydrogen dosing to reactor 2 [mg/hr] is shown. 

 
Figure 4. MFI5 (powder) over time (red dots). The hydrogen dosing to reactor 2 [mg/hr] is shown (blue). 

 
Density samples are not measured at the installation itself, but are send to Intertek for an accelerated 
measurement (Figure 5). 
 

  
Figure 5. Accelerated density measurement as a function of time (red) and the 1-butene dosing [g/hr] (blue).  

 
When ignoring the MFI change over time (shown in Figure 4), the accelerated density (when dosing 50 g/hr of 
1-butene) gave a density of 953 ± 2 kg/m³.  
 

  



SABIC Technology Center Geleen 

STCG-2015-XX 
CONFIDENTIAL 

 

 

 
 

Technology & Innovation 8/26 
 

4.4. Split control 
4.4.1. Split introduction 
One of the important bimodal HDPE polymer properties is the split of the polymer product. This split, further 
denoted as the polymer split, is defined as the mass of polymer produced in reactor 1 over the total mass of 
polymer produced after reactor 2. This is related to the feed flow split, which is equal to the feed flow of ethylene 
to reactor 1 divided by the total feed flow of ethylene. A higher polymer split implies a larger amount of (lower 
molecular weight) reactor 1 material in the powder. Typically, the polymer split is defined for a given recipe. How 
a certain polymer split can be achieved is documented for various installations, like the ACE/TOPS bench scale 
installations and the LD6. 
 
4.4.2. Split control in TOPS  
In TOPS, the amount of ethylene fed to the reactor is monitored via a mass flow controller. The cumulative 
amount of ethylene fed to the reactor is considered to be polymerized. Split control in TOPS (and ACE) is well-
controlled: due to the absence of a residence time distribution all particles spend an equal time at the given 
polymerization conditions. When measuring the amount produced after the first polymerizations step the slurry 
is filtered. When dosing so a small part of the low molecular weight polymer passes through the filter which 
needs to be taken into account when the polymer split is determined (Tom Schoffelen, 2010). 
 
4.4.3. Split control in LD6 
For LD6 measuring the polymer split is challenging. A first method used was to determine polymer split from the 
heat balances over the reactor system. The energy input via the suspension pumps, agitators, heat of the various 
streams, reactor jacket, and outer coolers were taken into account, together with the heat produced by the 
reaction. This method would depend on the accuracy of temperature measurements. A second method was to 
calculate the amount of unconverted ethylene that remains dissolved in the hexane that leaves the reactors. 
Here, the amount of ethylene flashed of in the flash vessel was not taken into account according to the current 
as-built situation (no residual conversion in the post reactor due to the sleeping mode thereof). The split 
calculations, based heat balance as well as the solubility data, gave the impression that based on a feed flow 
split of 51, an polymer split is obtained varying between 52-53. The reactor temperature, reactor pressure (cat 
yield) and phase ratio were expected to play an important role (Arjen Giesbers, Linda Havermans, 2012). A 
detailed in investigation is currently ongoing to study split by analyzing the polymer product itself. 
 
4.4.4. Split measurements in CUBE 
In CUBE the polymer split was studied. For this the production rate was measured in experiments were reactor 
1 was in operation and reactor 2 was operated in sleeping mode. Afterwards the production rate was measured 
with both reactors in operation. Three methods were used to measure the powder production rate.  
 

1. Powder was collected over a period of precisely 2 hours at the powder discharge point in the decanter. 
Prior to the collection the powder discharge point was cleaned. Powder was dried in the oven to remove 
hexane. 

2. Slurry was collected for 1 hour by bypassing the decanter. The slurry was filtrated over the TOPS filter 
after which the weight of the powder was measured, and the weight gain of the tank (due to deposits) 
was measured. 

3. The wet powder production is measured by the technician every 2 hours, after which the moisture 
content is measured (Paragraph 5.2). This production is listed over multiple hours. This yields the 
average hourly production rate.  

 
4.4.5. Measured polymer splits 
Method 1 yields the production rate based on multiple two hour averaged measurements. For method 2 a lower 
number of measurements is obtained, and the method selected was more labor intensive. For method 3 the 
value shown is calculated as the average over multiple hours. The measured production rates of polymer are 
shown in the Appendix 3, Table 12. Based on those measured rates, the polymer split was calculated (Table 3). 
 



SABIC Technology Center Geleen 

STCG-2015-XX 
CONFIDENTIAL 

 

 

 
 

Technology & Innovation 9/26 
 

Table 3. Split measured via three techniques. Method 1: collection of wet powder over 2 hrs, Method 2: Collect 
slurry for 1 hour and filter it, method 3: collected powder of 24 hrs. The calculated value is shown with 1 decimal. 
Statistical analysis showed that it is advised to round the calculated polymer split to the closest integer1.  
 

  Split Split split split 

Experiment Feed flow method 1 method 2 method 3 

BIM029 50.0 49.4 50.3 49.6 

BIM030 57.1 56.5 58.2 57.1 

BIM031 44.4 43.6 45.6 44.7 

BIM032 51.0 49.6 51.2 50.5 
 
In Table 3 the calculated polymer split is shown with 1 decimal. Statistical analysis showed that it is advised to 
round the calculated polymer split to the closest integer. When looking at Table 3, it cannot be concluded that 
for the measurement on CUBE powder the polymer split is 1 point higher than the feed flow split (at the H2/C2, 
pC2, and reactor temperatures applied). One way of making this visible is by plotting the difference between the 
polymer split and the feed flow split (Figure 6).  

 
Figure 6. Split comparison for the three methods that were indicated in Table 3. 

 
A first observation would be that method 1 predicts that the polymer split is below the feed flow split, whereas 
method 2 predicts that the polymer split is above than the feed flow split. Method 3 does not show structurally 
that the polymer split is higher or lower than the feed flow split. A second observation would be that method 1 
and method 2 both show a larger difference between the polymer split and the feed flow split. Method 3 gives a 
smaller difference. It should be remembered that method 3 yields a polymer split which is averaged out over a 
period ranging between 17 and 24 hours. Method 1 and 2 only yield the value that is determined over one or two 
hours. Keeping in mind that method 2 is extremely labor intensive, it is proposed to use method 3 in the future 
when performing a split experiment. Also notice that the 1-butene flow is not included in split calculations so-far. 
For A6060, assuming a 1.2% 1-butene incorporation corresponds to 15 gram compared to the 1.5 kg being 
produced. This 15 grams is entirely produced in reactor 2. For an experiment with feed flow split 50, this 
translates into half a point polymer split difference. When making a product with more 1-butene (like for example 
the steel pipe coating products) it could be wise to take this into account, especially if the point of interest is the 
ethylene-split.  

                                                
1 Stephen Clarke, from the statistics group in STC-Houston/Pittsfield is acknowledged for his support. 



SABIC Technology Center Geleen 

STCG-2015-XX 
CONFIDENTIAL 

 

 

 
 

Technology & Innovation 10/26 
 

For a follow-up experiment it would be relevant to see if the relation between measured split and expected split 
based on the C2-feed flow holds at different H2/C2 in reactor 1, at different pC2 in reactor 1. Also an experiment 
could be executed in which reactor 2 is kept at the standard reactor 2 polymerization temperature, without feeding 
any ethylene. For this experiment an estimation could be obtained how much ethylene would be converted in 
this reactor. Currently the CUBE is being extended with a third reactor. Therefore there will be three feed lines 
to GC. This would allow to quantify how much ethylene is flashed of between reactor 1 and 2, which could help 
in closing the mass balance over the system. 
  

4.5. Melt drop from powder to granulate 
For LD6 material it is known that a so-called melt drop is present, which is a difference in the MFI measured on 
the powder compared to the granules. This effect is hardly seen on material produced on the bench scale 
installations TOPS and ACE. An exact reason for this is not known but it might be an effect of residence time 
distribution that is present in a continuous process (Hans Martens, 2011). 
 
In the 2014 campaign it was observed that also for material produced in the CUBE installation had a melt drop. 
For the 2015 campaign one of the goals was to produce A6060 in granule specification with respect to MFI1.2, 
split, density and MFI5. To compensate for the melt drop a higher MFI5 of the powder was targeted. 
 
To accurately determine the MFI5 of the powder, the same procedure of the LD6 was implemented (Miran 
Milosevic; Francisco Perez Valencia, 2015). In detail: 

 Wet powder collected after the decanter is dried in an oven. 

 The dried powder is stabilized. 

 The powder is melted and mixed in the MFI machine using the MFI21.6 method. 

 The resulting strand is cut in small pieces and analyzed using the MFI5 method. 

 The obtained value is the powder MFI5, also PI5 called. 
 
This PI5 value is the value used to stir the CUBE and if necessary adjust the reactor 2 settings to reach the 
required powder specifications. The powder material is then being stabilized and granulated on the so-called 
CBSO extruder. From the granules also the MFI5 is measured, this value is also called the GI5. 
 

4.6. Producing the A6060 mimic 
A6060 grade was produced targeting granules specifications with respect to MFI5, split and density properties. 
The targeted properties are listed in Table 4. 
 
Table 4. Specification of A6060 targeted in BIM033. 
 

Property Value 
MFI1.2 

POWDER 105 ± 15 dg/min 

MFI5 GRANULATE  0.27 ± 0.03 dg/min 
Density 948 ± 2 kg/m³ 
Split  51 

 
To reach the targeted product split of 51, the ethylene dosing to reactor 2 was set to 770 g/hr. The first production 
campaign was held under code BIM033. Several days later a second run was made in which the set points 
learned from BIM033 were applied, results there of are listed under BIM043. Measurements of MFI, bulk density, 
density and catyield on these powders are summarized in Table 5. The settings used to obtain these data are 
shown in Table 6 for reactor 1, and Table 7 for reactor 2. Analyses were performed as was done in the previous 
report (Frans Visscher, Erik Janssen, Henk Stiphout, 2014). A more detailed analysis regarding strain hardening, 
tensile creep, notched charpy will be made in a separate report (Mark Boerakker; Frans Visscher, STCG-2015-
221).

The pC2 difference in reactor 1 for the experiments is ~5%. The pC2 in reactor 2 is higher for BIM043 compared 
to BIM033. The reason for this is not known: A logical explanation would be if there is a lower catalyst activity in 
reactor 2. This could be explained by an in-flow of oxygen after the first reactor. This does not seem to stroke 
with the catalyst yields shown in Table 5. 
 

4.7. Steel pipe coating production  
Four different medium density products were produced on CUBE to see if SABIC’s bimodal HDPE based on the 
MT catalyst would be suited for filling in a marked need. Products were made within 6 weeks time. For this trial 
for the first time 1-butene was dosed to the first reactor. The materials have been analysed within T&I, of which 
a separate report will be published. Also the material has been send for further analysis with the designated 
customer. In the coming CUBE campaign two products will be targeted based on BIM036. Based on those results 
a trial is being planned in LD6.

4.8. Summary reasons for shut down.  
4.8.1. Oxygen sensor (41% of failures) 
Several times during the productions the installation was forced to stop. The reason most frequently encountered 
was an alarm that went off related to the oxygen sensor after the decanter. This alarm is triggered due to hexane 
condensation in the sensor, which disturbs the flow to the test sample and the oxygen measurement. The SIL-
classification (Safety Integrity Level) of the tripping oxygen sensor was reconsidered. As of this campaign the 
technician on duty will evaluate the cooling flow to the nitrogen stream. As an additional safety measure it is 
under debate to install a nitrogen mass flow meter before the decanter which is an additional tool to monitor if 
the decanter is supplied with nitrogen properly. 



SABIC Technology Center Geleen 

STCG-2015-XX 
CONFIDENTIAL 

 

 

 
 

Technology & Innovation 12/26 
 

4.8.2. Reactor outlet plugging (28% of failures) 
Plugging is only scarcely observed in Reactor 1. The few times that this was observed this was due to a re-start 
of the system without proper cleaning prior to the start-up. There are two mitigations that have been initiated: 
first of all the pipe diameter from reactor 2 to the decanter will be increased. As such even when there is material 
gradually fouling the reactor there will be through low for a longer period.  
 
In order to keep sufficient flow through the pipe a constant flushing with hexane (at room temperature) between 
reactor 2 and the decanter was applied. This also has a possible disadvantage: the pipe is cooled which might 
result in more wax deposition on the inside. Therefore, during the last runs of the campaign the constant flushing 
was stopped, and only infrequent (‘pulse wise’) flushing was applied once per hour for 5 minutes. This approach 
was trialed only for a shorter period of time but seemed promising in reducing the amount of fouling the tube.   
 
4.8.3. Decanter powder discharge (21% of failures) 
The plugging of the powder discharge point of the decanter was observed only in the first weeks of the campaign. 
Powder was removed with a moisture content of 10-15%. Condensation at the top of the powder discharge point 
caused plugging on the discharge and hexane entrainment onto the dried powder after separation. Several 
solutions were attempted (heating and cooling specific locations of the decanter, different powder discharge 
geometry, applying a nitrogen purge). In the end reducing the rotational speed of the decanter screw and worm 
were the key. By lowering the rotational speed of the decanter less hexane vapors were forced to the dry powder 
outlet, resulting in less condensation (see paragraph 5.3). 
 
4.8.4. Flash vessel pump tubing (10% of failures) 
After using the peristaltic pumps for several days (for the recycle over the flash vessel, and for removing hexane 
after the decanter) the tubing inside the pump was damaged. This was especially the case for the pump used to 
recycle slurry over the flash vessel. Different tubing types were applied, also tubing was kept in stock to replace 
this as soon as required. To increase run duration a larger peristaltic pump was ordered. This pump has a larger 
diameter. At a lower rotational speed (and thus a lower friction to the tubing wall) it is able to recycle an equal 
amount of slurry. This pump was implemented two weeks before the end of the campaign and showed no tubing 
failure. 

 
4.9. Remaining topics 
From the previous campaigns it was known that the flow rate to the gas chromatograph needs to be calibrated 
on a regular basis. Calibrations were executed once a month during the campaign, all indicating that there was 
no change in the flow rate to GC.  
 
For the CUBE-ACP extension a third reactor is added to the installation. This will be mounted on the top floor of 
the building where currently also the catalyst dosing facility is located. A test run was made in which the catalyst 
suspension was dosed 1.5 m upwards from the catalyst-dosing pump before entering the reactor. No process 
disturbance was observed after 1,5 week of using this modification. As a result the catalyst dosing system will 
not be relocated to a higher position in the rack in which the installation is present. 
 
Currently within the capability project on Hostalen/MT modeling, a Matlab® based model for the polymerization 
of bimodal HDPE is being developed. The model accounts for kinetics, transport phenomena and arrangement 
of the reactors and predicts polymer properties (MN, MW, C4-content, split), particle size and the effect of the 
residence time distribution of the polymer particles inside the reactor. For this project powders after reactor 1 
and after reactor 2 were collected and sieved according to particle size. GPC and NMR on these samples were 
measured and will be used to further validate the developed code, and as such understand the translatability of 
results from the TOPS to CUBE installation to LD6 (reporting in progress). The GPC and NMR data will also be 
required for the further developed of the Aspen® based Hostalen plant model.  



SABIC Technology Center Geleen 

STCG-2015-XX 
CONFIDENTIAL 

 

 

 
 

Technology & Innovation 13/26 
 

5. Decanter  
5.1. introduction 
To evaluate if the powder-diluent separation could be improved by switching to a different separation mechanism, 
a decanter was rented from Siebtechnik. The model rented was a SBD 210K. This is a short-bowl decanter 
centrifuge which can separate solids if sedimentation rate in the carrier liquid is sufficiently high. Siebtechnik also 
delivered the decanter used in commercial assets, like LD6 (Frans Visscher, Geert-Jan Meppelder, 2014). 
 
The decanter is operate on the contraflow principle. This means that the suspension to be separated is fed 
approximately in the center of the drum (right in Figure 7), the sedimented solid matter is conveyed towards the 
smaller diameter by the screw rotating at a speed differential in relation to the drum, whilst the clarified liquid 
overflows over an adjustable weir at the opposite end of the drum. The decanter is designed to separate very 
fine solids from liquids of lighter density. The solids sediment from the liquid due to the centrifugal (g) forces on 
the inside of the rotating bowl (Siebtechnik, Accessed: August 2015) (Alan Records, 2001). 
 

 
Figure 7. Schematic representation of the SBD 210K decanter (Siebtechnik, Accessed: August 2015). 
 
The sedimentation rate depends on the particle size, the particle shape, the density difference between solid 
and liquid, and the viscosity of the latter. In many cases, significant improvement is possible by conditioning, for 
example heating or addition of flocculants. Also important is the geometrical design and establishment of 
operating parameters. Clarification of the liquid is effected in the case of solid bowl centrifuges primarily in the 
cylindrical section (yellow in Figure 7)., dewatering of the solid matter taking place by means of filtration or 
compression of the solid cake in the conical section of the drum (red in Figure 7). The height of the liquid level 
in the drum and thus the ratio of clarifying to drying section of the drum can be varied. This permits matching to 
the separation application involved.  
 

5.2. Moisture content and particle size 
The moisture content in the wet cake coming from the decanter is calculated by sampling 100 gram of wet cake 
at the powder discharge point of the decanter. This is dried on a heating plate for 1 hour. The weight loss after 
drying is recorded. This weight loss is taken as the moisture content. In LD6 the moisture content is calculated 
from the hexane recovered in the T2201 scrubber tower, and from the total amount of ethylene fed to the 
reactors. This means one is measured in KPB content per dry powder whereas the other is measured in KPB 
content per wet powder. 

moisture (CUBE) =  
weight loss of KPB [g]

initial weight of wet powder [g]
x 100%

Technology & Innovation 14/26 
 

The moisture content is measured by technicians every 2 hours. Values between 5 and 25% are observed, with 
an average of 14%. During the production of UHMWPE the lowers moisture content obtained was 2-3%, whereas 
the average was 5-10 %. For the production of bimodal HDPE the average moisture content obtained in the belt 
filer was 15%. It needs to be remembered that a bimodal production run with the belt dryer never exceeded 25 
hours, whereas with the decanter run lengths are obtained exceeding 10 days (10 days and 22 hours). The 
average moisture content per day is shown in Figure 8.   

 
Figure 8. Moisture content after the decanter. The average moisture content is shown for each day. Also the 
standard deviation is calculated for each day, and is represented by the error-bars. 
 
Some remarks on Figure 8:  

 On April 24th an additional nitrogen flow was added to the powder side of the decanter resulting in a 
decrease of moisture content.  

 From 11th-14th May only the first reactor was operated for polymerization (see BIM028, chapter 3). The 
moisture content increased over time with values up to 28%.  

 From May 15th, ethylene was fed to the second reactor. After 10 hours it was observed that the moisture 
content reduced to 15 wt%. An exact reason is unknown: it might be related to the particle size or that 
the reactor 1 material is more difficult to separate from hexane. To further clarify this the porosity of 
powder from reactor 1 and the final product will be compared.  

 In July different steel pipe coating recipes were developed (see chapter 4.7) for which an end density of 
945 kg/m3 was required in most cases. When looking at the moisture content it can be observed that in 
some cases the moisture content was high, especially in the hours before fouling of the second reactor 
caused a shut down. 

 

 
Figure 9. The particle size upon entering the decanter (red) and upon leaving the decanter (blue). A slight 
reduction is observed in the amount of bigger polymer particles, which could be due to attrition.

5.3. Proposed changes 
Several effect were studied to reduce the moisture content in the wet cake after the decanter and to increase 
the maximum run time length. At the powder discharge point condensation of hexane was observed. This caused 
plugging, which lead to several shut-downs. Both the slurry temperature at the decanter entrance (30oC – 80oC) 
and the nitrogen flow (500 ndm3/hr – 2000 ndm³/hr) over the decanter were optimized. Also an attempt was 
made to take the nitrogen from the decanter via the forced convection system instead of the venting system.  
 
During the CBSO campaign condensation at the powder discharge points of the decanter was studied via tests 
in absence of polymerization. These showed that the rotational speeds in the decanter should be reduced to 
reduce the convectional air stream caused by the rotation. The rotation was varied in steps between 500 RPM 
to 2000 RPM. The differential rotation speed was varied between 10 and 20 RPM.  A final test was made by 
filling the reactor with 2.5 kg powder, suspended in hexane. The resulting slurry was fed to the decanter, which 
was operated at 1500 RPM (maximum rotation without condensation). This resulted in powder with a moisture 
content of 8 wt% and a stop of the condensation that was visible to the eye. 
 
A continuous stream of fresh KPB fed to the decanter after R2 did not reduce plugging. Increasing the liquid feed 
rate to the decanter did not cause an observable change in the residual moisture content in the commercial 
installations (Frans Visscher, Miran Milosevic, Erik Janssen, Maryam Tamaddoni, 2015). If the line would be 
flushed with KPB at elevated temperatures plugging frequency should be less. 
 

5.4. Remaining options to improve the decanter performance. 
Based on the experimental outcome so-far (being specifically the increased run-time of the installation), it is 
proposed to acquire a decanter for a permanent implementation in this installation. There are several leads open 
to improve the decanter performance which can only be implemented in a tailor made machine: 

- Shape of the tube that feeds the slurry to the decanter  
- Increasing the diameter of tube that feeds slurry to the decanter 
- The gas-flow over the liquid pool to the liquid discharge side could be optimized if the machine would be 

equipped with a so-called “duikschijf” (a dip plate blocking-in the gas volume). 
- The decanter used in this campaign is designed for a throughput of maximum 250 kg/hr of dry powder. 

A smaller decanter would allow for a lower residual moisture content. 
 

 
 

  



SABIC Technology Center Geleen 

STCG-2015-XX 
CONFIDENTIAL 

 

 

 
 

Technology & Innovation 16/26 
 

6. Outlook for next campaign 
The hydrogen removal in the flash vessel has not been studied in detail yet. Specifically it could be studied for a 
given set of reactor 1 conditions how the reactor 2 headspace is affected by superimposing an increased 
recirculation flow over the flash vessel, the pressure in the flash vessel set by the control valve, and the level in 
the flash vessel (to see if gas bubbles are fully disintegrated). 
 
A point which is receiving increased attention is the formation of byproducts, being more specifically low 
molecular weight polymer. The presence of this material in the powder (hexane extractables) and in the liquid 
(wax determination at 40oC) should be obtained on a structured bases. A long term topic to investigate would be 
to quantify the effect of an external slurry recycle on the steady state concentrations of such material in the slurry.  
 
The experiments executed for this study to evaluate the split could be extended with measurement at a different 
ethylene partial pressure in the first reactor, different residence times in the reactor, and with experiments at 
different H2/C2 ratios. A split experiment should be executed in which reactor 2 is operated at the normal 
polymerization temperature but without feeding fresh components to the system.  
 
The installation of the decanter was the key for obtaining results in this campaign. The moisture removal should 
further be optimized like was mentioned in chapter 5.4. Also the presence of polymer fines in the machine should 
further be quantified to see how this related to the commercial machines. A bypass around the decanter is 
proposed. Such a bypass could be a filter, and would allow operators to perform short maintenance tasks for the 
decanter, without causing the need to induce a process disturbance in the reactor section of the installation.  
 

  



SABIC Technology Center Geleen 

STCG-2015-XX 
CONFIDENTIAL 

 

 

 
 

Technology & Innovation 17/26 
 

7. Conclusions of the campaign 
 
Experiments from 2014 were repeated, which proved the stability of experimental results obtained in the CUBE 
installation. Building on these previous experiments, granules were produced with an MFI, split and density 
specification similar to the commercial A6060 product. These experiments also confirmed that the melt drop 
observed so-far (the MFI difference between powder and granules) is in the same order of magnitude as for the 
commercial scale.  
 
The solid-liquid separation downstream of the installation was improved: the maximum run length of a single 
production run was ~11 days which is about 10 times higher than in 2014. To achieve this the belt filter was 
replaced with a rented decanter. Minimum moisture content achieved was 10%. It is believed that this can further 
be reduced by using a tailor made machine.  
 
Experimental programs were executed investigating the polymer split. There was no clear difference observed 
in the polymer split (produced in CUBE) and the feed flow split. This should be taken into account when 
developing recipes for new product introductions in CUBE.  
 
Next, four different steel pipe coating grades (25 kg each) was produced. These products were send for testing 
at a potential customer. For this product for the first time 1-butene was dosed to the first reactor.  

 
 
  



SABIC Technology Center Geleen
